@node Description "Description and Features"

QuickFile is a flexible, random access flat file database program. It was originally written by Alan Wigginton. Alan discontinued development in 1996, and Roland Florac asked for and recieved permission from Alan to recommence development in 1999.

Fundamentally, the new QuickFile is the same program. However, a number of significant enhancements have been made. QuickFile is now localized; it now uses 'gtlayout.library' (by Olaf 'Olsen' Barthel; available from Aminet in dev/gui) for requesters, though not for the main database window; there are dozens of new macro functions available, and others have been much improved; the function keys and other user-definable key combinations, as well as the menus, may now be programmed to launch macros; and other miscellaneous improvments and bug fixes. See the program @{"history" link History} for details.

@{b}Note@{ub} that several of the keyboard shortcuts for major menu items have changed in version 3.27:

                @{u}   Shortcut   @{uu}
  @{u}Menu Item   @{uu}  @{u}v3.25@{uu}   @{u}v3.27@{uu}
  About           ?     <none> 
  ARexx Script    X       ,
  Iconify         Y       I
  Indexes         I       X
  Query           Q       Y
  

QuickFile uses indexes for fast access to records. Databases can be larger than available RAM, but as much of the file as possible (configurable by the user) can be kept in RAM to reduce disk usage. Features include:

  * Multiple @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} with unique or non-unique keys
  * 8 @{"field" link Fields} types include CHARACTER, DATE, TIME, INTEGER, FLOATING, CYCLE,
    IMAGE and EXTERNAL
  * Character and numerical fields can also be calculated from the other
    fields
  * Support for @{"display of IFF ILBM images" link Images} directly in the database window
    via IMAGE fields and iffparse.library.
  * Up to 250 characters per field and 250 fields per record.
  * Up to 16777215 records per database
  * Multiple FORM and LIST @{"views" link AboutViews} of the same database possible, each with
    a different layout of available fields.
  * Custom @{"sort" link AboutIndexes} by any number of fields, each in ascending or descending
    order
  * Advanced record @{"queries" link Queries}, with operators including LIKE, EQUAL,
    BETWEEN, SOUNDS LIKE, NOT LIKE and NOT EQUAL
  * Manual @{"selection and deselection" link Queries} of records
  * Fields can be added, modified or deleted at any time
  * Flexible @{"import and export" link ImportExport}
  * Extensive @{"keyboard" link Keys} shortcuts available for scrolling through records,
    alternating between string gadgets, etc.
  * Flexible @{"printing" link Printing}, including multi-column labels, to the printer, a
    file, or to the QuickFile window
  * Multi-level @{"report groups" link Reports}, including totals, averages and counts
  * Any number of databases open, each in its own re-sizable intuition
    window and ARexx port
  * AppIcon on Workbench screen, and each open window is also an AppWindow
  * Online context-sensitive help
  * Extensive @{"macro" link Macros} support, featuring over 100 macro functions, with and
    without ARexx.
  * Menu, function keys and other key combinations may be configured to
    launch macros
  * Easy to use Intuition interface with font sensitivity

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

  Workbench/Kickstart 3.0 or higher
  68020 CPU or higher
  1 MB or more RAM recommended

@{b}Required Libraries@{ub}

  asl.library                For file requesters.
  mathieeedoubbas.library
  mathieeedoubtrans.library
  gtlayout.library           For requesters other than file requesters.
                             By Olaf 'Olsen' Barthel, available from Aminet
                             in dev/gui.

@{b}Optional libraries@{ub}

  iffparse.library           To display IMAGE fields.
  rexxsyslib.library         To use ARexx macros.
  amigaguide.library         To use online help.


QuickFile will work with XFH-handler (an automated file compression program) but XFH-handler requires that the decompressed file fit completely in RAM. To work with QuickFile such programs must support update of an existing file.

QuickFile is written using SAS/C.
@endnode
@node Fields "About Fields"

QuickFile allows up to 250 fields to be defined for any database, and fields may be up to 250 characters in length, however, not all fields may use the maximum length as the maximum record length is 32767.

QuickFile features eight field @{"types" link Types}, including CHARACTER, DATE, TIME, INTEGER, FLOATING, CYCLE, IMAGE and EXTERNAL. In addition, fields may be set to be mandatory and/or right justified, and numerical and character fields may be automatically @{"calculated" link Calc} from data in other fields.

Fields are defined via the @{"FIELDS" link FieldDef} panel on the left side of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester.
@endnode
@node AboutIndexes "About Indexes and Custom Sorting"

QuickFile uses indexes to sequence the records and to provide rapid access by key field value. Each database must have at least one index, but can have any number more. Indexes are automatically maintained as records are @{"inserted" link InsertModify}, @{"modified" link InsertModify} and @{"deleted" link Delete}.

Indexes are defined via the @{"INDEXES" link IndexDef} panel on the right side of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, and are based on one or more fields, each one in ascending or descending order.

If an index is set to be unique, QuickFile will reject the creation of records with duplicate index field values.

Each defined index is saved to a separate file on disk, and all available index files are loaded automatically when a database is opened.

The current index name is displayed in the title bar of the database window. If other indexes are available, they can be chosen from by selecting @{"INDEXES" link Indexes} from the ORDER menu.

In addition to using any previously defined indexes for a database, records can be custom @{"sorted" link Sort index} according to any criteria at any time, which creates a temporary index named SORTED that is not saved to disk.

Indexing does have some overheads in RAM usage. Each index requires a contiguous area of RAM that is 4*(<number of records> + 200) bytes in size. Custom sorting requires space in RAM for all sort fields, plus 8 bytes per record in one contiguous area.
@endnode
@node AboutViews "About Views"

Using views, a single QuickFile database can be displayed and @{"printed" link Printing} in many different ways. Views are typically used to print @{"labels" link Labels} and @{"reports" link Reports}, @{"export" link Export} or @{"import" link Import} selected @{"fields" link Fields}, or print lists containing only selected fields.

Each view is either a @{"FORM" link Form} or @{"LIST" link List} view by default, but may also be @{"toggled" link FormList} between the two types at any time during sessions. Each view may also have its own field order, titles, positions and lengths (which do not affect the actual field definitions or existing record data), window size and position, and print configuration. Each may display all or only a subset of available database fields, selected by the user. The @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester is used to set the view type and determine which fields are displayed and how for the purpose of a view.

Some aspects of view layouts can only be modifed with the @{"mouse" link MouseView}, including window size and position, and having several fields on the same line in FORM views.

Once a view is satisfactory, it may be @{"saved" link Save As } for future use. Each saved view is stored as a separate file on disk.

@{b}Note@{ub} that views are only saved if the user explicitly saves them, otherwise any changes are lost when the database window is closed.

When a database is opened, QuickFile looks for a view file named "<database>.View" in the same directory. If this is not found, a default FORM view, displaying all defined fields (one per line) is used. To have a desired view used automatically, it should be saved with this name in the same directory as the database. Any existing views other than the default must be loaded from disk, by selecting @{"LOAD" link Load  } from the VIEW menu, to be made available after a database is opened. Any previously loaded view may be chosen for use by selecting @{"VIEWS" link Views} from the VIEW menu. Alternatively, a STARTUP @{"MACRO" link Macros} may be used to load several views and select the desired one for use.

If simplicity is desired and the default layout is satisfactory, a view need not be defined at all.
@endnode
@node Queries "About Queries"

Queries allow the user to search all records for designated fields which match certain values or criteria. The fields and criteria to be searched for can be mixed and matched within the query in almost unlimited ways. Custom @{"sorting" link Sort index} sequences can be specified for the records returned, which are placed in a temporary @{"index" link AboutIndexes} named @{"SELECTED" link Selected} that is not saved to disk. A query can also be performed on only those records matched by a previous query.

The selection status of individual records can also be @{"toggled" link Toggle Record} manually.

Queries are specified and performed via the @{"Query" link Query} requester, and query specifications can be saved to disk for future use.
@endnode
@node Printing "About Printing"

QuickFile can print individual records, or all records in the current @{"index." link AboutIndexes} The format of what is printed is controlled by the current @{"view" link AboutViews} and by the settings defined in the @{"PRINT" link Print} requester. This requester allows the user to set a print title, select the output device (database window, file, or PRT:), set margins and temporarily override Workbench printer preference settings (only applicable if printing to PRT:). Additionally, a panel for configuration of @{"label" link Labels} printing is available for @{"FORM" link Form} views, and a panel for defining @{"REPORT GROUPS" link Reports} and summaries is available for @{"LIST" link List} views.

Print settings, including label configuration and REPORT GROUP definitions, are saved and loaded with each view. If several methods and formats of printing a particular database are desired, one need only define and save several different views with the appropriate configurations set for each one.
@endnode
@node Reports "About Report Groups"

REPORT GROUPS give the user more precise control over how all records in an @{"index" link AboutIndexes} are @{"printed" link Printing}. They are available only when the current @{"view" link AboutViews} type is @{"LIST" link List}. GROUP @{"FIELDS" link Fields} are printed only when their values change in the index. SUMMARY FIELDS may be summarized by count, total or average. Optionally, the user may specify that only summaries are to be printed.

Groups are defined via the @{"GROUPS" link Groups} panel on the right side of the @{"PRINT" link Print} requester.
@endnode
@node Images "About Image Display"

By using @{"IMAGE" link Image} fields, standard Amiga IFF ILBM images can be displayed in the database window, but only in @{"FORM" link Form} views. Also, no scaling or palette remapping is performed, and images are clipped to fit inside the field box established for the view. The display of images can be @{"toggled" link ImageToggle} on and off.

Images of@{b} any@{ub} format(s) can be displayed using an @{"EXTERNAL" link External} field with an appropriate picture viewer, also only in FORM views.
@endnode
@node ImportExport "About Import and Export"

QuickFile can @{"import" link Import} data from text files, and @{"export" link Export} data to text files, as well as to several Amiga word processor file formats. With both import and export, the user can choose from a variety of combinations of field start, end and separator, and record separator characters.
@endnode
@node Keys "About Keyboard Control"

The following abbreviations apply for the corresponding keys:

  BS      Backspace
  DEL     Delete
  LEFT    Left Arrow
  RIGHT   Right Arrow
  UP      Up Arrow
  DOWN    Down Arrow
  CTRL    Control
  RAMIGA  Right Amiga

@{b}General@{ub}

In the database window and requesters, keyboard shortcuts for most gadgets are identified by an underlined character, which work as long as no string gadget is already active. For requester cycle gadgets, pressing the key cycles forward, pressing the SHIFTed key cycles backward.

The following key may be used in record VIEW and INSERT/EDIT modes, and in QuickFile requesters, if no string gadget is active:

  HELP    Displays context-sensitive help text using AmigaGuide or MultiView
          if available. QuickFile can continue to be used while the help
          window is open.

The following key may be used in record VIEW mode:

  RETURN  Enter EDIT mode for current record.@{b} Note@{ub} that in @{"LIST" link List} views, a
          record must have already been selected with the mouse prior to
          pressing RETURN for this to work.

The following keys may be used in record INSERT/EDIT mode, and in requesters, if no string gadget is active:

  RETURN  Same as OK button
  ESC     Same as CANCEL button
  TAB     Activates first string gadget

The following key may be used in record INSERT mode if no string gadget is active:

  SHIFT-RETURN  Same as selecting OK button to insert the record, then
                selecting COPY button to copy values from the current record
                to the next record to be inserted.

The following key may be used in record INSERT/EDIT mode with a string gadget active:

  SHIFT-ESC     De-activate gadget, ignoring errors.

@{b}Record/Requester Navigation@{ub}

The following keys may be used in record VIEW mode, and requester lists, if no string gadget is active:

  UP          Previous item or record
  DOWN        Next item or record
  SHIFT-UP    Previous page of items/records (LIST views, lists);
              Previous 10th record (FORM views)
  SHIFT-DOWN  Next page (LIST/lists) or next 10th record (FORM)
  ALT-UP      Top of list (LIST/lists) or first record (FORM)
  ALT-DOWN    Bottom of list (LIST/lists) or last record (FORM)

@{b}String Editing/Navigation@{ub}

The following keys may be used in string gadgets:

  @{u}Key        @{uu}  @{u}Alternate@{uu}  @{u}Function                                         @{uu}
  SHIFT-TAB       UP      Previous string gadget
  TAB            DOWN     Next string gadget

  RAMIGA-X      CTRL-X    Erase all text in the gadget
  RAMIGA-Q                Restore previous text
  SHIFT-LEFT    CTRL-A    Move to beginning of string
  SHIFT-RIGHT   CTRL-Z    Move to end of string
  SHIFT-DEL     CTRL-K    Erase all characters from cursor to end of gadget
  SHIFT-BS      CTRL-U    Erase all characters to the left of the cursor

  RETURN                  De-activate gadget and accept value, if valid
@endnode
@node Macros "About Macros"

@{"Macros" link MacroRef} allow the user to automate repetetive tasks. For instance, a user could easily create a macro which performs a query on all records in a database, then sets a certain field in all matching records returned by the query to a designated value, then generates a screen report. Macros can be significantly more sophisticated, however.

QuickFile allows the running of macros by several means. The @{"AREXX MACRO" link ARexx Script} requester is used to run ARexx file and inline macros. File macros and individual QuickFile functions may be run from either the @{"DIRECT MACRO" link Direct Macro} requester, or from @{"function" link Function Keys} keys, which may be configured by the user. A file macro stored in the same directory as a database with the same name as the database definition file, plus the extension ".startup" is run automatically when the database is loaded into QuickFile. A typical use of a startup macro might be to @{"load" link Load  } several @{"view" link AboutViews} files.

QuickFile provides over 100 macro @{"functions" link Functions}.
@endnode
@node QuickStart "Getting Started"

@{b}WARNING:@{ub} QuickFile is a random access database program that buffers records in memory. Failure to exit the program properly after records are updated or inserted will result in data loss.

@{b}ALWAYS@{ub} exit the program before rebooting or powering off the Amiga.

@{b}DO@{ub} backup databases regularly, including all associated files -- definition, data, indexes, views, startup macros, etc.

@{b}Installation@{ub}

To install QuickFile to a harddrive or floppy disk, use the provided installation script, or simply copy the QuickFile directory to the directory of choice. To have the online AmigaGuide help system available, be certain to copy the QuickFile guide file to the same directory.

@{b}Starting from Workbench@{ub}

QuickFile can be started from Workbench using the QuickFile icon or a project icon for a database. If started from a project icon, the file is opened and the first record is displayed. If started from the program icon, an empty window is opened, and the @{"menu" link Menus} or a @{"macro" link Macros} must be used to @{"load" link Load } an existing database, or the menu to @{"define" link New} a new one.

@{b}Starting from the Shell@{ub}

To start QuickFile from the Shell, the current directory should first be set to QuickFile's home directory, as various configuration files for QuickFile are searched for in the current directory and sub-directories of the current directory. The program name may then optionally be followed by one or more path(s)/name(s) of existing database(s) to be opened upon startup. For example:

  Work:QuickFile/
  QuickFile Data:AddressBook/AddressBook

Without arguments, a single empty database window is opened. If database arguments are provided, each existing one is opened in its own window and the first record displayed. For each non-existent database argument, an error message is displayed and an empty database window is opened.


QuickFile opens its windows on the default public screen. The default window size is 640x256. For existing databases, the size and position of the window will depend on the default @{"view" link AboutViews} for that database.

An AppIcon is also placed on the Workbench screen, and each open window is an AppWindow. Databases may be loaded into windows by dragging and dropping icons for the database definition files onto them.@{b} Note@{ub} that project icons are not generated by QuickFile.

Saving each database to a separate directory is recommended, as having a number of index and view files for different databases in the same directory could become confusing. This also makes it easy to back up databases by simply copying each directory to a backup disk.

The current @{"view" link AboutViews} determines the format of the display, reports, and exported or imported files. Views can be added, deleted and edited, and are saved to separate files that can be loaded from disk (except for the default view) or freed from memory (unless there's only one left loaded) at any time.

The current @{"index" link AboutIndexes} determines the sequence that records are displayed in. Indexes can also be added, deleted and edited and are saved to separate files, which are all loaded when the database is opened.

Database records can be @{"re-sorted" link Sort Index} into any sequence, based on any number of fields in any combination or ascending and descending orders, at any time. @{"Queries" link Queries} may also be performed to select and display only those records matching certain criteria. The selection status of individual records can also be @{"toggled" link Toggle Record} manually. Sorts, queries and toggle-selecting create temporary indexes, which may be discarded from memory at any time.


New users should browse through this document to get a feel for the program. Example databases are provided in the Examples drawer. Click on one of these icons to start Quickfile and load the database.

There are also several ARexx @{"macros" link Macros} provided, and the included @{"Demo.quickfile" link ARexx/Demo.quickfile/Main} macro shows off many of the ARexx capabilities of QuickFile. Before running it, open or load the AddressBook database.
@endnode
@node DataBases "QuickFile Database Structure"

The structure of a QuickFile database is primarily specified via the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, in which the @{"fields" link Fields} and @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} are defined. When saved to disk, each database always consists of at least three separate files. For a database named 'Products', the following files will be saved:

  Products

The database definition file, which stores all information regarding the fields, index(es) and other general information.

  Products.Data

This file stores the actual records data.

  Products.<index>X

One file for each index defined for the database, which maintains information regarding the order of records for that index. <index> is the name given the index when it was defined. Each database must have at least one index.

There may be additional files associated with a QuickFile database, which could include:

  Products.View

An optional default @{"view" link AboutViews}, storing information about the layout of fields in the window, which QuickFile will attempt to load whenever the database is opened. If QuickFile is not able to locate the file in the same directory as the database definition file, a message to that effect will be reported, and a default @{"FORM" link FORM} view layout will be used.

  <view>[.View]

Any number of optional additional view files, one for each defined and saved view. <view> is the name given the view when it was defined. By default, QuickFile adds the extension '.View' and presents the full name in a file requester, where the name may be modified, if and when the user proceeds to save a new or view to disk. The extension is not required, however, and view files may actually have any legal filename.

  Products.Startup

An optional ARexx @{"macro" link Macros} to be run when the database is opened.

  Products.Macros

An optional configuration file for items in the MACROS menu for this database, saved and loaded by the @{"DEFINE MACROS" link Define Macros} requester.

  Products.Keys

An optional configuration file for the function keys for this database, saved and loaded by the @{"FUNCTION KEYS" link Function Keys} requester.

  <query>[.qry]

Saved query files, which store the criteria used for frequently used @{"queries" link Queries}, saved and loaded by the @{"QUERY" link Query} requester. These are by default saved with the extension '.qry' but may have any legal filename.
@endnode
@node Window "Main Window"

If a database has been loaded into a window, the title bar of the window displays a status line containing the names of the current view and index, the current record number and the total number of records. Status and information messages may periodically be displayed here, temporarily replacing the above information.

A row of buttons is displayed across the top of the window to allow quick access to frequently used functions:

  @{"GoTo     " link GotoButton}  Go to a record by index field value(s)
  @{"Modify   " link InsertModify}  Modify an existing record
  @{"Insert   " link InsertModify}  Insert a new record
  @{"Delete   " link Delete}  Delete an existing record
  @{"Form/List" link FormList}  Toggle between LIST and FORM view formats
  @{"All/Sel  " link AllSel}  Toggle between ALL and SELECTED records
  @{"Images   " link ImageToggle}  Toggle image display on and off

The vertical scroll bar controls movement through the current index and works in the usual way. Selecting one of the arrow buttons scrolls one record at a time. Clicking the mouse in the empty portion of the scroll box to scrolls one windowful at a time in @{"LIST" link List} views and one record at a time in @{"FORM" link Form} views. Dragging the scroll bar allows the user to scroll through as many records as desired.

Scrolling may also be done using the up and down arrow keys, by themselves, and in combination with certain qualifier keys. See @{"Keyboard Usage" link Keys} for more details.

If there are more fields than will fit in the current window, the horizontal scroll bar can be used to view the additional fields. There are no arrows buttons or keyboard shortcuts available for horizontal scrolling.

Windows can be positioned and resized using the standard title bar, size and zoom gadgets, and can be shrunk to a small button by selecting @{"Iconify" link Iconify}, or hidden from view completely by selecting @{"Hide" link Hide}, from the Project menu.

The remaining functions are accessed via the @{"Menus" link Menus}.
@endnode
@node GoToButton "Go to a Record by Index Key Value(s)"
@toc Window

Selecting the GOTO button displays a requester with string gadgets for each field that is used in the current @{"index" link AboutIndexes}, into which index key values the user wishes to jump to may be entered. This enables fast access to any record, even in large databases.

Case is ignored, and entry must begin with the first index field that is not left blank in the desired record. Entry values need not necessarily be complete in order to locate the record, however. For example, if the following values exist in records for the first index field, the corresponding GOTO values shown would be the minimum entries required to jump to that record:

  @{u}Record@{uu}  @{u}Index Field 1 Value@{uu}  @{u}GOTO Value 1@{uu}
  1       Smart                sm
  2       Smith                smi
  3       Smithers             smithe
  4       Smithfield           smithf
  5       Smythe               smy

When entering multiple GOTO values to locate records in an index with multiple index fields, all values must be entered completely except for the last one. For example:

          Index Field 1  Index Field 2
  @{u}Record@{uu}  @{u}    Value    @{uu}  @{u}    Value    @{uu}  @{u}GOTO Value 1@{uu}  @{u}GOTO Value 2@{uu}
  1       Smith          Greg           smith         g
  2       Smith          Jerry          smith         j
  3       Smith          John           smith         jo

If the GOTO values entered do not exist in the corresponding field in any records, the next closest matching record which would follow it is displayed, or the last record if there is no next closest matching record.
@endnode
@node InsertModify "Inserting or Modifying Records"
@toc Window

Selecting either the INSERT button or the MODIFY button at the top of the main database @{"window" link Window} switches the display to record EDIT mode. Only those @{"fields" link Fields} used in the current @{"view" link AboutViews} are displayed in the EDIT mode window, and they are laid out as in a @{"FORM" link Form} view, even if the current view is a @{"LIST" link List} view.

If the SHIFT key is held down when the INSERT button is selected, all field values are copied from the current existing record and are displayed for editing. Otherwise, all displayed field string gadgets are empty.

If the MODIFY button is selected, the current record is displayed for editing.

@{"CALCULATED" link Calc} fields that are part of the current view are displayed, with any labels given them, in the EDIT mode window, however, their values may only be modified by editing the contents of the fields from which they are calculated, or by editing the CALCULATION EXPRESSION for the corresponding field in the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq} requester.

CYCLE fields are displayed in the EDIT mode window as cycle gadgets, which must be repeatedly selected with the mouse until the desired string appears. The available strings may only be changed by modifying the CYCLE EXPRESSION for the field in the FIELD requester.

All other field types are displayed as string gadgets, in which field values may be directly entered. An arrow button is additionally displayed to the right of each string gadget for @{"IMAGE" link Image} and @{"EXTERNAL" link External} fields. Selecting this button causes a file requester to be displayed, with which the desired file/field value may be selected,.@{b} Note@{ub} that there is no notification of invalid file path/names until the database window is returned to VIEW mode and QuickFile attempts to access them.

If the cursor is in an empty string gadget for a field that is set to MANDATORY in the field definition, it cannot be deactivated by pressing TAB or RETURN, nor can the cursor be moved to the next or previous string gadget by pressing the UP or DOWN arrow keys. It CAN always be deactivated by pressing ESC or by clicking elsewhere with the mouse.

If there are more fields in the current view than will fit in the window, the horizontal scroll bar can be used to access the additional fields. No keyboard shortcuts exist for it.

At the top of the EDIT mode window are OK and CANCEL buttons. When INSERTing a new record, there is also a COPY button. Selecting COPY causes the values of all fields in the current existing record (the record that was displayed before INSERT was selected, if any) to be copied to the new record in progress for editing. This is useful when inserting new records with identical or similar values in some of the fields.@{b} Note@{ub} that selecting COPY will cause any values already entered to be replaced.

Selecting OK, or pressing RETURN on the keyboard when no string gadget is active, inserts the new record or updates the revised record, unless the record would be a duplicate index entry in an index that has been @{"defined" link IndexReq} as unique, in which an error message is displayed. If a new record is being inserted and it is not a duplicate index entry in a unique index, all string gadgets are cleared of values so that another new record can be entered.@{b} Note@{ub} that a completely empty record cannot be inserted.

Holding a SHIFT key down while selecting OK, or while pressing RETURN, has the same effect as selecting OK, and then selecting COPY for the next record to be inserted.

Selecting OK after an existing record has been modified commits the modified record and returns the database window to record VIEW mode, unless the record has become a duplicate index entry, in which case an error message is displayed. The record displayed when EDIT mode is exited may not be the one just modified, if changes made to any INDEX fields in it cause the record to be re-positioned in the current @{"index" link AboutIndexes}, in which case either the next record that was before it or after it is displayed.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub} Selecting CANCEL will result in the loss of any values already entered or modified. Select OK to insert a record in progress if it is to be kept, then CANCEL to stop inserting more records.
@endnode
@node Delete "Deleting Records"
@toc Window

Selecting the DELETE button displays a requester asking for confirmation to delete the current record. Selecting OK deletes the record and closes the requester.@{b} Warning:@{ub} Once a record has been deleted it cannot be restored.
@endnode
@node FormList "Toggling Between FORM and LIST View Formats"
@toc Window

Selecting the FORM/LIST button toggles display of the current @{"view" link AboutViews} between @{"FORM" link Form} and @{"LIST" link List} display formats. It is the same as selecting @{"ALTER" link Alter } from the VIEW menu and changing the View type.

@{b}Note@{ub} that changes made to a view in one mode also affect the other mode, but this button provides a quick way to switch modes on the fly, and keeps field labels, length and order the same.
@endnode
@node AllSel "Toggling between ALL and SELECTED records"
@toc Window

Selecting the ALL/SEL button toggles between displaying all records in the file using the current permanent @{"index" link AboutIndexes}, and displaying only selected records. If no records have been selected, a blank record is displayed.

The same thing may also be accomplished by choosing the SELECTED index from the @{"INDEX" link Indexes} requester, or by selecting @{"Show Selected" link Show All Records} from the SELECTION menu.
@endnode
@node ImageToggle "Toggling Image Display On and Off"
@toc Window

The IMAGES checkbox allows the user to toggle display of @{"images" link Images} (via @{"IMAGE" link Image} fields) off for faster processing, and back on again, while using a @{"FORM" link FORM} view. For @{"LIST" link List} views and databases which have no IMAGE fields defined, the status of this checkbox has no effect.

IMAGE fields are intended to store only the file path/names of IFF ILBM image files that are accessible to Quickfile while the database is in use. The images themselves are loaded from the named files for display with each record. When image display is toggled off, the file path/names are displayed.

@{b}Note@{ub} that "iffparse.library" must be available in LIBS: in order for images to be displayed.
@endnode
@node Menus "Menu Functions"

@{b}Project Menu@{ub}

  @{"Open                   " link Open }  Open a database in a new window
  @{"Load                   " link Load }  Open a database in the current window
  @{"Save                   " link Save }  Save changes to the database
  @{"Close                  " link Close }  Close the database and window
  @{"Save As                " link Save As}  Save the current database with a new name
  @{"New                    " link New}  Define a new database
  @{"Alter                  " link Alter}  Edit the current database definition
  @{"Import                 " link Import}  Import records from a file
  @{"Export                 " link Export}  Export records to a file
  @{"Reorganise             " link Reorganise}  Optimise the database
  @{"Iconify                " link Iconify}  Reduce the current window to a title bar button
  @{"Hide                   " link Hide}  Hide the current database window
  @{"About                  " link About}  Show information about QuickFile
  @{"Quit                   " link Quit}  Close all windows and quit QuickFile

@{b}View Menu@{ub}

  @{"Views                  " link Views}  Display list of loaded views
  @{"New                    " link New }  Define a new view
  @{"Load                   " link Load  }  Load a view from disk
  @{"Save                   " link Save  }  Save changes to a view
  @{"Save As                " link Save As }  Save the current view with a new name
  @{"Alter                  " link Alter }  Edit the current view definition
  @{"Reset form             " link Reset form}  Set view back to default layout

@{b}Order Menu@{ub}

  @{"Indexes                " link Indexes}  Display list of indexes
  @{"Sort index             " link Sort index}  Sort file into a new sequence
  @{"Show Sorted            " link Show Sorted}  Display file in sorted sequence
  @{"Rebuild Index          " link Rebuild Index}  Rebuild current index

@{b}Selection Menu@{ub}

  @{"Query                  " link Query}  Select records matching certain criteria
  @{"Toggle Record          " link Toggle Record}  Select/Unselect single record
  @{"Show Selected Records  " link Show Selected Records}  Display selected records
  @{"Show All Records       " link Show All Records}  Display all records

@{b}Print Menu@{ub}

  @{"Displayed Records      " link Displayed Records}
  @{"Current Index          " link Current Index}

@{b}Macros Menu@{ub}

  @{"Direct Macro           " link Direct Macro}  Invoke single QuickFile functions
  @{"ARexx Script           " link ARexx Script}  Run a file or inline ARexx script
  @{"Define Macros          " link Define Macros}  Configure the rest of this menu
  @{"Macro...               " link Macro...}  Run macros configured with DEFINE MACROS
  @{"Function keys          " link Function Keys}  Configure function keys for macros
  @{"Help...                " link Help...}  Get help for macro functions

@{b}Options Menu@{ub}

  @{"Buffers                " link Buffers}  Edit number of buffers to use
  @{"Configuration          " link Configuration}  Specify fonts to use, online help, etc.
@endnode
@node Open  "Opening a Database"
@toc Menus

Selecting OPEN from the PROJECT menu causes a file requester to be displayed, with which a database definition file may be selected to open in a new database window. By default, the file requester hides @{"index" link AboutIndexes}, @{"view" link AboutViews}, @{"data" link Databases} and ".info" files. If it also hides the desired database definition file, the pattern string should be cleared.

If ARexx is available and an ARexx script @{"macro" link Macros} with the name "<database>.startup" exists in the same directory as the definition file, it will be run automatically after the database has been opened.
@endnode
@node Load  "Loading a Database"
@toc Menus

Selecting LOAD from the PROJECT menu causes a file requester to be displayed, with which a database definition file may be selected to LOAD into the current window, replacing the database currently open in it, if any. By default, the file requester hides @{"index" link AboutIndexes}, @{"view" link AboutViews}, @{"data" link Databases} and ".info" files. If it also hides the desired database definition file, the pattern string should be cleared.

If ARexx is available and an ARexx script @{"macro" link Macros} with the name "<database>.startup" exists in the same directory as the definition file, it will be run automatically after the database has been opened.
@endnode
@node Save  "Saving Changes to a Database"
@toc Menus

Selecting SAVE from the PROJECT menu causes all updated @{"blocks" link IO} and @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} to be saved to disk. This should be done periodically during long update sessions. Nothing is written if no changes have been made since the database was opened or since the last save.
@endnode
@node Close  "Closing the Current Database and Window"
@toc Menus

Selecting CLOSE from the PROJECT menu causes a requester to be displayed, asking for confirmation that the current window is to be closed if a database has been loaded into it. Selecting OK from the requester saves all updated @{"blocks" link IO} and @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} to disk and closes the current database and window. If no database has been loaded, the current window is closed immediately.

If the current window is the only one open, the program is also quit at this time.
@endnode
@node Save As "Saving the Current Database or Index with a Different Name"
@toc Menus

Selecting SAVE AS from the PROJECT menu causes a file requester to be displayed, in which to enter a new name to save the current @{"index" link AboutIndexes} as. If the current index is @{"SELECTED" link Selected}, only the selected records are saved to the new database. It is recommended that all databases are saved in separate directories.

The new database is @{"reorganized" link Reorganise} as it is written. Indexes are not created for it at this time, but will be built the first time it is opened. After the new database has been created, a requester is displayed asking if it should be opened, or if the session with the current database should be continued.
@endnode
@node New "Defining a New Database"
@toc Menus

Selecting NEW from the PROJECT menu causes the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester to be displayed, in which @{"fields" link Fields} and @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} are defined, and several values are set for database input and output. If the current window already has a database loaded into it, a new database window is also opened for the new database.
@endnode
@node Alter "Altering the Defintion of an Existing Database"
@toc Menus

Selecting ALTER from the PROJECT menu causes the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester to be displayed, unless no database has been loaded into the current window. The requester is used to define and modify @{"fields" link Fields} and @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes}, and to set several values that are used for database input and output. All unsaved changes to the data in the current database are saved to disk immediately. The current database definition is then displayed in the DEFINE FILE requester for editing. If there is no database loaded into the current window, the requester is not displayed.

If any @{"SORTED" link Sorted} or @{"SELECTED" link Selected} indexes exist, they are discarded when the DEFINE FILE requester is opened.
@endnode
@node DefineFile "The Define File Requester"
@toc Menus

The DEFINE FILE is displayed when either NEW or ALTER is selected from the PROJECT menu. The requester is used to define @{"fields" link Fields} and @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes}, and to set several values that are used for database input and output. For new databases, only default input and output values are displayed in the requester for editing. For existing databases, the current database definition is displayed for modification.

The requester is divided into four sections:

  @{"Fields       " link FieldDef}  Definition of fields
  @{"Indexes      " link IndexDef}  Definition of indexes
  @{"IO Settings  " link IO}  Setting block size, maximum buffers and free space
  @{"External Path" link ExtPath}  Setting a default path for use with @{"IMAGE" link Image} and @{"EXTERNAL" link External}
                  fields

Everything except BLOCK SIZE may be altered in a database definition at any time, even after records have been added to the database. Fields and indexes may be added or deleted; field names, types and lengths may be changed; index names, fields, field lengths and orders may be modified.@{b} Note@{ub} that changing the TYPE or LENGTH of a field that already contains data may result in some data loss if existing field values are incompatible with the new type, or if they exceed the new length.

In the bottom right corner of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK displays a requester asking for confirmation that the altered database definition should be saved.
@endnode
@node FieldDef "Defining Fields"
@toc DefineFile

The FIELDS panel, at the left of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, is where fields are defined. A listview shows all existing fields, their @{"types" link Types}, maximum lengths, and whether or not they are calculated. A bar indicates which field is currently selected in the list.

Below the listview are buttons labeled ADD, MODIFY and DELETE. Selecting ADD or MODIFY displays the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq} requester. If ADD was selected, all settings and definitions in the requester are empty, so that a new field may be defined. If an existing field is highlighted in the field listview, the new field is inserted above it. QuickFile has a limit of 250 fields per database.

If MODIFY was selected and an existing field was highlighted in the listview, the definition of that field is displayed for editing.

Selecting DELETE displays a requester asking for confirmation that the selected field should be deleted. If OK is selected, the field is deleted immediately, and cannot be salvaged. @{b} Note@{ub} that deleting a field makes its data inaccessible, even if the same field definition is re-added. If a field is accidentally deleted, the CANCEL button in the lower right corner of the DEFINE FILE requester should be selected. However, doing so will also discard any other changes that have been made, and they will have to be re-done if desired.

@{b}Note@{ub} also that modifying or deleting any fields that are used in field calcualtions, indexes or saved views may result in errors and/or additional requesters informing the user of such problems.
@endnode
@node FieldReq "The Field Requester"
@toc FieldDef

The FIELD requester is displayed when the ADD or MODIFY button is selected from the FIELDS panel of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, to either define a new field or modify the definition of an existing one. Its components are:

@{b}Name@{ub}

The name of the field, up to 12 characters.

@{b}Type@{ub}

This listview displays the available field @{"types" link Types}. A bar indicates the current type selected for this field. A different type may be selected with the mouse, or by using the UP and DOWN arrow keys to scroll through the list.

@{b}Length@{ub}

The maximum allowable length for the field, must be a whole number between 1 and 250 inclusive. @{"DATE" link DateField} and @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields require certain minimum lengths. DATE, TIME, @{"FLOAT" link Float}, @{"INTEGER" link Integer} and @{"CYCLE" link Cycle} fields each have maximum useable data lengths that are significantly less than 250, although the field length may be set to a higher number if desired. @{b} Note@{ub} that for @{"FORM" link Form} views, the number of characters that can be displayed on a line in record VIEW mode is limited by the font used, and by the width of the database window. This is limited by the screenmode and overscan settings used, typically to about 60 to 70 characters for NTSC/PAL screens. Longer field values may be entered and data is retained when inserting and modifying records, but the additional data is not visible in VIEW mode.

Space is only used for the actual data entered in fields, not for the maximum field length. If a field is empty, no space is used.

@{b}Decimals@{ub}

The number of decimals places to be stored and displayed, only enabled for FLOAT fields. Must be a whole number between 0 and 9 inclusive. Values entered into the field are rounded to this number of decimals as necessary whenever a record is @{"inserted or modified" link InsertModify}.

@{b}Right Justified@{ub}

If checked, values entered into the field are displayed right justified, otherwise left justified. By default, this box is checked for INTEGER and FLOAT fields, and unchecked for all other field types.

@{b}Mandatory@{ub}

If checked, the field requires some value other than NULL in all records. QuickFile positions the cursor in the field and displays the message "Value must be entered" if the user attempts to insert or update a record in which the field was left blank, but only if the field is part of the current @{"view." link AboutViews}

@{b}Calculated@{ub}

If checked, values for this field are @{"calculated" link Calc} from other field values in the same record according to a formula entered into the EXPRESSION string gadget below. All field types except @{"DATE" link DateField} and @{"CYCLE" link Cycle} can be calculated, and certain restrictions apply to each type.

@{b}Expression@{ub}

This string gadget is available only for the following two field types and corresponding uses:

  @{"Cycle     " link Cycle}  A list of possible values to choose from, separated by commas
  @{"Calculated" link Calc}  An expression to calculate from other field values

@{b}Command@{ub}

For @{"EXTERNAL" link External} fields only, the desired command or program path/name to operate on field values, which are typically file path/names. Unless the command or program resides somewhere in the user's command path (usually established with the AmigaDOS "PATH" command in the Startup-Sequence), or in the current directory, the full path to it must be specified here.

Any other arguments, in addition to the field values, that the user wishes to pass to the command for@{b} all@{ub} records may also be included here. Include "%s" in the string to designate where the field value should be filled in. For example, if the COMMAND string is specified as:

  SYS:Utilities/MultiView %s SCREEN

And the EXTERNAL field value in the current record is:

  Work:Pictures/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm

The actual command string is executed as:

  SYS:Utilities/MultiView Work:Pictures/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm SCREEN


All settings defined in this requester, except TYPE, can be changed for any field at any time. If the length of a field is decreased, however, existing field data in excess of the new allowable length is only discarded from records if and when they are updated. Increasing the field length again will restore the old data, except for any in records that have been updated since the length was changed. @{b} Note@{ub} that @{"reorganizing" link Reorganise} a database updates ALL records, and all excess data is lost.

Field TYPE can also be changed, but existing field values may be lost when changing to a type that the values are not compatible with. Existing values will ALWAYS be lost when changing field types to or from CYCLE. Also, QuickFile may display error requesters for any calculated fields in which the field types are incompatible with the calculation expression.


At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK when a new field has been defined causes the newly defined field to be accepted, assuming the new field has been defined fully. If it has not, a message is displayed in the title bar of the requester informing the user of what is required.

After a new field has been accepted, the requester remains open and the contents cleared from the NAME string gadget, so that another new field may be defined. To stop defining additional fields, CANCEL should be selected after the last new field definition was OK'd. The requester is then closed, and all new fields are displayed in the FIELDS listview in the DEFINE FILE requester.

If OK is selected when an existing field definition has been modified, the requester is closed and modified field definition accepted. Display of the modified field in the FIELDS listview is updated as necessary.
@endnode
@node Types "Field Types"
@toc FieldReq

The TYPE of a field affects how it is displayed, how it is used in @{"indexes and sorting" link AboutIndexes}, and how it is considered during @{"queries" link Queries}. QuickFile features the following field types:

  Character  Character strings; may be calculated from other field types
  @{"Float   " link Float}  Real numbers; displayed with up to 9 decimal places
  @{"Integer " link Integer}  Whole numbers only; may be calculated from FLOAT fields
  @{"Date    " link DateField}  Date values, in the form "dd-Mmm-yyyy (e.g. "24-Feb-2000")
  @{"Time    " link TimeField}  Time values, in the form "hh:mm:ss (e.g. "16:41:11")
  @{"Cycle   " link Cycle}  A choice of up to 32 pre-defined strings in a cycle button
  @{"Image   " link Image}  File path/names of IFF-ILBMs to be displayed
  @{"External" link External}  Strings (usually file path/names) to be passed to an external
             command or program configured for the field

All field types except DATE and CYCLE fields may be @{"calculated" link Calc}. Certain restrictions apply to each type.
@endnode
@node Float "Float Fields"
@toc Types

FLOAT fields store real numbers in the range -999999999999999 to 999999999999999 with up to 9 decimal places, and may be @{"calculated" link Calc} from other FLOAT fields, as well as from @{"INTEGER" link Integer} and @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields. Up to 15 digits may be entered before the decimal point (if the field length is sufficient). If more than 15 are entered, the cursor remains in the field when the user attempts to exit and QuickFile displays the message "Too may digits in number (15 max)" in the title bar of the EDIT window.

Any number of decimal place digits may be entered (up to the allowed field length), however, they are truncated to the number of decimals specified for the field in the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq} requester when records are inserted or updated.

@{b}Note@{ub} that there are several limitations of the Amiga math libraries which can affect FLOAT values:

1) Only the first 15 digits entered (non-decimal and decimal combined) are retained when records are committed. Any digits entered in excess of 15 become zeros. For example:

  @{u}          Entered as...        @{uu}  @{u}           Stored as...       @{uu}
            1234567890.123456789             1234567890.123450000
  12345678901234567890.123456789   12345678901234500000.000000000

2) Numbers entered with more than 8 digits are usually stored and displayed incorrectly, unless the last digit is a zero, in which case they are correct unless they exceed 9 digits. For example:

  @{u}          Entered as...        @{uu}  @{u}          Stored as...        @{uu}
                        555555555            555555554.999999000
                        100000000            100000000.000000000
                       1000000000            999999999.999999000

3) Numbers entered with more than 9 digits are usually calculated incorrectly. For example:

  @{u}           Field1             @{uu}  @{u}Field2 (calculated as Field1*2)@{uu}
            1111111110.999990000             2222222221.999960000
       123456789012345.000000000        246913578024688.000000000
@endnode
@node Integer "Integer Fields"
@toc Types

INTEGER fields store whole numbers in the range -2147483648 to 2147483648, and may be @{"calculated" link Calc} from other INTEGER fields, as well as from @{"FLOAT" link Float} and @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields. The display flashes if the user attempts to enter a number outside the specified range. @{b} Note@{ub} however that it is possible to set the value of an INTEGER field to -2147483649 or 2147483649 using the @{"macro" link Macros} function @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}.
@endnode
@node DateField "Date Fields"
@toc Types

DATE fields store date values, require a minimum length of 11, and must be entered as DAY NUMBER, MONTH and YEAR, separated by spaces, slashes, dashes or periods.

MONTH may be entered as a one or two digit number, or as a three character name.

YEAR may be entered as two or four digits; if two digits are entered, any number greater than or equal to 50 is assumed to be 19xx, and any number less than 50 is assumed to be 20xx. Years less than 1950 and greater than 2049 must be entered using four digits, and must also be in the range 0100 to 9999.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

  03/08/93
  3-8-93
  3.aug.93
  3 8 1993

All are re-formatted and displayed as "03-Aug-1993". DATE fields may not be @{"calculated" link Calc}, but may be used in calculated CHARACTER fields.
@endnode
@node TimeField "Time Fields"
@toc Types

TIME fields store time values, require a minimum length of 8, and are entered as HOURS, MINUTES and SECONDS, separated by colons, spaces or periods. HOURS may exceed 24, and may be entered in the range 0 to 2147483647. Trailing (lower order) zeros may be omitted. For example:

  3:10:2
  3.10.2

    >>> 03:10:02

  1.0.0
  1.0
  1

    >>> 01:00:00

  2147483647:15:0
  2147483647:15

    >>> 2147483647:15:00

@{b}Note@{ub} that TIME fields can be set to out-of-range HOUR values using the @{"macro" link Macros} function @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}, but the resulting stored values will be in the range -2147483647 to 2147483647. For example:

    Value used
  @{u}with PUTFIELD@{uu}  @{u}   Stored Value  @{uu}
    2147483648   -2147483648:00:00
    4294967296         [blank]
    5000000000     705032704:00:00

TIME fields may be calculated from @{"INTEGER" link Integer} and @{"FLOAT" link Float} fields, as well as other TIME fields, and are treated as the total number of seconds when used in numerical calculations.
@endnode
@node Cycle "Cycle Fields"
@toc Types

CYCLE fields allow the user to establish a list of up to 32 pre-defined strings, from which the desired string may be selected, via a cycle button, for each record. The strings are stored in the EXPRESSION string gadget in the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq} requester, separated by commas. EXPRESSION accepts up to 250 characters; however, none of the strings may be longer than 30 characters. Any spaces entered in EXPRESSION will be included with the adjacent string. For example:

  Expression    = "Blue, Green, Light Blue, Red"
  Cycle strings = "Blue", " Green", " Light Blue", " Red"

  Expression    = "Blue,Green,Light Blue,Red"
  Cycle strings = "Blue", "Green", "Light Blue", "Red"

CYCLE fields may not be @{"calculated" link Calc}, but may be used in calculated CHARACTER fields.
@endnode
@node Image "Image Fields"
@toc Types

IMAGE fields store character strings, which are usually file path/names of standard Amiga IFF-ILBM images. Image files specified in the field are displayed in the database window in @{"FORM" link Form} view, if "iffparse.library" is available in LIBS:, and if the @{"IMAGES" link ImageToggle} checkbox at the top of the database window is checked. If not checked, the character strings are displayed.

In record @{"edit" link InsertModify} mode, IMAGE fields are displayed as string gadgets with arrow buttons to the right of them. Selecting the button displays a file requester with which the user may choose the desired file and path. The @{"EXTERNAL PATH" link ExtPath} specified in the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester is used as a default path for IMAGE fields, unless a full path is specified in the field.

Displayed images are cropped to the size of the field box defined in the FORM, with no scaling or palette remapping. To display images with the correct palette and resolution, or images in formats other than IFF-ILBM, an @{"EXTERNAL" link External} field should be configured for use with an appropriate display program.

@{"Queries" link Queries}, @{"indexes and sorting" link AboutIndexes}, and @{"printing" link Printing} operate only on the character strings stored in the field.
@endnode
@node External "External Fields"
@toc Types

EXTERNAL fields store character strings (usually file path/names) to be passed to the external command or program, defined in the COMMAND string gadget in the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq} requester, for processing. This allows the user to display images, text files or animations, play sounds, run programs, extract archives, launch ARexx scripts, or anything else that can be accomplished from a Shell prompt.

Any arguments to be passed to the defined COMMAND for some records but not others may also be specified in the field.

EXTERNAL fields are displayed with an @{"R" link RunCommand} button to the left of them in record VIEW mode if the current view type is @{"FORM" link Form}. Selecting the button runs the external command and passes the arguments stored in the field to it. In @{"LIST" link List} views, the @{"R" link RunCommand} button is not available.

In record @{"EDIT" link InsertModify} mode, EXTERNAL fields are displayed as string gadgets with arrow buttons to the right of them. Selecting the button displays a file requester with which the user may select the desired file and path. The @{"EXTERNAL PATH" link ExtPath} specified in the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester is used as a default path for EXTERNAL field filenames, unless a full path is specified in the field.

If any file path/names used in this field contain spaces, a double-quote mark should be added to the end of the filename in each record in which the field is used, and one should also be placed at the beginning of the external path specification. If the field contains the full path to the file, the first double-quote mark should be placed at the beginning of the path in the field itself.
@endnode
@node RunCommand "External Fields: R button"
@toc External

Selecting this button runs the command specified in the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq} requester for the corresponding @{"EXTERNAL" link External} field.
@endnode
@node Calc "Calculated Fields"
@toc FieldReq

If the CALCULATED box is checked in the @{"FIELD" link FieldReq}, a calculation expression must be specified in the EXPRESSION string gadget. All field @{"types" link Types} except @{"DATE" link DateField} and @{"CYCLE" link Cycle} may be calculated from other field values, with certain restrictions.

The expression may be up to 511 characters in length, and may contain constants, operators and macro @{"functions" link Functions} (especially @{"GETFIELD" link GetField}, to refer to other fields).@{b} Note@{ub} that all macro functions@{b} must@{ub} be entered in UPPER CASE in the expression gadget, and all literal strings must be quoted. Numbers need not be quoted. Fields referenced must have already been defined, or QuickFile will report an error. Other calculated fields may be used.

Normal precedence rules apply, and parentheses may be used to modify the evaluation order.

@{"TIME" link TimeField} field values are treated as the total number of seconds in numerical calculations. For example:

  @{u}TIME value@{uu}  @{u}Treated as@{uu}
   00:00:35         35
   00:04:35        275
   01:20:35       4835

Any field types (numerical, string, DATE and CYCLE) may be used in string field calculations.

See the @{"macro" link MacroRef} reference section for details on the functions and operators available for use in field calculations.
@endnode
@node IndexDef "Defining Indexes"
@toc DefineFile

The INDEXES panel, at the right side of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, is where @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} are defined. A listview displays all previously defined indexes. At least one index is required for each database. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected index in the listview. A different index may be selected, if available, with the mouse or keyboard.

Below the listview are NEW, MODIFY and DELETE buttons. Selecting NEW or MODIFY displays the @{"INDEX" link IndexReq} requester. If the NEW button is selected, a new index may be defined. If an existing index is selected in the listview when NEW is selected, the new index will be inserted above it. To add a new index to the bottom of the list, "== End ==" should first be selected. There is no limit to the number of indexes per database.

If an existing index is selected in the listview and the MODIFY button is selected, the definition of that index is displayed for editing.

If an existing index is selected in the listview and the DELETE button is selected, a requester is displayed, asking for confirmation that the selected index should be deleted. If the OK button is selected, the index is deleted immediately, and cannot be salvaged.
@endnode
@node IndexReq "The Index and Sort Requesters"
@toc IndexDef

The INDEX requester is displayed when the NEW or MODIFY button is selected from the @{"INDEXES" link IndexDef} panel at the right side of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester. If NEW is selected, a new index may be defined. If MODIFY is selected and an existing index is highlighted in the INDEXES panel listview, its definition is displayed for editing, to either define a new index or edit the definition of an existing one.

The SORT requester is displayed when @{"SORT" link Sort index} is selected from the ORDER menu, and when the ORDER button is selected from within the @{"QUERY" link Query} requester. The SORT requester is nearly identical to the INDEX requester, except that the name for the resulting index is either SORTED (if SORT was selected from the menu) or SELECTED (if specifying the order for a @{"query" link Queries}). It cannot be edited, and the UNIQUE checkbox is unavailable.

The requester components are:

@{b}Name@{ub}

The name of this index, up to 14 characters. The index is saved to disk with the name "<database>.<index>X".@{b} Note@{ub} that QuickFile allows index names with spaces, double-quote marks, and various other characters that are illegal in AmigaDOS filenames, and will happily save them to disk that way.@{b} Note also@{ub} that when using the SORT requester, the name of the index is displayed as SELECTED (if for a query) or SORTED and cannot be edited, and the index in either case is not saved to disk.

@{b}Unique@{ub}

If checked, the user is notified and duplicate index entries are rejected by QuickFile when @{"inserting" link InsertModify} or @{"modifying" link InsertModify} records. A duplicate index entry exists if there two records in which the corresponding index fields, for the current index, have the same value.@{b} Note@{ub} that this checkbox is not available when using the SORT requester.

@{b}Available Fields@{ub}

An untitled listview on the left side of the requester, listing all fields defined for the current database.

@{b}Index Fields@{ub}

An untitled listview on the right side of the requester, listing all fields used in this index. Fields are added to this list by clicking on their names in the AVAILABLE FIELDS listview on the left with the mouse. If an INDEX field is selected in the list when a new field is added, the new field will be inserted above it. To add a new field to the bottom of the list, "== End ==" should first be selected.

Each index can be based on any combination of available fields, in any order. The order of fields in the list determines their priority in the index. Database records are sorted by the top field first, and by subsequent fields only when several records exist in which values in corresponding higher fields are identical.

@{b}Length@{ub}

The index field length, or maximum portion of the field that index sorting is based on, of the highlighted index field, which can be less than the actual field length. For example:

  Field value         = "A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court"
  Field value length  = 43
  Index field length  = 20
  Sort based only on... "A Connecticut Yankee"

Using a smaller index length for index fields can reduce processor and RAM requirements when sorting and rebuilding indexes.@{b} Note@{ub} that either@{b} TAB or RETURN must@{ub} be pressed after entering a field index length or the value is ignored.

@{b}Order@{ub}

Which of these buttons is selected determines whether the currently highlighted index field is sorted in ASCENDING order (NORMAL) or DESCENDING order (REVERSE). The order may be set separately for each index field. When new fields are added to the index, they are set to NORMAL by default.

@{b}Delete@{ub}

Selecting this button deletes the highlighted index field from the list. No confirmation is asked.

@{b}Clear@{ub}

Selecting this button clears@{b} ALL@{ub} index fields from the list. No confirmation is asked.


At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK causes the new or modified index definition to be accepted and closes the requester, updating the INDEXES listview display in the DEFINE FILE requester as necessary. If an existing index is modified, it is rebuilt when the DEFINE FILE requester is closed.
@endnode
@node IO "Database Input/Output Settings"
@toc DefineFile

The database input/output details are displayed at the upper right side of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester. The settings are described below:

@{b}Block Size@{ub}

QuickFile does not read and write single records at a time, but builds them into blocks first. Each block contains a number of records, the number depending on the block size and the size of each record. This reduces the number of disk reads and writes required. Block size must be larger than the maximum record size (in bytes or characters) plus free space, and some space for control fields (2 bytes per field plus 2 bytes for the record length).

Once a database has been defined for the first time, the block size cannot be modified, except by @{"reorganizing" link Reorganise} the database with a new size. This may be required in order to add fields to an existing database whose block size is insufficient to accommodate the additional fields.

@{b}Free Space@{ub}

The number of bytes to be reserved in each block to allow for records to expand. As QuickFile only stores the actual data entered (not trailing blanks), additional space is required if modifications to a record results in a longer record. Records are moved to another block if necessary, so this is not critical.

The amount of free space used for a database can be changed permanently at any time by entering a new value in this requester.

@{b}Buffers@{ub}

The maximum number of buffers QuickFile will use for holding blocks of records in memory. A buffer is a chunk of RAM used to hold a block of records. QuickFile will try to keep as many blocks in RAM as possible to reduce disk accesses. Performance is much better, particularly with floppy disks, if records can be held in RAM rather than having to be read from disk.

Except for very large databases or limited RAM, using a large number of buffers, such as 100, is recommended. The more of the file in memory, the faster QuickFile works. The memory used is approximately (<number of buffers> * <buffer size>). QuickFile will never use more buffers than are required for the whole file.@{b} Note@{ub} that when using a compression program like XFH-handler with QuickFile, the number of buffers should be a small number, such as 3. XFH will already have the decompressed copy of the file in RAM.

The number of buffers used for a database can be changed permanently at any time by entering a new value in this requester, or temporarily (for the current session only) by selecting @{"BUFFERS" link Buffers} from the OPTIONS menu.
@endnode
@node ExtPath "Default External Path"
@toc DefineFile

The EXTERNAL PATH string gadget, at the lower right of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, is used to specify an optional default path to be used for @{"IMAGE" link Image} and @{"EXTERNAL" link External} fields. This can reduce the necessity of having to store long pathnames in the given field for each record in which it is used. A trailing slash ("/") may be included if applicable, but is not required.

If a relative path (i.e. without a device or volume name and colon) is specified with a filename in an IMAGE or EXTERNAL field, that path is assumed to be relative to the path entered here. If an absolute path is specified, then EXTERNAL PATH is ignored. For example:

  EXTERNAL PATH     = "Examples/Images/ImageData/"

  IMAGE field value = "Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm"
  Accessed as "Examples/Images/ImageData/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm"

  IMAGE field value = "///ImageData/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm"
  Accessed as "ImageData/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm"

  IMAGE field value = "Work:Graphics/Pictures/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm"
  Accessed as "Work:Graphics/Pictures/Fractals/Mandelbrot.ilbm"

@{b}Note@{ub} that if a relative path is specified in EXTERNAL PATH, it is assumed to be relative to the current directory. If EXTERNAL PATH is left empty, all fields are assumed to be relative to the current database's home directory. For example:

  QuickFile current directory = "Work:QuickFile/"
  Database current directory  = "Work:QuickFile/Images"
  IMAGE field value           = "Mandelbrot.ilbm"

  EXTERNAL PATH          = "Images/ImageData/"
  Actual path to file is   "Work:QuickFile/Images/ImageData/Mandelbrot.ilbm"

  EXTERNAL PATH          = [empty]
  Actual path to file is   "Work:QuickFile/Images/Mandelbrot.ilbm"
@endnode
@node Import "Importing Records from a File"
@toc Menus

Selecting IMPORT from the PROJECT menu displays a requester which allows specification of the record and field @{"separator" link Separators} characters used in an ASCII file, so that records may be read from the file and inserted into an existing database. The requester also features a check box for FAST IMPORT. If checked, importing of very large files will be significantly faster, but certain tests on the imported data, such as whether duplicate records are being imported, will not be performed.

Not all fields which have been defined for the database need be present in the input file; however, the sequence and @{"type" link Types} of fields in the file must correspond to those in the current @{"view" link AboutViews}. It may be necessary to @{"define" link New }, @{"load" link Load  } or @{"select" link Views} an appropriate view prior to selecting IMPORT. Any fields not present or empty in the file are left empty in the imported records.@{b} Note@{ub} that QuickFile will not report an error if any @{"mandatory" link FieldReq} fields are left empty while importing.

The length of fields in the file should be less than or equal to the maximum length defined for each respective field. Any field values exceeding their maximum length will be truncated.

@{b}Note@{ub} that a database should be backed up prior to importing records. If the import format is wrong, it is easier to restore the database from the backup than to fix or delete all incorrect records.@{b} Note also@{ub} that a large number of @{"buffers" link IO} should be used when importing many records.
@endnode
@node Separators "Record and Field Separators for Import/Export"
@toc Import

Record and field separators must be specified for records or partial records to be imported from, or exported to, an ASCII file. When @{"IMPORTING" link Import}, they inform QuickFile how to distinguish between separate records and fields in the file. When @{"EXPORTING" link Export}, they determine how the records and fields are separated in the file to be written to.

A choice is provided between PRESET and CUSTOM separator formats. The only PRESET format available for IMPORTING is displayed in the FORMAT listview as ["...",]. This format is for records in which all fields begin and end with double-quote marks, and are separated by commas, as in:

  "John Q.","Public","123 South Main Street","South Pole","Antarctica"

This format is also available for EXPORTING, along with preset mailmerge formats for several Amiga word processing programs (most of which, admittedly, are now rather dated), including:

  FinalCopy
  Interword
  KindWords 3
  ProWrite
  WordWorth

Only the KindWords 3 format has been tested by the (original) author, Alan Wigginton.

To specify a custom format for record and field separators, CUSTOM must first be selected in the FORMAT listview. The cycle gadgets on the right side of the requester may then be used to select the desired combination of separator characters. The available characters are (though not all are available for each type of separator):

  ,     Comma
  ;     Semi-colon
  :     Colon
  '     Single-quote mark
  "     Double-quote mark
  None  No character used
  Tab   A tab character (ASCII 009)
  LF    Line Feed (ASCII 010, the standard Amiga end-of-line character)
  CRLF  Carriage Return (ASCII 013), followed by Line Feed (the standard
        MS-DOS end-of-line characters)

The separator types, controlled by the cycle gadgets, are:

  FIELD START  Designates the start of a field (usually NONE unless fields
               fields are enclosed in quotes). Any of:

    '     Single-quote mark
    "     Double-quote mark
    None  No character

  FIELD END    Designates the end of a field (usually NONE unless fields
               are enclosed in quotes). Any of:

    '     Single-quote mark
    "     Double-quote mark
    None  No character
    Tab   Tab character
    CRLF  Carriage Return-Line Feed

  FIELD SEP    Separates fields in each record; does not appear after the
               last field in a record (usually TAB or COMMA). Any of:

    ,     Comma
    ;     Semi-colon
    :     Colon
    None  No character
    Tab   Tab character
    LF    Line Feed
    CRLF  Carriage Return-Line Feed

  RECORD END   Designates the end of a record (usually LF). Any of:

    None  No character
    LF    Line Feed
    CRLF  Carriage Return-Line Feed

If FIELD START is specified (set to other than NONE), FIELD END must also be specified. If neither FIELD END nor FIELD SEPARATOR is specified, the imported records are of fixed length with each field padded to its maximum length with spaces.

Examples:

  "field1","field2","field3","field4"<LF>

  FIELD START = "
  FIELD END   = "
  FIELD SEP   = ,
  RECORD END  = LF

  field1<TAB>field2<TAB>field3<TAB>field4<TAB><LF>

  FIELD START = NONE
  FIELD END   = NONE
  FIELD SEP   = TAB
  RECORD END  = LF

@{b}Note@{ub} that the same character should@{b} NOT@{ub} be used for both FIELD SEP and RECORD SEP when IMPORTING.
@endnode
@node Export "Exporting Records to a File"
@toc Menus

Selecting EXPORT from the PROJECT menu displays a requester, allowing specification of record and field @{"separator" link Separators} characters. These characters are used in order to write all records in the current @{"index" link AboutIndexes} to an ASCII file, which is typically done to exchange data with other applications such as word processing programs, text editors, other databases, etc.

Which fields are exported, and their sequence and lengths in the export file, are determined by the current @{"view" link AboutViews}. It may be necessary to @{"define" link New }, @{"load" link Load  } or @{"select" link Views} an appropriate view to provide the desired record and field layout for the file prior to selecting EXPORT.

A HEADERS checkbox appears at the upper right of the requester. If checked, field labels used in the current view are also exported at the top of the resulting file.

At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK displays a file requester, with which a path/name may be specified for the export file.
@endnode
@node Reorganise "Reorganizing a Database"
@toc Menus

Selecting REORGANISE from the PROJECT menu allows reorganization of a database by creating a new, optimized version, and then copying it over the original database file. Reorganizing is not necessarily essential, but if many additions and deletions have been made to a database, it can reduce file size and improve performance. During reorganization, @{"free space" link IO} is adjusted to the value specified in the database @{"definition" link DefineFile} and records are physically stored in the sequence of the @{"index" link AboutIndexes} in use. Selecting the most used index prior to reorganization can drastically improve performance with floppies.

If the current index is @{"SORTED" link Sorted} or @{"SELECTED" link Selected}, reorganization cannot take place. Otherwise, a file requester is displayed, in which a filename (and path, if desired) must be specified for the work file that is created during reorganization. By default, a name consisting of the existing database definition filename with the added extension ".Wrk" appears in the requester. The work file is@{b} not@{ub} automatically deleted upon completion of the reorganization, and may be kept as a backup if desired.@{b} Note@{ub} that care should be taken to ensure that other wanted files are not overwritten by the specified name.

After the work filename is specified, another requester displays the current @{"block size" link IO} for the database, which may be changed if desired. This is the only way to modify the block size of an existing database after it has been initially defined.
@endnode
@node Iconify "Iconifying Database Windows"
@toc Menus

Selecting ICONIFY from the PROJECT menu reduces the current database window to a short title bar button. The window can be restored by activating the button and either pressing any key, or clicking the middle (if available) or right mouse button.
@endnode
@node Hide "Hiding Database Windows"
@toc Menus

Selecting HIDE from the PROJECT menu causes the current database window to be hidden. The window can be restored by double-clicking on QuickFile's AppIcon, or by issuing the @{"WINTOFRONT" link WinToFront} macro function.@{b} Note@{ub} that at this time, if more than one database window has been hidden, double-clicking on the AppIcon will restore only the first window hidden. Any other windows can only be restored via WINTOFRONT.
@endnode
@node About "About QuickFile"
@toc Menus

Selecting ABOUT from the PROJECT menu causes a window to be displayed which shows information regarding the current version of QuickFile, the current database window's ARexx port, and available system memory.
@endnode
@node Quit "Quitting QuickFile"
@toc Menus

Selecting QUIT from the PROJECT menu causes a requester to be displayed, asking for confirmation that QuickFile is to close all database windows and quit.
@endnode
@node Views "Selecting a View"
@toc Menus

Selecting VIEWS from the VIEWS menu causes a requester with a listview of all @{"views" link AboutViews} that have been @{"loaded" link Load  } to be displayed. With the exception of the default view, all views must be explicitly loaded from disk in order to be available for selection. If no views have been loaded, a single default view named "[databasename].View" is listed. If a view has already been @{"defined" link New } and @{"saved" link Save As } to disk with that name, it is loaded automatically when the database is loaded.

The view currently in use is highlighted. A different view may be selected with the mouse, or by scrolling through the list with the UP and DOWN arrow keys.

At the bottom of the requester are OK, FREE, ALTER and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK causes the highlighted view to be used and closes the requester, updating the database window display as necessary. A view may also be selected and used in one step by double-clicking on it in the list, which also closes the requester.

Selecting FREE closes the requester and unloads the highlighted view from memory, which may be useful in low RAM situations. At least one view, which need not be the default view, must remain loaded.

Selecting ALTER closes the requester and displays the definition of the highlighted view in the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester for editing.
@endnode
@node New  "Creating a New View"
@toc Menus

Selecting NEW from the VIEWS menu causes the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester to be displayed, in which the desired view fields for a new view, as well as their order and displayed labels and lengths, may be specified.
@endnode
@node DefineView "The DEFINE VIEW Requester"
@toc Menus

The DEFINE VIEW requester is displayed when either NEW or ALTER VIEW is selected from the VIEW menu, or when the ALTER button is selected in the @{"SELECT VIEW" link Views} requester, and is used to create new @{"views" link AboutViews} or modify existing views. If ALTER was selected from the menu, the current view definition is displayed for modification; if the ALTER button in the SELECT VIEW requester, the highlighted view is displayed.

Although views are primarily created using this requester, there are certain aspects of view layout which can only be accomplished with the @{"mouse" link MouseView}. For instance, each field added in the requester is placed on a separate line, while fields may be rearranged using the mouse so that several occupy a line. Also, the size and position of the database window for the current view can only be changed with the mouse.

The requester components are:

@{b}View Name@{ub}

The name of the view, up to 30 characters. When defining new views, the name is "NoBase" by default, and may be changed as desired. For previously defined and @{"saved" link Save As } views, the name is for display only in this requester and cannot be edited. In this case it may be changed only by selecting SAVE AS from the VIEW menu, or by renaming the view definition file from Workbench or Shell.@{b} Note@{ub} that QuickFile accepts views with illegal filename characters in them ('"', ':', '/', '?', etc.), and will happily save them to disk that way.

@{b}Type@{ub}

The type of the view, one of:

  @{"Form" link Form}  Displays one record at a time
  @{"List" link List}  Displays as many records as can fit in the window, one per line

Each type enables certain options and settings when @{"printing" link Current Index}.@{b} Note@{ub} that the view type may also be changed on the fly while viewing records with the @{"FORM/LIST" link FormList} button at the top of the database window.

@{b}Headings@{ub}

If checked, field names are displayed; otherwise not. Having a view without field names displayed may be desired for certain printing operations, such as mailing labels.

@{b}Lock@{ub}

If checked, field positions are locked in this view to prevent the user from accidentally dragging them with the mouse. This should only be unchecked if and when rearrangement of fields with the mouse is desired.

@{b}Available Fields@{ub}

This listview displays all fields that have been @{"defined" link FieldDef} for the database, their @{"types" link Types}, maximum lengths, and whether or not they are @{"calculated" link Calc}.

@{b}View Fields@{ub}

This listview displays all fields used in this view. Fields are added to the list by clicking on their names in the AVAILABLE FIELDS listview on the left with the mouse. If a field is highlighted in the list when a new field is added, the new field is inserted above it. To add a new field to the bottom of the list, "== End ==" should first be highlighted.@{b} Note@{ub} that modifying an existing field's name or length, or deleting it from the database definition, will@{b} not@{ub} automatically adjust the definition of any views that use the field. If a view which uses a particular field that has been renamed or no longer exists is loaded, QuickFile displays a requester notifying the user that the field could not be located.

@{b}Name@{ub}

The displayed name for the highlighted field for this view only. By default, this is the same as the actual field name when the field is added to the VIEW FIELDS list, but may be different, or even blank. @{b} Note@{ub} that TAB or RETURN@{b} must@{ub} be pressed on the keyboard after a view field name has been modified, otherwise the modifications are ignored.

@{b}Length@{ub}

The displayed length for the highlighted field for this view only. By default, this is the same as the actual field length when the field is added to the VIEW FIELDS list, and may be different, but must be at least 1.@{b} Note@{ub} that TAB or RETURN@{b} must@{ub} be pressed on the keyboard after a view field length has been modified, otherwise the modifications are ignored.

@{b}Delete@{ub}

If selected, the highlighted field (if any) is deleted from the VIEW FIELDS list. No confirmation is asked. The DELETE button is ghosted if no view fields is highlighted in the list.

@{b}Clear@{ub}

If selected, all fields are deleted from the VIEW FIELDS list. No confirmation is asked.


At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK causes the new or modified view to be used and closes the requester.@{b} Note@{ub} that the view is not automatically @{"saved" link Save  } to disk.
@endnode
@node Form "Form Views"
@toc DefineView

The FORM view format displays a single record in the database window in the format specified by the current view @{"definition" link DefineView}. If there are more @{"fields" link Fields} in the view than will fit in the window, the horizontal scroll bar can be used to access the additional fields.

By default, one field is displayed per single line, with no blank lines in between, with the exception of @{"IMAGE" link Image} fields, which occupy two lines by default. View field sequence, positions and lengths can be modifed within the window by dragging the fields or their sizing gadgets with the @{"mouse" link MouseView}.@{b} Note@{ub} that although view field heights can be changed, only IMAGE fields can actually use more than a single line. If present, image display may be toggled on and off with the @{"IMAGES" link ImageToggle} checkbox at the top of window. When image display is off, the path/names for the image files are displayed.

@{"EXTERNAL" link External} fields are displayed with an @{"R" link RunCommand} button to the left of them. Selecting the button runs the command @{"defined" link FieldReq} for the field.

The @{"FORM/LIST" link FormList} button at the top of the window may be used to quickly toggle between FORM and @{"LIST" link List} view formats, without altering the actual view definition.
@endnode
@node List "List Views"
@toc DefineView

The LIST view format displays as many records as will fit in the database window, one line per record. If the view record length, which is the sum of all view field lengths, is wider than the window, the horizontal scroll bar may be used to scroll left or right. View field sequence and lengths can only be modified via the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester.

@{"IMAGE" link Image} fields only display the path/names for the image files in LIST views, regardless of the status of the @{"IMAGES" link ImageToggle} checkbox at the top of the window. @{"EXTERNAL" link External} fields are displayed without the @{"R" link RunCommand} button that enables running the command @{"defined" link FieldReq} for the field.

When records are @{"inserted or modified" link InsertModify} while in LIST view, the display switches to a @{"FORM" link Form} view in edit mode. A record may be modified by selecting the MODIFY button when the desired record is displayed at the top of the window, clicking once on the record with the mouse and then selecting MODIFY, or by simply double-clicking on the record. To delete a record, it must be clicked on once with the mouse prior to selecting the @{"DELETE" link Delete} button.

The @{"FORM/LIST" link FormList} button at the top of the database window may be used to quickly toggle between LIST and FORM view formats, without altering the actual view definition.
@endnode
@node MouseView "Using the Mouse to Fine-Tune Views"

The default @{"view" link AboutViews} for any database is a @{"FORM" link Form} view displaying all @{"fields" link Fields}, with one field per line, in a 640x256 window. If this is not satisfactory, views may be customized and @{"saved" link Save As } to disk. Views are primarily defined and customized via the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester; however, certain aspects of view layout can be modified only with the mouse.

Window position and size may be set for each view as usual, by dragging the window title bar and/or sizing gadget.

If the current view is a FORM view and the LOCKED checkbox is not checked in the DEFINE VIEW requester for it, each field may be selected for manipulation by clicking on it with the mouse. The field will then be outlined with a box, and can be dragged to a different position in the window. This method allows the placement of several fields on the same line in the view, while the DEFINE VIEW requester does not.

In the lower right hand corner of the outline box is a sizing gadget for the field, which, if the mouse is clicked and held over, causes the mouse pointer to become a set of connected arrows. The length and height of the field can be changed by dragging the gadget around. @{b}Note@{ub} that although the height of any field type can be increased, only @{"IMAGE" link Image} fields can actually utilize more than a single line.

The window and field positions and sizes are part of the view definition, and are saved with it if the view is saved. It is best to use the DEFINE VIEW requester first to set the order of fields, then adjust the view with the mouse.
@endnode
@node Load   "Loading a View"
@toc Menus

Selecting LOAD VIEW from the VIEW menu displays a file requester, with which @{"view" link AboutViews} files may be selected and loaded from disk. Multi-select is not available in the requester; only one view may be loaded at a time.

By default, the requester displays only files with the default filename extension for QuickFile views, which is ".View". However, view files may have any name; if views exist with non-standard names, clearing the requester's pattern string will make them become visible.

When a view is loaded, it becomes the current view and the database window display changes accordingly. If @{"fields" link Fields} existing in the @{"view" link DefineView} definition cannot be located in the @{"database" link DefineFile} definition, a requester is displayed to notify the user that fields are missing. This can be expected if fields have been deleted, or field names have been modified. The view definition is not automatically modified to reflect the missing views.

Fields in the view and database definitions are associated by name. If a view file for a database other than the current one is loaded, only those fields which have the same name in both databases will be displayed.
@endnode
@node Save   "Saving a View"
@toc Menus

Selecting SAVE VIEW from the VIEW menu saves the current @{"view" link AboutViews} to disk, whether any modifications have been made or not. If the current view does not yet exist as a disk file, a file requester is displayed to confirm the name. The default name appears in the requester as the name given the view when it was @{"defined" link DefineView}, with the extension ".View" (if not already specified in the definition, and if the name is 23 characters or less).@{b} Note@{ub} that view files are not required to have the ".View" filename extension. They may have any legal filename.

The size and position of view fields and database display windows are saved with the views.
@endnode
@node Save As  "Saving a View with a New Name"
@toc Menus

Selecting SAVE VIEW AS from the VIEW menu displays a file requester with which to specify a new filename to save the current @{"view" link AboutViews} as. By default, the name of the current view appears in the requester, with the extension ".View" if it was not already specified when the view was defined.@{b} Note@{ub} that view files are not required to have the ".View" filename extension. They may have any legal filename.
@endnode
@node Alter  "Altering a View"
@toc Menus

Selecting ALTER from the VIEWS menu causes the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester to be displayed, in which the desired view fields, as well as their order and displayed labels and lengths, may be modified for the current view.
@endnode
@node Reset form "Resetting Field Positions in a Form View"
@toc Menus

Selecting RESET FORM from the VIEW menu resets all @{"field" link Fields} positions for the current view to the default positions, and affects @{"FORM" link Form} views only. Each field in the view is displayed on a separate line, with no blank lines between them. Field sequence is maintained and the @{"LIST" link FormList} display is not affected. This may be useful if fields have been added or deleted from a view, which may result in large gaps or overlapping fields in the display.
@endnode
@node Indexes "Selecting an Index"
@toc Menus

Selecting INDEXES from the ORDER menu displays a requester listing all available @{"indexes" link AboutIndexes} for the current database. The list includes the temporary index @{"SELECTED" link Selected}, regardless of whether any records are currently selected. It may also include the temporary index @{"SORTED" link Sorted} if the database has been custom-sorted during the current session.

The index currently in use is highlighted. A different index may be selected with the mouse, or by scrolling through the list with the UP and DOWN arrow keys.

At the bottom of the requester are OK, FREE and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK causes the highlighted index to be used and closes the requester. An index may also be selected and used in one step by double-clicking on it in the list, which also closes the requester.

Either of the temporary indexes SORTED (if listed) and/or SELECTED may be purged from memory by selecting it in the list, and then selecting the FREE button.@{b} Note@{ub} that freeing the SELECTED index de-selects all records that were selected, but does not remove the index name from the list. If SELECTED is made the current index when no records are selected, a blank record is displayed.

The permanent indexes, of which there must remain at least one, may only be modified or deleted via the @{"INDEXES" link IndexDef} panel on the right side of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester.
@endnode
@node Sorted "SORTED Index"
@toc Indexes

SORTED is the name of a temporary @{"index" link AboutIndexes} created when a database is @{"custom-sorted" link Sort index}. If the database is re-sorted again in the same session, the previous SORTED index is replaced by a new one. The index can be purged from memory from within the @{"SELECT INDEX" link Indexes} requester.
@endnode
@node Selected "SELECTED Index"
@toc Indexes

SELECTED is the name of a temporary @{"index" link AboutIndexes} that is created when a database is loaded. It consists of all database records that have been selected, usually the results of a @{"query" link Queries}. Records may also be selected @{"manually" link Toggle Record}.

SELECTED becomes the current index after one of these actions:

  - Automatically upon completion of a query
  - If selected from within the @{"SELECT INDEX" link Indexes} requester
  - If @{"SHOW SELECTED RECORDS" link Show Selected Records} is selected from the SELECTION menu
  - If SELECTED is not already the current index, and the @{"ALL/SEL" link AllSel} button
    at the top of the database window is selected.

If no records have been selected and SELECTED is made the current index, a blank record is displayed.

While SELECTED is the current index, it is automatically updated as records are @{"modified" link InsertModify} or @{"deleted" link Delete}.@{b} Note@{ub} that if a record in the SELECTED index has been modified so that it no longer matches the criteria of the query that placed it there, it is not automatically de-selected. Therefore it is continued to be displayed in the index, though its position in the index may change if any of the permanent index field values were modifed.@{b} Note also@{ub} that any new records @{"inserted" link InsertModify} are not automatically selected, and therefore are not displayed in the index.

When a database is first opened, the SELECTED index exists, but is empty, as no records have been selected and no queries performed yet. Records may be added to or removed from the index by manually selecting or de-selecting them. But every time a new query is performed, the records that were previously selected are replaced in the index by the results of the new query, which may be none if no matching records were found.

The contents of the SELECTED index may be purged from within the SELECT INDEX requester. The name will continue to appear in the index list after being purged, but it will contain no records until one or more are again selected, either manually or via a query.
@endnode
@node Sort Index "The Sort Requester"
@toc Menus

The SORT requester is displayed when SORT INDEX is selected from the ORDER menu, and when the ORDER button is selected from within the @{"QUERY" link Query} requester. It is nearly identical to the @{"INDEX" link IndexReq} requester, except that the name of the @{"index" link AboutIndexes} is SORTED and cannot be modified, and the index may not be made unique.

Performing a custom sort creates a temporary index named @{"SORTED" link Sorted} and makes it the current index. The SORTED index is updated automatically as records are inserted, deleted and modified. The index is discarded when the database is closed, but until then it will not be necessary to re-sort in order to have new or modified records displayed in the desired sequence.

Any number of fields may be utilized for a single sort. If a sort is performed while @{"SELECTED" link Selected} is the current index, only the selected records will be sorted and displayed.

The technique used for sorting requires that all sort fields are resident in memory, so record buffers may be freed to increase the memory available to perform the sort. Disk activity will likely increase after a sort as buffers are reloaded. If RAM availability is a concern, it may help to sort using less than the full length of long fields.

See the @{"INDEX" link IndexReq} requester section for further details.
@endnode
@node Show Sorted "Show Sorted"
@toc Menus

Selecting SHOW SORTED from the ORDER menu causes @{"SORTED" link Sorted} (if it exists) to become the current @{"index" link AboutIndexes}. SORTED is a temporary index created when a database is @{"custom-sorted" link Sort index} into a sequence other that those specified by the permanent indexes defined for it, and it becomes the current index at that time. If another index is later @{"selected" link Indexes} for use, this menu item may be used to quickly return to SORTED.
@endnode
@node Rebuild Index "Rebuilding the Current Index"
@toc Menus

Selecting REBUILD INDEX from the ORDER menu item causes the current @{"index" link AboutIndexes} to be rebuilt from the data file. This may become necessary if the index and data file are inconsistent for some reason (e.g. a system failure). Rebuilding the index is recommended if QuickFile notifies the user with a "Block not found" message, or any message to the effect that QuickFile could not find a record it searched for.
@endnode
@node Query "The Query Requester"
@toc Menus

Selecting QUERY from the SELECTION menu causes the QUERY requester to be displayed. With this requester, the user may specify multiple criteria to search for in database records, and have the matching records displayed in a temporary @{"index" link AboutIndexes} named @{"SELECTED" link Selected}. The selected records may also optionally be custom-sorted into a sequence other than that of the default permanent index, which will be the sequence used if no custom sort sequence is specified, even if a different permanent index is in use when the query is initiated. The query may be performed on all database records, or only on those matched by a previous query (if any). Commonly-performed queries may be saved to, and loaded from disk, if desired.

The requester is composed of the following items:

@{b}Records@{ub}

A cycle gadget which determines whether the query is to be performed on ALL records in the database, or only on previously SELECTED records, if any.

@{b}Order@{ub}

Selecting this button causes the @{"SORT" link Sort index} requester to be displayed, with which a custom sort sequence may be specified for the results of the query.@{b} Note@{ub} that if no sequence is specified, the results of the query is sorted in the order determined by the default permanent index and not necessarily the index in use when the query is started.

@{b}Criteria@{ub}

An unnamed listview which appears in the center of the requester, in which specified search criteria are displayed. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected criteria set, if any.

@{b}New@{ub}

Selecting this button causes the FIELD @{"SELECTION" link CriteriaReq} DETAILS requester to be displayed, in which a new set of search criteria may be specified. If an existing criteria set is highlighted in the CRITERIA listview when the button is selected, the new criteria set is inserted above it.

@{b}Modify@{ub}

Selecting this button with an existing criteria set highlighted in the CRITERIA listview causes the highlighted criteria set to be displayed in the FIELD SELECTION DETAILS requester for modification.

@{b}Delete@{ub}

Selecting this button causes the highlighted criteria set, if any, to be deleted from the criteria list. No confirmation is asked.

@{b}Load@{ub}

Selecting this button causes a file requester to be displayed, with which a previously defined and saved query may be selected to load from disk. By default, the pattern string for the requester is "#?.qry"; however, saved queries may have any filename.@{b} Note@{ub} that the criteria sets specified in the loaded query replace any and all criteria sets currently in the criteria list.

@{b}Save@{ub}

Selecting this button causes a file requester to be displayed, with which a filename may be specified to save all criteria sets currently in the criteria list, and sort sequence (if specified), to disk. By default, the pattern string for the requester is "#?.qry"; however, queries to be saved may have any filename.


At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK begins the query. When completed, the matching records are placed in a temporary index named @{"SELECTED" link Selected}, which then becomes the current index.
@endnode
@node CriteriaReq "Field Selection Details Requester"
@toc Query

The FIELD SELECTION DETAILS requester is displayed when either the NEW or the MODIFY button is selected in the @{"QUERY" link Query} requester. If NEW was selected, a new search criteria set may be specified. If MODIFY was selected while an existing criteria set is highlighted in the CRITERIA listview in the QUERY requester, the highlighted set definition is displayed for modification.

The requester is composed of the following items:

@{b}Logic@{ub}

Mutually exclusive buttons labelled AND and OR, only available for criteria sets listed after the first one in the QUERY requester when multiple sets have been defined; which button is depressed determines how the current the current criteria set is to be considered in conjunction with the one listed above it as shown below:

  AND  Both criteria sets must be satisfied for a record to be matched
  OR   Either criteria set must be satisfied for a record to be matched

If more than two criteria sets are defined, using a variety of AND and OR logic, certain precedence rules apply. The list of criteria sets is separated into groups at OR criteria sets. For example:

  Group 1       [Criteria set 1] (first in list)
           AND  [Criteria set 2]
           AND  [Criteria set 3]

  Group 2   OR  [Criteria set 4]
           AND  [Criteria set 5]

  Group 3   OR  [Criteria set 6]

Records are matched in this case if all criteria sets in group 1 OR group 2 OR group 3 are satisfied.

Each new criteria set added to the list after the first becomes OR by default, unless changed by the user.@{b} Note@{ub} that if a new criteria set is inserted at the top of the list, the one that was first before the new one was inserted will now have logic, which will be OR by default.

@{b}Available Fields@{ub}

A listview displaying all fields defined for the current database. The highlighted field will be searched for the search strings during the query. By default, the field at the top of the list is selected when the requester is opened for new criteria to be specified. A different field may be selected with the mouse, or by scrolling through the list using the UP and DOWN arrow keys.

@{b}Operator@{ub}

The @{"operator" link MatchOp} used, which determines how the search field is to be matched. The available operators and their corresponding matching methods are:

  @{u}Operator    @{uu}  @{u}Matches Field Values...                                @{uu}
  Like          Containing either search value anywhere within it
  Equal         Equal to either search value
  Between       Equal to or between VALUE 1 and VALUE 2
  Sounds Like   Whose first word sounds like either search value
  Not Like      NOT containing either search value anywhere within it
  Not Equal     NOT equal to either search value

@{b}Value 1@{ub}

The primary value to search the selected field for; may be left empty to search for empty fields.

Case is always ignored in queries. If case-sensitive matching of strings in records is desired, a @{"macro" link Macros} should be used.

For @{"FLOATING" link Types}, @{"DATE" link DateField} and @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields, search strings may be entered in any of the formats that are acceptable for entering data in the fields themselves.

@{b}Value 2@{ub}

A secondary value to search the selected field for; required for BETWEEN searches and optional (ignored if left empty) for use with all other operators. The word AND or OR is displayed between VALUE 1 and VALUE 2 in the requester, depending on which operator is selected. AND is used with BETWEEN, NOT LIKE and NOT EQUAL; OR is used with all others.


Examples:

      Occupation EQUAL    "programmer"
  AND City       EQUAL    "sydney"
  OR  Occupation EQUAL    "programmer"
  AND City       EQUAL    "paris"

These criteria will find all programmers who live in Sydney or in Paris. Note that OCCUPATION had to be repeated, due to the grouping by OR criteria; however, the same result could also be achieved by entering search strings in VALUE 1 and VALUE 2 as follows:

      Occupation EQUAL    "programmer"
  AND City       EQUAL    "sydney" OR "paris"

The following will find all programmers who live in Sydney, and EVERBODY who lives in Paris:

      Occupation EQUAL    "programmer"
  AND City       EQUAL    "sydney"
  OR  City       EQUAL    "paris"

The following will find all persons named John, except those named John Smith:

      FirstName  EQUAL    "john"
  AND LastName   NOTEQUAL "smith"
@endnode
@node MatchOp "Search Operators"
@toc CriteriaReq

The six search operators, available for use in the FIELD @{"SELECTION" link CriteriaReq} DETAILS requester, and with the @{"NEWSEARCH" link NEWSEARCH} and @{"ADDSEARCH" link ADDSEARCH} macro functions, are explained here in more detail with examples.@{b} Note@{ub} that case is always ignored in searches.@{b} Note also@{ub} that when searching in @{"FLOAT" link Types}, @{"DATE" link DateField} or @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields with any of the operators except SOUNDS LIKE, search strings may be entered in any of the alternate formats that are acceptable for data entry in the fields.

@{b}Like@{ub}

Matches fields that contain either search string anywhere within them.

  @{u}Search String@{uu}  @{u}Field Type@{uu}  @{u}Matches                                     @{uu}
  "bit"          CHARACTER   "The Hobbit", "Bitter", "two bits", etc.
  "3:5:6"        TIME        "03:05:06"

@{b}Not Like@{ub}

Matches fields that DO NOT contain either search string anywhere within them (opposite of LIKE).

@{b}Equal@{ub}

Matches fields only if they equal either search value (except for case).

  @{u}Search String@{uu}  @{u}Field Type@{uu}  @{u}Matches                                     @{uu}
  "dog"          CHARACTER   "Dog", "dog", "DOG", "dOg", etc.
  "17-3-00"      DATE        "17-Mar-2000"

@{b}Not Equal@{ub}

Matches fields that DO NOT equal either search value (opposite of EQUAL).

@{b}Between@{ub}

Matches fields whose values are equal to, or are between, the search values. Intended mainly for use with INTEGER, FLOAT, DATE and TIME @{"fields" link Types}, but may also be used with the other types, in which case string comparisons are performed.

  @{u}Search Strings    @{uu}  @{u}Field Type@{uu}  @{u}Matches                                 @{uu}
  "0", "6"            INTEGER     "0", "1", "2", "3", "4", "5", "6"
  "a", "cf"           CHARACTER   "a", "A ", "book", "Center", etc.
  "1-1-00", "1-2-00"  DATE        "01-Jan-2000" through "01-Feb-2000"

@{b}Sounds Like@{ub}

Matches fields in which the first word sounds like either search string. This is a bit of a gimmick and is far from perfected, but may be useful. A version of the old soundex technique is utilized, which requires that the first character is known, and has a number of other limitations.@{b} Note@{ub} especially that only the first word of field values are considered.

  @{u}Search String@{uu}  @{u}Field Type@{uu}  @{u}Matches                                     @{uu}
  "character"    CHARACTER   "Chapter", "Chronicle", "Chicago", etc.
  "the"          CHARACTER   "The", "This", "Thinking", "Two", etc.
  "we"           CHARACTER   "we", "why", "who", etc.
  "smith"        CHARACTER   "Smith", "Smyth", "Smythe", etc.
@endnode
@node Toggle Record "Toggling the Selection of Individual Records"
@toc Menus

Selecting TOGGLE RECORD from the SELECTION menu adds the current record to the @{"SELECTED" link Selected} index, if the current index is one other than SELECTED. If SELECTED is the current index, the current record is removed from it. If the current record is already selected, but SELECTED is not the current index, nothing happens. A message reflecting which action was performed is displayed in the title bar of the database window.

In @{"FORM" link Form} views, the current record is the one displayed in the database window. In a @{"LIST" link List} view, the current record is the one highlighted, or the first (topmost) record in the window if none are highlighted.
@endnode
@node Show Selected Records "Showing Selected Records"
@toc Menus

Selecting SHOW SELECTED RECORDS from the SELECTION menu causes the temporary index named @{"SELECTED" link Selected}, consisting of all currently selected records, to become the current index. Records which have been selected are usually the results of a @{"query" link Query}, but may also have been selected @{"manually" link Toggle Record}. If there are no records currently selected, a blank record is displayed.

@{b}Note@{ub} that the current index can also be toggled between SELECTED and the current permanent index in use via the @{"ALL/SEL" link AllSel} button at the top of the database window.
@endnode
@node Show All Records "Showing All Records"
@toc Menus

Selecting SHOW ALL RECORDS from the SELECTION menu causes the most recent permanent index in use to become the current index, if it is not already. This is usually used to switch from the temporary index @{"SELECTED" link SELECTED}, which holds all currently selected records.

@{b}Note@{ub} that the current index can also be toggled between SELECTED and the current permanent index in use via the @{"ALL/SEL" link AllSel} button at the top of the database window.
@endnode
@node Displayed Records "Printing Displayed Records"
@toc Menus

Selecting DISPLAYED RECORDS from the PRINT menu allows the printing of all records currently displayed in the database window. For @{"FORM" link Form} views, this is always a single record. The @{"PRINT" link PRINT} requester is displayed to allow customization of the printed output.
@endnode
@node Current Index "Printing All Records in the Current Index"
@toc Menus

Selecting CURRENT INDEX from the PRINT menu allows the printing of all records in the current index. The @{"PRINT" link PRINT} requester is displayed to allow customization of the printed output.
@endnode
@node Print "The Print Requester"
@toc Menus

The PRINT requester is displayed when either DISPLAYED RECORDS or CURRENT INDEX is selected from the PRINT menu. DISPLAYED RECORDS allows printing of all records currently displayed in the database window, which is always a single record for @{"FORM" link Form} views. CURRENT INDEX allows printing of all records in the current index in sequence.

Several of the settings available in this requester are identical to settings available in Workbench's Printer preference program, are by default set to the same values as Workbench, and are indicated as such below. Changing any of these values does not affect the Workbench settings.

Apart from the settings available in this requester, what is printed and how it is printed can also be affected by the current view. Only those @{"fields" link Fields} included in the current view are printed; view field labels are only printed for the fields if the LABELS box is checked in the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester. Additionally, certain settings are only available for FORM views, and certain other settings only for @{"LIST" link List} views. It may be necessary to create and customize a view specifically to achieve the desired printing results. The settings used here are specific to the current view, and are saved with it if and when the view is saved.

The requester components are:

@{b}Title@{ub}

An optional title for the printed report. If used, it is automatically centered between the left and right margins set below, and the current system date is also printed on the title line at the left margin, and page number at the right margin. This line is printed even if only a single space character is entered here.@{b} Note@{ub} that if the distance between the left and right margins is not wide enough to accommodate the title entered, date and page number, the line may be garbled.

@{b}Left Margin@{ub}

Same as Workbench.@{b} Note@{ub}, however, that QuickFile requires this value to be greater than 0, although 0 is an acceptable value for Workbench.

@{b}Right Margin@{ub}

Same as Workbench; must be greater than that for the left margin.

@{b}Lines/Page@{ub}

How many lines QuickFile should print on each page, which by default is equal to:

  (<prefs_page_height> x <prefs_line_spacing>) - 8

This allows for top and bottom margins of four lines each. QuickFile sends a Form Feed after each set of this many lines (unless the OUTPUT TO setting, below, is WINDOW or FILE), which may be a limitation with some printers. Please contact the @{"author" link Author} if any problems are encountered.

Entering a value of 0 here causes the title line and Form Feeds to be suppressed.

@{b}Spacing@{ub}

Same as Workbench; ignored if OUTPUT TO, below, is set to WINDOW or FILE. Available values are 6 and 8 LPI.

@{b}Pitch@{ub}

Same as Workbench; ignored if OUTPUT TO, below, is set to WINDOW or FILE. Available values (also shown in characters per inch) are:

  @{u}Setting@{uu}  @{u}CPI  @{uu}
  Pica     10
  Elite    12
  Fine     15-17

The numbers shown in parenthesis next to PICA and ELITE in the requester indicate how many characters fit on an eight inch line for that pitch.

@{b}Output To@{ub}

A cycle gadget which is used to specify a destination for the printed report. Available settings are:

  PRT:

The Workbench preferences printer.

  File

An ASCII file. A file requester will be displayed to specify a desired path and name when printing is started.

  Window

The database window. Print data will temporarily replace display of database records in the window, with OK and CANCEL buttons provided. Horizontal and vertical scrolling are not available. Lines are truncated at the right edge of the window, if necessary. If there is more data to be printed than fits in the window vertically, selecting the OK button, or pressing RETURN, causes the next windowful of data to be dsiplayed; otherwise display of database records resumes.

If set to WINDOW or FILE, the settings for SPACING and PITCH are ignored.

@{b}View Line Length@{ub}

An informational line which calculates and displays the sum of all view field lengths, plus an additional space between fields, for @{"LIST" link List} views only. If the value is greater than the print width (<RIGHT MARGIN> - <LEFT MARGIN>), and WRAP FIELDS is not checked in the @{"GROUPS" link Groups} panel (described below), printed lines will be truncated at the right margin.

@{b}View Type Settings@{ub}

The panel displayed on the right side of the PRINT requester depends on whether the current view is a FORM or LIST view, and offers settings that are only available for one or the other. These are:

  Setting  View
  @{u} Panel @{uu}  @{u}Type @{uu}  @{u}Controls printing of...                         @{uu}
  @{"Labels" link Labels}  @{"FORM" link Form}  Records in multiple rows and columns
  @{"Groups" link Groups}  @{"LIST" link List}  Advanced reports and field summaries


At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK begins the printing process and closes the PRINT requester.
@endnode
@node Labels "Label Settings Panel"
@toc Print

The LABELS settings panel is displayed on the right side of the @{"PRINT" link Print} requester if the current view is a @{"FORM" link Form} view. It may be necessary to create a view specifically for label printing to obtain the desired results. Ordinarily, the HEADINGS checkbox should be left unchecked in the @{"DEFINE VIEW" link DefineView} requester for label printing, the fields should be arranged in the upper left corner of the view. Also, LINES/PAGE, on the left side of the PRINT requester, should be set to 0 for label printing, to supress QuickFile from sending Form Feeds during printing.

The following items may be configured in the panel, all of which may be set to 0 to print a single column of labels, using the number of lines used in the current view as the LABEL HEIGHT:

@{b}Across@{ub}

The number of columns of labels to fit on a page.@{b} Note@{ub} that this value, WIDTH (explained below) and the print width (<rightmargin> - <leftmargin>) are all mutually dependent upon each other, in that ((<across> x <width>) + (<across> - 1)) must be less than or equal to the print width.

@{b}Width@{ub}

The width (in number of characters) of each label column. One or more spaces is added between columns; increasing this value increases the number of spaces added.@{b} See note@{ub} for LABELS ACROSS, above, regarding limitations of this value.

@{b}Down@{ub}

The number of labels to print in one column before proceeding to the next column. For example:

  @{u}Settings  @{uu}  @{u}Printed Sequence@{uu}
  ACROSS = 3    1    5    9
  DOWN   = 4    2    6   10
                3    7   11
                4    8   12

               13   17   21
               14   18   22
               15   19   23
               16   20   24
               [etc.]

  @{u}Settings  @{uu}  @{u}Printed Sequence@{uu}
  ACROSS = 3    1    2    3
  DOWN   = 1    4    5    6
                7    8    9
               10   11   12
               [etc.]

@{b}Height@{ub}

The height (in number of lines) of each label. An additional blank line is added between labels in a column. If set to 0, the number of lines in the current view is used.@{b} Note@{ub} that if this is set to a value greater than 0 but less than the number of lines in the view, labels will overlap.
@endnode
@node Groups "Groups Panel"
@toc Print

The GROUPS panel is displayed on the right side of the @{"PRINT" link Print} requester if the current view is a @{"LIST" link List} view. In it, fields may be organized into REPORT GROUPS (also known as CONTROL BREAKS), which enables advanced control over how records are printed. GROUP fields are only printed when their values change, allowing a hierarchical structure to be established for the resulting report. Each group may include several fields, but normally only one field is used per group.

Summary values may also be calculated and printed for multiple fields with each group.

@{b}Note@{ub} that records must be @{"sorted" link Sort index} correctly in order to acheive the desired result with GROUP printing. Generally, sorting should be done by the fields that make up the groups, with those of the higher-level groups used first.

The panel has the following components:

@{b}Groups@{ub}

A listview displaying all currently defined groups and their corresponding types.

@{b}Add@{ub}

If selected, causes the @{"GROUP DETAILS" link GrpReq} requester to be displayed so that a new group can be defined. New groups are inserted into the GROUPS listview above whichever group is currently highlighted, if any.@{b} Note@{ub} that certain restrictions apply to how the different group types may be used in combination with each other, and are explained fully with the GROUP DETAILS requester.

@{b}Modify@{ub}

If selected, causes the GROUP DETAILS requester to be displayed with the definition of the existing group that is highlighted in the GROUPS listview, if any, for modification.

@{b}Delete@{ub}

If selected, the currently highlighted group in the listview above, if any, is discarded without further confirmation.

@{b}Summary Only@{ub}

If checked, only total and sub-total summary lines are printed for the highlighted group. The group field values are printed with the summary values for the group.@{b} Note@{ub} that a group of type REPORT must be defined for this to function. See the AddressBook example database and Demo.quickfile @{"macro" link Macros}.@{b} Note also@{ub} that an extra 4 characters are added at the start of each summary line printed for the summary type as defined in the GROUP DETAILS requester.

@{b}Wrap Fields@{ub}

If checked, lines that are longer than the print width (<rightmargin> - <leftmargin>) are wrapped, at word boundaries if possible, to succeeding lines as necessary in the printed report.
@endnode
@node GrpReq "Group Details Requester"
@toc Groups

The GROUP DETAILS requester is displayed when either the ADD or MODIFY button is selected in the @{"GROUPS" link Groups} panel at the right of the @{"PRINT" link Print} requester, and is used to define and modify report groups. It is composed of the following items:

@{b}Group@{ub}

A name for the group, which is printed on summary lines.

@{b}Type@{ub}

The group type. Available types and their corresponding uses are:

  Report

Allows SUMMARIES (see below) to be generated for the entire report. No GROUP fields (see below) are defined for this type of group. If used, must be the first group listed in the GROUPS panel listview.

  Page

A new page is started each time the GROUP fields values change. GROUP fields are printed before column headings.

  Subtitle

GROUP fields are printed on a separate line each time their values change. Reduces line length, and works best when the same value is used in a field in a large number of records.

  Standard

GROUP field values are printed only on the first line for each change they change.

See the Report Group @{"examples" link GrpExample} for a demonstration of usage of the various types.

Multiple levels of GROUPS of the same type may be defined, but those defined for higher-order index fields must be listed above those for lower-order fields in the GROUPS panel listview.

@{b}View Fields@{ub}

A listview displaying all the fields that are included in the current view. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected VIEW field.

@{b}Group Fields@{ub}

A listview displaying all VIEW fields that are to be used in the current group. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected GROUP field. A new group begins in the resulting report when the value of any of these fields change.@{b} Note@{ub} that no GROUP fields are required, or allowed, for a REPORT group.

Below the listview are INSERT and DELETE buttons. Selecting INSERT causes the selected VIEW field to be inserted into the list, above the selected GROUP field, if any.

Selecting DELETE causes the selected GROUP field to be removed from the list without further confirmation.

@{b}Summaries@{ub}

A listview displaying all SUMMARY fields (fields to be summarized in the printed report) for the current group. Below the listview are INSERT and DELETE buttons, which function the same as for GROUP FIELDS. Below the buttons are checkboxes for the available summary types. The status of the checkboxes determine which type(s) of summaries are to be printed for the highlighted SUMMARY field. The types are:

  Tot (total)

The sum of all values for the selected field for each different GROUP field value, or for ALL records if the group type is REPORT.

  Cnt (count)

The number of records for each different GROUP field value, or ALL records for REPORT groups.

  Avg (average)

The average of all values for the selected field for each different GROUP field value, or ALL records for REPORT groups.

More than one box may be checked for each SUMMARY field; however, TOT and AVG may only be used with @{"FLOAT" link Float}, @{"INTEGER" link Integer} and @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields, while CNT may be used with any field @{"type" link Types}.

Each summary type checked is printed on a separate line, with a label (Tot, Cnt or Avg) at the beginning of the line. The name of the group the summary is defined for is printed after the type label, but only for the first summary printed for the group.@{b} Note@{ub} that field order in the current view may need to be rearranged for summaries to be printed correctly. Summary fields should be arranged so that they are NOT printed first or near the beginning of lines, as there may not be room for their summary values to be printed in the summary lines. See the @{"examples" link GrpExample}.@{b} Note also@{ub} that it is inadvisable, though possible, to use GROUP fields as SUMMARY fields when the GROUP type is PAGE or SUB-TITLE, as the summary values will not be printed in positions corresponding to the field values in this case.

At the bottom of the requester are OK and CANCEL buttons. Selecting OK accepts the new or modified group, closes the GROUP DETAILS requester and reopens the PRINT requester, updating the information displayed in the GROUPS panel as necessary.
@endnode
