@node Direct Macro "DIRECT MACRO requester"
@toc Menus

Selecting DIRECT MACRO from the MACROS menu causes the DIRECT MACRO requester to be displayed. Any string of QuickFile @{"functions" link Functions} and/or @{"operations" link MacroOps} may be executed by entering it in the string gadget and selecting OK.@{b} Note@{ub} that ARexx instructions and functions may not be used here, and that ARexx need not be active for DIRECT @{"macros" link Macros}, unless the QuickFile @{"CALL" link Call} function is used to launch an ARexx script.

Selecting the arrow button to the right of the string gadget in the requester causes a listview requester of all available QuickFile macro functions and their templates for usage to be displayed. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected function. Selecting OK causes the selected function and its template to be inserted into the string gadget.
@endnode
@node ARexx Script "AREXX SCRIPT requester"
@toc Menus

Selecting AREXX SCRIPT from the MACROS menu causes the AREXX MACRO requester to be displayed. An ARexx script may be executed by entering its name in the string gadget and selecting OK. The path for the macro need not be specified in the string if it resides within a directory named "ARexx" that is within QuickFile's current directory. If a relative path is specified, it is assumed to be relative to the current directory, rather than to the "ARexx" directory. The filename extension of the script need not be specified if it is ".quickfile".

Selecting the FILE button causes a file requester to be displayed, with which a script may be selected for execution. By default, the path of the requester is the "Arexx" directory. The specified script, if valid, is launched as soon as OK is selected.

AREXX MACRO is disabled if "rexxsyslib.library" is not available in LIBS:. RexxMast must also have already been run prior to running a macro.
@endnode
@node Define Macros "Configuring the MACROS Menu"
@toc Menus

Selecting DEFINE MACROS from the MACROS menu causes the MACROS DEFINITION requester to be displayed, with which up to ten @{"macros" link Macros} may be configured to be accessible from the menu and keyboard for each database, and for empty database windows. The requester has the following components:

@{b}Menu Title@{ub}

Ten string gadgets in which to specify menu labels, which are required, for all configured macros. The labels are limited to 19 characters in length, and may not contain any spaces.

@{b}Command@{ub}

Ten string gadgets with arrow buttons to the right of them, in which to enter the macro functions and/or operations to be performed for each macro. Each macro is limited to 255 characters in length.@{b} Note@{ub} that ARexx instructions and functions may not be used here, and that ARexx need not be activate in order to launch the macros, unless the QuickFile @{"CALL" link Call} function is used to start an ARexx script.

Selecting the arrow button to the right of a string gadget causes a listview requester displaying all available QuickFile macro functions and their templates for usage to be displayed. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected function. Selecting OK inserts the selected function and its template into the corresponding string gadget in the MACROS DEFINITION requester and closes the listview


At the bottom of the requester are buttons labeled SAVE, SAVE AS, LOAD, USE and CANCEL. Selecting SAVE causes the current configuration to be saved in the current database's home directory with the name "<database>.macros", where <database> is the name of the database's definition file. The file is loaded automatically whenever <database> is opened, and will be used whenever its window is active. If no database has been loaded into the current window, the file is saved as "NoBase.macros" in QuickFile's home directory, and is used for each empty database window.

SAVE AS and LOAD allow macro definition files to be saved to or loaded from files with user-specified names or paths.

Selecting the USE button causes the current configuration to be used for the rest of the current session of the active window/database, but the changes are discarded when the database is closed or QuickFile is quit.
@endnode
@node Macro... "Macro..."
@toc Menus

Up to ten @{"macros" link Macros} can be configured with the @{"MACROS DEFINITION" link Define macros} requester to appear in and be launched from the MACROS menu. This may be done separately for each open database. The title defined for each configured macro and database appears in the corresponding entry in the menu for that database's window. For any entries not yet configured, "Macro..." appears in the menu. Selecting any unconfigured entry causes the MACROS DEFINITION requester to be displayed.
@endnode
@node Function Keys "Configuring the Function Keys"
@toc Menus

Selecting FUNCTION KEYS from the MACROS menu causes the FUNCTION KEYS configuration requester to be displayed, with which the function keys, with and without qualifiers, may be configured to launch DIRECT macros, made up of QuickFile macro @{"functions" link Functions} and/or @{"operations" link MacroOps}.

Multiple configuration files may be saved and loaded. If it exists, a file named "QuickFile.keys" in QuickFile's home directory is automatically loaded when QuickFile is started, and its contents are displayed the first time this requester is opened each session.

The requester has the following components:

@{b}Qualifier@{ub}

The qualifier key to use with function keys. The available choices are:

  None    No qualifier
  Alt     Either ALT key
  Shift   Either SHIFT key
  Ctrl    The CONTROL key

@{b}F1@{ub} through@{b} F10@{ub}

Ten string gadgets with arrow buttons to the right of them, in which to enter a DIRECT macro for each of the ten function keys in combination with the currently selected qualifier key. Up to forty combinations may be configured.@{b} Note@{ub} that ARexx instructions and functions may not be used here, and that ARexx need not be active in order to launch the macros, unless QuickFile's @{"CALL" link Call} function is used to start one or more ARexx scripts.

Selecting the arrow button to the right of a string gadget causes a listview requester displaying all available QuickFile macro functions and their templates for usage to be displayed. A highlight bar indicates the currently selected function. Selecting OK inserts the selected function and its template into the corresponding string gadget in the FUNCTION KEYS configuration requester and closes the listview


At the bottom of the requester are buttons labelled SAVE, SAVE AS, LOAD, MERGE, USE and CANCEL. Selecting SAVE causes the currently displayed configuration to be used and saved as 'QuickFile.keys' in QuickFile's current directory. This file will be loaded and used automatically each time the program is started, if it exists.@{b} Note@{ub} that if any keyboard macros have been programmed with the @{"MAP" link MAP} macro function, they will also be saved with the file, and loaded whenever the file is loaded, but only the function key configurations are displayed and may be edited from within this requester.

Selecting USE results in the current configuration being used for the current session without being saved.

Selecting SAVE AS or LOAD causes a file requester to be displayed. For SAVE AS, the requester may be used to specify an alternative path or filename for the current configuration to be saved to. For LOAD, any such existing file may be loaded and displayed.

Selecting MERGE causes a file requester to be displayed, with which another configuration file may be selected to have merged with the one currently displayed. The second file, i.e. the one selected in the file requester, takes precedence. Any key and qualifier combination which is configured in the first file will be overwritten by the corresponding configuration, if one exists, in the second file. For example, if the two files have the following configurations for the function keys shown:

  @{u} Keys @{uu}  @{u} First  @{uu}  @{u} Second @{uu}  @{u} Merged @{uu}
  Alt-F1  <macro1>  <macro5>  <macro5>
  Alt-F2  <macro2>            <macro2>
  Alt-F3  <macro3>  <macro6>  <macro6>
  Alt-F4            <macro7>  <macro7>
  Alt-F5  <macro4>            <macro4>
@endnode
@node Help... "Help with Macro Functions"
@toc Menus

Selecting HELP from the MACROS menu causes a requester with a string gadget to be displayed. If the name of any help node in this guide file is entered into the string gadget and OK is selected, the node will be displayed, as long as the necessary system files (AmigaGuide or MultiView and associated libraries) are available. This is primarily intended to obtain quick help for Quickfile's macro functions, but any correctly named node will be displayed. If OK is selected while the string gadget is empty, or when a non-existent name is entered, the last previously accessed node is displayed, or the main node, if no other node has been accessed yet.
@endnode
@node Buffers "Buffer Control"
@toc Menus

Selecting BUFFERS from the OPTIONS menu displays a requester showing information regarding the usage of @{"RAM buffers" link IO} in the current database, and allowing the number of buffers to be temporarily changed. The information shown includes:

@{b}Blocks in File@{ub}

The size of the current database expressed in blocks, which is also the number of buffers required to hold the entire database in memory.

@{b}Buffers in Use@{ub}

The number of RAM buffers currently allocated. This starts at 1 when a file is first opened.

@{b}Buffer Size@{ub}

The amount of RAM required for each buffer allocated.

@{b}Maximum Buffers@{ub}

The maximum number of buffers to be used. By default, this is the same as the number of buffers specified for use in the @{"INPUT/OUTPUT" link IO} settings panel of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester, and may be changed for the current session only. The next time the file is opened, the maximum will revert to the value specified in the database definition, where it may be changed permanently at any time if desired.
@endnode
@node Configuration "Configuring QuickFile"
@toc Menus

Selecting CONFIGURATION from the OPTIONS menu displays the CONFIGURATION requester, in which the following global settings and values used by QuickFile may be configured:

@{b}Memory Save@{ub}

If checked, this forces QuickFile to reduce memory usage, but also causes @{"sorting" link Sort index} to take longer. By default, this is checked when a configuration file has not yet been saved. Unchecking it is recommended if RAM availability is not a concern.

@{b}Requesters@{ub}

A Cycle gadget which determines the initial position of any requesters that may open. Two choices are available:

  Window Center  Requesters will be centered over the current window
  Follow Mouse   Requesters will open under the current mouse position

@{b}Fonts@{ub}

A font can be specified for each of three general uses in QuickFile. These are:

  Standard  Used in @{"FORM" link Form} views and most gadgets; may be proportional.

  List      A fixed width font used for @{"LIST" link List} views and listview gadgets
            in various requesters.

  Report    A fixed width font used to display reports printed to the
            window.

Each font field has an arrow button next to it. Selecting the arrow causes a font requester to be displayed, with which a new font and/or size may be selected.@{b} Note@{ub} that some gadget imagery may be garbled if very wide fonts are used.


At the bottom of the requester are SAVE, USE and CANCEL buttons. Selecting SAVE closes the requester, uses the current settings and saves them to a file named "QuickFile.config" in QuickFile's home directory. Selecting USE closes the requester and uses the current settings for this session, but does not save them to disk. The next time QuickFile is run, the settings will revert to those previously saved, or the program defaults if none were saved.
@endnode
@node MacroRef "Macro Reference"

  @{"Overview               " link Overview}
  @{"Basic Syntax           " link BasicSyntax} @{b}Should be read before ARexx syntax!@{ub}
  @{"ARexx Script Syntax    " link ARexxSyntax}
  @{"Caveats and Limitations" link Caveats}
  @{"Notation Description   " link Notation}
  @{"General Error Messages " link Errors}
  @{"Macro Operators        " link MacroOps}
  @{"Macro Functions        " link Functions}
@endnode
@node Overview "Macro Overview"
@toc MacroRef

QuickFile can be automated using two types of macros: DIRECT macros, and ARexx scripts. DIRECT macros are strings of one or more QuickFile macro functions and operations which are not sent to ARexx for interpretation, but are interpreted and executed directly by QuickFile. ARexx need not even be available to run DIRECT macros, unless QuickFile's @{"CALL" link CALL} function is used within one to launch a separate ARexx script.

Since DIRECT macros are not sent to ARexx, they may not contain any ARexx instructions or functions, and they cannot interact with other programs. This may seem limiting, but QuickFile provides over 100 functions and numerous operators that make it possible to construct DIRECT macros which are quite flexible and sophisticated. There is also a significant speed advantage, as can be seen in the examples shown for the @{"FOR" link FOR} function.

The following methods are available for launching DIRECT macros:

  @{"DIRECT MACRO requester    " link Direct Macro}
  @{"MACROS menu configuration " link Define Macros}
  @{"FUNCTION KEY configuration" link Function Keys}

In addition to these, DIRECT macros may be programmed to various keys and key combinations using the @{"MAP" link MAP} function.

ARexx scripts may also be launched via any of the above methods (by using CALL), as well as by either of the following methods:

  STARTUP macros
  @{"AREXX SCRIPT requester    " link ARexx Script}

STARTUP macros are ARexx scripts which are run automatically, if they exist. If "ARexx/QuickFile.startup" exists within QuickFile's current directory (the directory from which QuickFile was started), it is run whenever a new database window is opened. If a script named "<database_definition>.startup" exists in the corresponding database's home directory, it is run whenever the database is opened.

The default filename extension for QuickFile ARexx scripts other than STARTUP macros is ".quickfile", which need not be specified when running scripts that have it.

Each open database window has its own task and ARexx port. For the first window, the ARexx port name is 'QuickFile.0'. The number is incremented by one for each additional window opened. There should be no need to run multiple copies of QuickFile, but the ARexx port numbering scheme continues in the order that database windows are open, regardless of which running copy of QuickFile opened them. The ARexx port is automatically set for macros launched from within QuickFile, so the port name need be specified only for ARexx scripts launched from elsewhere (Shell, or another application), or when address changes are required within a QuickFile script..

Not all QuickFile functions are available via macro. Contact the @{"author" link QuickFile.guide/Author} if additional functions are desired.
@endnode
@node BasicSyntax "Basic Macro Syntax"
@toc MacroRef

@{b}Functions@{ub}

QuickFile's macro @{"functions" link Functions} are somewhat similar in usage to ARexx functions. Although several of the functions do not require any arguments, most do, and for nearly all of those which do, the arguments must be enclosed in parenthesis, must be separated from each other by commas when there is more than a single argument, and must immediately follow the function name. In addition, functions may be nested, in order to use the result of one function as an argument to another. For example:

  <FUNCTION1>(<arg1>,<FUNCTION2>(<arg2>))

@{b}Arguments and Constants@{ub}

Unlike ARexx, QuickFile distinguishes between numeric and string arguments and constants. Strings must be enclosed by double-quote marks, even if the string is composed only of numerals. Single-quote marks may not be substituted. If it is desired that a character string argument contain literal double-quote marks, for example to set the value of a CHARACTER field to a string that has double-quote marks in it, the literal marks must be doubled in the argument string. For example:

  <FUNCTION>("He said, ""Hello there!""")

Numerical values must@{b} not@{ub} be enclosed by quote marks, and may be expressed in decimal format, or in hexadecimal format when preceded by a dollar symbol ($). For example:

  <FUNCTION>(512)
  <FUNCTION>($200)

@{b}Variables@{ub}

Variables may be used in DIRECT macros. QuickFile variable names may be composed of one or more of the following characters, with restrictions as indicated:

  @{u}May be used anywhere in name@{uu}
  A through Z
  A E I O U Accented
  Ć
  ß
  Đ
  Ţ
  Ř
  ×
  _ (underscore)

  @{u}May not be used as first character@{uu}
  0 through 9
  #
  $

A variables may be set to a literal numeric or string value, or may be set directly to the result of a QuickFile function. For example:

  A=512
  B="This is a string"
  C=<FUNCTION>(<arg1>,<arg2>)

Once a variable has been set to either a string or numerical value, it may from then on only be used for the same type of value, unless and until the @{"INIT" link INIT} function is used on it. After set with the desired values, variables may be used as arguments to functions, or in operations (see below).@{b} Note@{ub} that a QuickFile variable retains its value after the macro which used it has completed, but it is only active for the database window the macro was run from.

@{b}Operations@{ub}

In addition to the setting of variables to values using the equals sign (=), other mathematical and string operations, such as addition of numerical values and concatenation of strings, may also be performed for variables, and within arguments for macro functions. See the table of macro @{"operators" link MacroOps} for details.

@{b}Multiple Clauses@{ub}

Multiple, sequential clauses are possible in QuickFile macros by separating them with the colon character, as shown below:

  A=1:B=<FUNCTION1>(A,<FUNCTION2>(<arg>)):<FUNCTION3>

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"Syntax for Use in ARexx Scripts" link ARexxSyntax}
@endnode
@node ARexxSyntax "Macro Syntax for Use in ARexx Scripts"
@toc MacroRef

@{b}Note:@{ub} @{"Basic Syntax" link BasicSyntax} should be read prior to this section.

@{b}Circumstances Requiring Outer Quotes@{ub}

Due to certain conventions of QuickFile macro clauses, parts or all of a clause line may need to be enclosed in quote marks when used in ARexx scripts, depending on the circumstances. For simplicity, it is advisable to generally quote QuickFile macro clauses in their entirety.

Since double-quote marks are used to denote string values for QuickFile, single-quote marks should be used for the outer quotes. The presence of any of the following circumstances will require the use of outer quote marks:

1. Parenthesis (), used to enclose arguments to QuickFile functions. If unquoted, would cause the function to be misinterpreted by ARexx as an ARexx function call.

2. Double-quote marks (""), used to inform Quickfile that a value is a character string and not a number. Outer quote marks are removed by ARexx prior to a line being sent back to the host for interpretation.

3. Colon (:), used to separate multiple QuickFile macro clauses in a line. The colon is a reserved character in ARexx, which is used at the end of a label which introduces a subroutine or internal function.

4. Certain QuickFile operators (@{"+" link AddJoin}, @{"/" link Divide}, @{"%" link Modulo}, @{"^" link Power}, @{"<<" link ShiftLeft}, @{">>" link ShiftRight}, @{"&" link AND}, @{"?" link XOR}, @{"|" link OR}). While most of the operators have (mostly) identical counterparts in ARexx, some either work somewhat differently than the ARexx operators, or are represented by different symbols.

5. Any QuickFile variable names. Quickfile variables are not the same as ARexx variables. If a variable name is unquoted, it will be considered an ARexx variable.

6. Certain QuickFile function names (@{"CALL" link CALL}, @{"IF" link IF}, @{"SELECT" link SELECT}) which are identical to those of ARexx instructions. If unquoted, the ARexx instruction will be used, and will most likely be misinterpreted due to inconsistencies in usage.

The following are examples of alternative code fragments which achieve the same result:

  'A=<FUNCTION1>(5)^10:<FUNCTION2>(<FUNCTION3>("string"))'

  'A='<FUNCTION1>'('5')^'10':'<FUNCTION2>'('<FUNCTION3>'("string"))'

@{b}Note@{ub} that QuickFile requires that all function and variable names are in UPPER CASE. When entering them as DIRECT macros into any of the various requesters, they may be entered in upper or lower case, as QuickFile will convert anything that is not enclosed in double-quote marks to upper case when the applicable requester is closed. ARexx likewise converts to upper case anything that is not quoted, but since some QuickFile code requires outer quote marks to avoid misinterpretation, care must be taken that it is quoted in the correct case.

@{b}Using Both QuickFile and ARexx Variables in Scripts@{ub}

For any Quickfile macro clause or string of multiple clauses, the results of the final clause in the line will be placed in ARexx's RESULT variable, as long as it has already been enabled for the script with the line 'OPTIONS RESULTS'. For example, if there is a hypothetical function AVG which returns the average of all argument values:

  'AVG(2,4,6,8,10)'
  say result

    >>> 5

If the final clause has nested functions, the result of the outermost function is returned. For example:

  'AVG(25,AVG(2,4,6,8,10))
  say result

    >>> 15

If the final clause is the setting of a Quickfile variable to a value, or just the variable name by itself, its value will be the result. For example:

  'A=AVG(2,4,6,8,10)+20' /* Or... */ 'A=AVG(2,4,6,8,10)+20:A'
  say result

    >>> 25

To use the values of one or more ARexx variables in QuickFile macro functions, simply leave them out of the outer quotes used. For example:

  a=1
  b=2
  c=3
  'AVG('a','b','c')'

In keeping with QuickFile's requirements, ARexx variables which are intended as character strings must be surrounded by double-quote marks, which must themselves be quoted, when used with QuickFile macro functions, unless they already have the quotes embedded within them. For example:

  a='This is a string'
  '<FUNCTION>("'a'")'

  /* Or... */

  a='"This is a string"'
  '<FUNCTION>('a')'

Extra care must be taken with ARexx variables containing double-quote marks that are intended as literal, since literal double-quote marks must be doubled to be interpreted correctly. For example:

  /* Literal string to be used is 'He said, "I'm not going."' */
  a='He said, ""I''m not going.""'
  '<FUNCTION>("'a'")'

The included external ARexx function macro @{"FixQuotes.quickfile" link ARexx/FixQuotes.quickfile/Main} may be used, or its code included in scripts as an internal function, to test and double up the double-quote marks in such variable values as necessary.
@endnode
@node Caveats "Caveats and Limitations"
@toc MacroRef

@{b}Modifying Index Fields in All Records@{ub}

Anytime the value of a field that is used in the current index is modified in an existing record, whether via macro or manually, the record may be re-positioned within the index as soon as it is updated. If a macro is to modify the same index field in all records in the current index, there is a potential that some records will be modified more than once and others not at all, due to records being re-positioned within the index upon update. Care should be taken to switch to an index that does not use the field to be modified, or to sort the records in a sequence based on other fields.

The included external function macro @{"ReSort.quickfile" link ARexx/ReSort.quickfile/Main} may be used to test whether fields to be modified by a macro are used in the current index, and automatically re-sort records, using a field that is not being modified by the macro, when necessary.@{b} Note@{ub} that if@{b} all@{ub} existing database fields are being modified by a macro, there will be no unused field to re-sort with.
@endnode
@node Notation "Function Notation Description"
@toc MacroRef

The following conventions are used in the function template descriptions:

  Function names and keyword arguments are in UPPER CASE.

  Arguments in square brackets [ ] are optional.

  One of the arguments in curly braces {A|D} is required.

  Repeated arguments are indicated by ellipsis ...

  <enclosed lower case words> represent user-provided values.
@endnode
@node Errors "General Error Messages"
@toc MacroRef

Most QuickFile macro functions give a return code (RC) of 20 if they fail for any reason, but a requester with an error message is usually also displayed. The following are various error messages and the problems they may have resulted from:

  @{u}Message                 @{uu}  @{u}Possible Problem                                @{uu}
  Argument type mismatch    Numeric argument given where string argument
                            expected.

                            Floating point argument given where integer
                            argument expected.

                            String argument not enclosed in double-quote
                            marks.

  Incorrect argument value  Numeric argument is out of range for required
                            usage.

  Incorrect number format   A semi-colon (";") was placed after a numeric
                            value, possibly instead of a colon (":") to
                            separate two functions and/or evaluations in a
                            mulitple QuickFile function string.

  Incorrect operand         Function name not in upper case.

                            Parenthesis present, but required argument(s)
                            missing.

                            String argument not enclosed in double-quote
                            marks.

  Incorrect string          Matching double-quote mark missing.

  Incorrect variable value  

  Missing argument          One or more arguments provided, but more
                            required.

  Missing operator          A semi-colon (';') was used between two
                            QuickFile functions in a string of functions
                            instead of a colon (':').

  Variable type mismatch    String argument given where numeric argument
                            expected.

  Undefined field           An invalid field name was given as an argument
                            for a function requiring a field name.
@endnode
@node MacroOps "Macro Operators"
@toc MacroRef

The following macro operators are available, in order of descending priority:

  @{u}Symbol@{uu}  @{u}Pri@{uu}  @{u}Operation                                                  @{uu}
    @{"^" link Power}    10   Exponentiation (numbers only; exponent must be >= 0)

    @{"*" link Multiply}     9   Multiplication (numbers only)
    @{"/" link Divide}     9   Division (numbers only)
    @{"%" link Modulo}     9   Modulo division (numbers only; denominator must be integer)

    @{"+" link AddJoin}     8   Addition (numbers); concatenation (strings)
    @{"-" link Subtract}     8   Subtraction, negation (numbers only)

   @{"<<" link ShiftLeft}     7   Shift left (integers and strings)
   @{">>" link ShiftRight}     7   Shift right (integers and strings)

    @{"&" link AND}     6   AND (integers only)
    @{"?" link XOR}     5   XOR (exclusive OR; integers only)
    @{"|" link OR}     4   OR (non-exclusive; integers only)

    @{">" link GT}     3   Greater than (numbers, strings)
    @{"<" link LT}     3   Less than (numbers, strings)
   @{">=" link GTEQ}     3   Greater than or equal to (numbers, strings)
   @{"<=" link LTEQ}     3   Less than or equal to (numbers, strings)
   @{"==" link EqualTo}     3   Equal to (numbers, strings)

    @{"=" link Equals}     2   Variable assignment (numbers, strings)
@endnode
@node Power "Macro Operator: ^ (Exponentiation)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on numbers only; the second value, which is the power the first number is to be raised to, must be greater than or equal to 0. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}  Result   @{uu}
     2^3          8
     3^2          9
     6^8       1679616
     5^1          5
    10^.5    3.162277660
    17^0          1
@endnode
@node Multiply "Macro Operator: * (Multiplication)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on numbers only. Examples:

  @{u}  Operation   @{uu}  @{u}   Result   @{uu}
       5*5             25
      -2*-8            16
  3*3.3333333333  10.000000000
@endnode
@node Divide "Macro Operator: / (Division)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on numbers only. If both numerator and denominator are integers, result will also be an integer (any non-integer portion will be dropped). Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}  Result   @{uu}
    3/2           1
    3/2.0    1.500000000
    3.0/2    1.500000000
@endnode
@node Modulo "Macro Operator: % (Modulo division)"
@toc MacroOps

Returns the remainder of a division operation. Operates on numbers only; denominator must be an integer. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}   Result   @{uu}
     3%2          1
     5%3          2
     8%2          0
   -10.5%6   -4.500000000
@endnode
@node AddJoin "Macro operator: + (Addition of numbers, concatenation of strings)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings. Numbers are added. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
    1+2         3
    5+-8       -3

Strings are concatenated (joined without any extra spaces added between). Example:

  @{u}     Operation     @{uu}  @{u}     Result     @{uu}
  "testing"+" 123..."  "testing 123..."
@endnode
@node Subtract "Macro Operator: - (Subtraction, negation)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on numbers only. Subtracts one number from another, or negates (multiplies by -1) the following number. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
    10-6        4
    10--6      16
@endnode
@node ShiftLeft "Macro Operator: << (Shift Left)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings, but the second argument must be an integer in either case. For integers, 'X<<Y' is equal to 'X*(2^Y)'. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
    1<<3        8
    3<<5       96

For strings, 'X<<Y' deletes the first Y characters in string X and returns the result. If Y is equal to or greater than the number of charcters in X, an empty string is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
  "test"<<0  "test"
  "test"<<1  "est"
  "test"<<2  "st"
  "test"<<3  "t"
  "test"<<4  ""
@endnode
@node ShiftRight "Macro Operator: >> (Shift Right)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings, but the second argument must be an integer in either case. For integers, 'X>>Y' is equal to the integer portion only of 'X/(2^Y)'. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
   100>>2      25
    32>>5       1

For strings, 'X>>Y' deletes the last Y characters in string X and returns the result. If Y is equal to or greater than the number of charcters in X, an empty string is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
  "test">>0  "test"
  "test">>1  "tes"
  "test">>2  "te"
  "test">>3  "t"
  "test">>4  ""
@endnode
@node AND "Macro Operator: & (AND)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on integers only. Multiplies individual corresponding bits in the binary translations of both values and returns the concatenated results as a decimal integer. For example:

  10&12

  @{u}Decimal@{uu}  @{u}Binary@{uu}

       10   1010
  @{u}AND  12@{uu}  @{u} 1100@{uu}
   =    8   1000
@endnode
@node XOR "Macro Operator: ? (Exclusive OR)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on integers only. Subtracts individual bits in the binary translation of one value from the corresponding bits in the other, and returns the concatenated signs of the results as a decimal integer. For example:

  10?12

  @{u}Decimal@{uu}  @{u}Binary@{uu}

       10  1010
  @{u}XOR  12@{uu}  @{u}1100@{uu}
   =    6  0110
@endnode
@node OR "Macro Operator: | (OR)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on integers only. Adds individual corresponding bits in the binary translations of both values and returns the concatenated signs of the results as a decimal integer. For example:

  10|12

  @{u}Decimal@{uu}  @{u}Binary@{uu}

       10  1010
  @{u}OR   12@{uu}  @{u}1100@{uu}
   =   14  1110
@endnode
@node GT "Macro Operator: > (Greater than)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings. For numbers, 1 is returned if the first value is greater than the second value, otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
     8>5        1
     3>3        0
     1>4        0

For strings, the comparison is performed based on the ASCII values of the beginnings of the two strings. 1 is returned if the strings are found to differ at some point AND the first character at which they are found to differ has a higher ASCII value in the first string than in the second string, otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
  "a">"A"       1
  "a">"999"     1
  "ab">"ac"     0
  "az">"az"     0
  "10">"9"      0
@endnode
@node LT "Macro Operator: < (Less than)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings. For numbers, 1 is returned if the first value is less than the second value, otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
     8<5        0
     3<3        0
     1<4        1

For strings, the comparison is performed based on the ASCII values of the beginnings of the two strings. 1 is returned if the strings are found to differ at some point AND the first character at which they are found to differ has a lower ASCII value in the first string than in the second string, otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
  "a"<"A"       0
  "a"<"999"     0
  "ab"<"ac"     1
  "az"<"az"     0
  "10"<"9"      1
@endnode
@node GTEQ "Macro Operator: >= (Greater than or equal to)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings. For numbers, 1 is returned if the first value is greater than or equal to the second value, otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
     8>=5       1
     3>=3       1
     1>=4       0

For strings, the comparison is performed based on the ASCII values of the beginnings of the two strings. 1 is returned if the strings are identical, OR if they are found to differ at some point AND the first character at which they are found to differ has a higher ASCII value in the first string than in the second string; otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation @{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
  "a">="A"       1
  "a">="999"     1
  "ab">="ac"     0
  "az">="az"     1
  "10">="9"      0
@endnode
@node LTEQ "Macro Operator: <= (Less than or equal to)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings. For numbers, 1 is returned if the first value is less than or equal to the second value, otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation@{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
     8<=5       0
     3<=3       1
     1<=4       1

For strings, the comparison is performed based on the ASCII values of the beginnings of the two strings. 1 is returned if the strings are identical, OR if they are found to differ at some point AND the first character at which they are found to differ has a lower ASCII value in the first string than in the second string; otherwise 0 is returned. Examples:

  @{u}Operation @{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
  "a"<="A"       0
  "a"<="999"     0
  "ab"<="ac"     1
  "az"<="az"     1
  "10"<="9"      1
@endnode
@node EqualTo "Macro Operator: == (Equal to)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either numbers or strings. Returns 1 if the first number or string is exactly equal to the second number or string. Leading zeros in numbers are ignored. Examples:

  @{u}Operation @{uu}  @{u}Result@{uu}
    10==10       1
    01==1        1
    35==53       0
  "01"=="1"      0
  "at"=="At"     0
  "at"=="at"     1
 
@endnode
@node Equals "Macro Operator: = (Equals)"
@toc MacroOps

Operates on either number variables or string variables; sets the value of the named variable. Examples:

  A=512
  B="This is a string"

@{b}Note@{ub} that once a QuickFile variable is set to a number or string value, it can from then on only be used for the same type of value, unless the @{"INIT" link INIT} macro function is used to re-initialize it.@{b} Note@{ub} also that QuickFile variables continue to hold their values (and type of values) after the macros in which they were used complete. It is therefore adviseable to use the INIT function with all variables used in a macro at the beginning of it. Variables are specific to the QuickFile windows for which the macros which used them were launched.
@endnode
