@node String "Macro Functions: Processing of character strings"
@toc Subjects

  @{"ASC      " link ASC} Returns the ASCII code of a character
  @{"CHR      " link CHR} Returns the character with the specified ASCII code
  @{"LASTPOS  " link LASTPOS} Returns the last starting postion of a string within another
  @{"LEFT     " link LEFT} Returns the left part of a string
  @{"LEN      " link LEN} Returns the length of a character string
  @{"LOWER    " link LOWER} Returns string converted to lower-case
  @{"POS      " link POS} Returns the starting position of a string within another
  @{"RIGHT    " link RIGHT} Returns the right part of a string
  @{"SUBSTRING" link SUBSTRING} Returns a part of a string
  @{"UPPER    " link UPPER} Returns a string converted to upper-case
@endnode
@node Numerical "Macro Functions: Processing of numerical values"
@toc Subjects

  @{"ABS" link ABS} Returns the absolute value of a number
  @{"INT" link INT} Rounds a number to the nearest integer and returns it
  @{"SGN" link SGN} Returns the sign (+/-) of a number
@endnode
@node Convert "Macro Functions: Conversion between strings and numerical values"
@toc Subjects

  @{"ASC       " link ASC} Returns the ASCII code of a character
  @{"CHR       " link CHR} Returns the character with the specified ASCII code
  @{"STR       " link STR} Converts a number into a character string
  @{"TIMESTRING" link TIMESTRING} Converts a floating time value to a time string
  @{"TIMEVAL   " link TIMEVAL} Converts a time string to a floating time value
  @{"VAL       " link VAL} Converts a character string into a number
@endnode
@node Requesters "Macro Functions: Requesters"
@toc Subjects

  @{"ASKNUM    " link ASKNUM} Displays an integer requester
  @{"ASKTEXT   " link ASKTEXT} Displays a string requester
  @{"MESSAGE   " link MESSAGE} Displays a message
  @{"REQBASE   " link REQBASE} Displays a requester with a button for open window
  @{"REQFIELD  " link REQFIELD} Displays a listview requester of all fields
  @{"REQFILE   " link REQFILE} Displays a file requester
  @{"REQLIST   " link REQLIST} Displays a custom listview, returns string number
  @{"REQLISTSTR" link REQLISTSTR} Displays a custom listview, returns a string
  @{"REQNUMBER " link REQNUMBER} Displays an integer requester, also returns button pressed
  @{"REQPATH   " link REQPATH} Displays a path requester
  @{"REQSTRING " link REQSTRING} Displays a string requester, also returns button pressed
  @{"REQUEST   " link REQUEST} Displays a requester with OK and CANCEL buttons
  @{"SELECT    " link SELECT} Displays a requester with user-definable buttons
  @{"SELECTSTR " link SELECTSTR} Displays a custom button requester, returns a string
@endnode
@node Info "Macro Functions: Global informational functions"
@toc Subjects

  @{"DATE     " link DATE} Returns the actual date
  @{"FONTNAME " link FONTNAME} Returns the name of a font used by QuickFile
  @{"FONTSIZE " link FONTSIZE} Returns the size of a font used by QuickFile
  @{"HELP     " link HELP} Displays an AmigaGuide help node
  @{"LANGUAGE " link LANGUAGE} Returns the name of the language locale in use
  @{"SCRHEIGHT" link SCRHEIGHT} Returns the screen height
  @{"SCRMODE  " link SCRMODE} Returns the ID of the screen mode
  @{"SCRWIDTH " link SCRWIDTH} Returns the screen width
  @{"VERSION  " link VERSION} Returns the version number of QuickFile
@endnode
@node Windows "Macro Functions: File and window management"
@toc Subjects

  @{"BLOCKSIZE " link BLOCKSIZE} Returns the blocksize in use for the current database
  @{"CLOSE     " link CLOSE} Closes the current database or all the databases
  @{"FILE      " link FILE} Returns the number of, and path/names of databases/windows
  @{"FILENAME  " link FILENAME} Returns the name of the current database
  @{"FREEVIEW  " link FREEVIEW} Unloads a view from memory
  @{"FULLNAME  " link FULLNAME} Returns the full path and name of the current database
  @{"LOAD      " link LOAD} Loads a database into the current window
  @{"LOADVIEW  " link LOADVIEW} Loads a view
  @{"OPEN      " link OPEN} Opens a database in a new window
  @{"PATH      " link PATH} Returns the path of the current database
  @{"PORTNAME  " link PORTNAME} Returns an ARexx port name corresponding to a window
  @{"REFRESH   " link REFRESH} Updates the database window display with any changes
  @{"REXXPORT  " link REXXPORT} Returns a window's ARexx port
  @{"SAVE      " link SAVE} Saves the current database
  @{"SAVEVIEW  " link SAVEVIEW} Saves a loaded view
  @{"SELFILE   " link SELFILE} Activates and brings to the front a database's window
  @{"SELPORT   " link SELPORT} Activates and brings to the front an ARexx port's window
  @{"TITLE     " link TITLE} Displays a message in the title bar of the current window
  @{"WINHEIGHT " link WINHEIGHT} Returns the height of the current window
  @{"WINLEFT   " link WINLEFT} Returns the horizontal position of the current window
  @{"WINTOBACK " link WINTOBACK} Sends the current window to the back
  @{"WINTOFRONT" link WINTOFRONT} Brings the current window to the front
  @{"WINTOP    " link WINTOP} Returns the vertical position of the current window
  @{"WINWIDTH  " link WINWIDTH} Returns the width of the current window
@endnode
@node Control "Macro Functions: Macro and program control"
@toc Subjects

  @{"CALL       " link CALL} Runs an ARexx script
  @{"DEF        " link DEF} Defines a new function
  @{"EXEC       " link EXEC} Interprets and executes a string as macro code
  @{"FOR        " link FOR} Initiates a conditional loop
  @{"IF         " link IF} Performs a test and decides action
  @{"INIT       " link INIT} Initializes variables (resets type and value)
  @{"LOCK       " link LOCK} Locks out user input in the current window
  @{"MAP        " link MAP} Programs a macro to a keyboard shortcut sequence
  @{"READDEF    " link READDEF} Returns the definition of a user-defined function
  @{"READMAP    " link READMAP} Returns the macro assigned to a key sequence
  @{"RESET      " link RESET} Resets the value, but not type, of variables
  @{"REXXPATH   " link REXXPATH} Changes and/or returns the default path used by CALL
  @{"SECURITY   " link SECURITY} Sets the maximum number of loops to allow
  @{"SENDCOMMAND" link SENDCOMMAND} Sends one or more macro commands to another QuickFile window
  @{"UNLOCK     " link UNLOCK} Restores user input in the current window
  @{"UNMAP      " link UNMAP} Deletes a programmed key sequence and macro
  @{"WHILE      " link WHILE} Initiates a conditional loop
@endnode
@node ABS "Macro function: ABS"
@toc Numerical

@{b}ABS(<number>)@{ub}

Returns the absolute value of <number>, padded to nine decimal places for floating point values.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <number>

An integer in the range -2147483647 to 2147483647;

A floating point with up to nine decimal places and up to fifteen digits (decimal and non-decimal combined).

@{b}Examples@{ub}

  'ABS(-8)'

    >>> 8

  'ABS(4.0)'

    >>> 4.000000000

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"SGN" link SGN}
@endnode
@node ADDSEARCH "Macro function: ADDSEARCH"
@toc DBase

@{b}ADDSEARCH("{AND|OR}","<field>","<operator>,"<value1>"[,"<value2>"])@{ub}

Adds additional search criteria to any that were previously established with @{"NEWSEARCH" link NEWSEARCH} and ADDSEARCH, for the performance of a query. The actual query is performed by @{"DOSEARCH" link DOSEARCH}.

Returns the number of criteria established so far.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  AND

Match records that meet this criteria AND the previous criteria.

  OR

Match records that meet this criteria OR the previous criteria.

All other parameters are the same as for @{"NEWSEARCH" link NEWSEARCH}.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* select records in which surname is "brown" or "smith" */
  'NEWSEARCH("surname","equal","brown")'
  'ADDSEARCH("or","surname","equal","smith")'
  'DOSEARCH'
@endnode
@node ASC "Macro function: ASC"
@toc String

@{b}ASC("<string>",<position>)@{ub}

Returns the ASCII value of the character at <position> in <string>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string.

  <position>

An integer in the range of 1 to the length of <string>, representing the position of the character whose ASCII value is to be returned.

@{b}Examples@{ub}

  /* ASCII code of character "e" */
  'ASC("element",1)'

    >>> 101

  text = 'ABCBA'
  'ASC("'text'",LEN("'text'"))'

    >>> 65

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"CHR" link CHR}  @{"LEN" link LEN}
@endnode
@node ASKNUM "Macro function: ASKNUM"
@toc Requesters

@{b}ASKNUM("<message>",<integer>)@{ub}

Displays an integer requester with OK and CANCEL buttons.

Returns the number in the requester if OK is selected, or an empty string if cancelled.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to be displayed above the number gadget.

  <integer>

A default integer, in the range -2147483647 to 2147483647, to appear initially in the requester.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'ASKNUM("Please enter an integer from 1 to 10...",5)'

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"ASKTEXT" link ASKTEXT}  @{"REQNUMBER" link REQNUMBER}  @{"REQSTRING" link REQSTRING}
@endnode
@node ASKTEXT "Macro function: ASKTEXT"
@toc Requesters

@{b}ASKTEXT("<message>","<string>")@{ub}

Displays a string requester with OK and CANCEL buttons.

Returns the string in the requester if OK is selected, or an empty string if cancelled.@{b} Note@{ub} that there no way to determine whether the requester was OK'd with an empty string in it, or cancelled. If such functionality is needed, @{"REQSTRING" link REQSTRING} should be used instead.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to be displayed above the string gadget.

  <string>

A default text string of up to 255 characters to appear initially in the requester.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'ASKTEXT("Please enter some text...","")'

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"ASKNUM" link ASKNUM}  @{"REQNUMBER" link REQNUMBER}
@endnode
@node BLOCKSIZE "Macro function: BLOCKSIZE"
@toc Windows

@{b}BLOCKSIZE@{ub}

Returns the blocksize in use for the current database, or 0 if no database has been loaded into the current window.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILENAME" link FILENAME}  @{"PATH" link PATH}  @{"SAVE" link SAVE}
@endnode
@node CALL "Macro function: CALL"
@toc Control

@{b}CALL("<script>"[,"<arg1>"[,"<arg2>"...]])@{ub}

Runs ARexx <script> asynchronously, passing optional arguments to it.@{b} Note@{ub} that this should not be used to call external function scripts.@{b} Note also@{ub} that execution of the current macro resumes immediately, without waiting for <script> to finish.

Returns <script>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <script>

The name of an ARexx script to be run. A path need not be specified if <script> resides in the current default ARexx script path, which is normally "ARexx/" relative to QuickFile's current directory, but may be changed at any time with @{"REXXPATH" link REXXPATH}. The filename extension need not be specified if it is ".quickfile".

  <arg1> etc.

Up to 15 optional arguments to be passed to <script>. Double-quote marks are required around string arguments.

@{b}Examples@{ub}

  'CALL("clrfldinrecs","comment",10)'
@endnode
@node CHR "Macro function: CHR"
@toc String

@{b}CHR(<code>)@{ub}

Returns the character having the specified ASCII value, which can be used to place characters such as linefeeds into custom requester messages.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <code>

An integer in the range of 1 to 255.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'MESSAGE("This message"+CHR(10)+"has two lines")'

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"ASC" link ASC}
@endnode
@node CLOSE "Macro function: CLOSE"
@toc Windows

@{b}CLOSE(<integer>)@{ub}

Closes the current window, or quits QuickFile and closes all windows, without any further warning. All changes are saved prior to closing.

Returns <integer>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

-1 to close all windows and quit the program;

Any other integer to close only the current window.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"LOAD" link LOAD}  @{"OPEN" link OPEN}
@endnode
@node CLRRECORD "Macro function: CLRRECORD"
@toc DBase

@{b}CLRRECORD@{ub}

Clears all fields in preparation to set up a new record. Fields are set to the desired values with @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}, and the new record is then inserted with @{"INSRECORD" link INSRECORD}. If CLRRECORD is not used first, any fields having values in the current record and not explicitly set to new values will retain their values from the current record.

Returns 0.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'CLRRECORD'
  'PUTFIELD("lastname","Brown")'
  'PUTFIELD("firstname","John")'
  'PUTFIELD("address","23 George Street")'
  'INSRECORD'
@endnode
@node CURRENTREC "Macro function: CURRENTREC"
@toc DBase

@{b}CURRENTREC@{ub}

Returns the number of the current record in the current index, or -1 if no database has been loaded into the current window.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"NBRECORDS" link NBRECORDS}  @{"NEXT" link NEXT}
@endnode
@node CYCLESTRING "Macro function: CYCLESTRING"
@toc DBase

@{b}CYCLESTRING("<cyclefield>",<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of available values for <cyclefield>, or the value corresponding to <integer> for it.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <cyclefield>

The name of a CYCLE field in the current database.

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of available values for <cyclefield>;

Any integer in the range of 1 to CYCLESTRING(<cyclefield>,0) to obtain the corresponding value for <cyclefield>.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* For a cycle field named "Status" with */
  /* strings "Active,Pending,Cancelled"    */
  'CYCLESTRING("status",0)'

    >>> 3

  'CYCLESTRING("status",1)'

    >>> Active

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"STRINGCYCLE" link STRINGCYCLE}
@endnode
@node DATE "Macro function: DATE"
@toc Info

@{b}DATE(<integer>)@{ub}

Return the current date in the form dd-Mmm-yy, optionally preceeded by <weekday>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to omit <weekday>;

Any other integer to include <weekday>.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'DATE(0)'

    >>> 26-Nov-00

  'DATE(1)'

    >>> Sunday 26-Nov-00

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"TIMESTRING" link TIMESTRING}
@endnode
@node DEF "Macro function: DEF"
@toc Control

@{b}DEF <function>(<arg1>[,<arg2>...]) = <definition>.@{ub}

Specifies the definition <definition> of a custom macro function <function>, which may use QuickFile's built-in functions and operators, as well as other custom functions that were previously defined. Only one custom function may be defined in a single line, and they may be redefined at any time.

Returns <function>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <function>

A name for the custom function; must begin with an alphabetic character or underscore and may be up to 13 characters long, in any combination of alphanumeric chracters and underscores.

  <arg1>, etc.

At least one and up to fifteen arguments required for this function, as represented by distinct symbol-names which should correspond to those used in the definition. The number of arguments required is fixed for each definition.

When using the custom function, if it does not actually use any arguments, any string, including "", may be provided as the required argument. All string arguments must be enclosed by double-quote marks.

  <definition>

One or more functions and/or operations, and their required arguments, as represented by distinct symbol-names, which should correspond to those used in <arg1>, etc. Multiple clauses must be separated by colons (:).@{b} Note@{ub} that everything to the right of the first equal sign (=) is considered part of the definition, up to the end of the line.

@{b}Examples@{ub}

  'DEF MAX(A,B) = IF(A>B,A,B)'

    >>> MAX

  'MAX(3,8)'

    >>> 8

  'DEF TEST(A) = DATE(0)'

    >>> TEST

  'TEST("")'

    >>> 25-Nov-00

  /* To calculate factorials, ie 6 factorial (6!) = 6x5x4x3x2x1 */
  'DEF FACT(A)=B=1:FOR(I=0,I<A,I=I+1,B=B*I):B'

    >>> FACT

  'FACT(6)'

    >>> 720

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"READDEF" link READDEF}
@endnode
@node DELRECORD "Macro function: DELRECORD"
@toc DBase

@{b}DELRECORD@{ub}

Deletes the current record (if any) without further warning. The next record becomes the new current record. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used. If there are no records in the current index (for example, if the current index is SELECTED but no records have been selected), an error message is displayed.

Returns 0.
@endnode
@node DOSEARCH "Macro function: DOSEARCH"
@toc DBase

@{b}DOSEARCH("{SELECTED|<string>}")@{ub}

Searches all, or previously selected records, for those which meet the criteria that were previously established with @{"NEWSEARCH" link NEWSEARCH} and @{"ADDSEARCH" link ADDSEARCH}; places the matching records (if any) into the temporary index SELECTED and makes it the current index. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.

Returns the number of records matched.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  SELECTED

Perform the search on currently selected records.

  <string>

Any string other than SELECTED to perform the search on all records.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'NEWSEARCH("lastname","equal","brown")'
  'ADDSEARCH("or","lastname","equal","smith")'
  'DOSEARCH("foo")' /* Will search ALL records */

    >>> foo
@endnode
@node EXEC "Macro function: EXEC"
@toc Control

@{b}EXEC("<string>")@{ub}

Interprets and executes <string> as a string of QuickFile functions and/or operations, which allows for dynamically constructed code within DIRECT macros, similar to the use of INTERPRET in an ARexx script.

What is returned depends on the contents of <string>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any valid string of one or more QuickFile functions and/or operations.

@{b}Examples@{ub}

  /* In a direct macro... */
  STRING = "MESSAGE(DATE(1)+CHR(10)+TIMESTRING(-1))":EXEC(STRING)

  /* Or, to accomplish the same thing in an ARexx script... */
  string = 'MESSAGE(DATE(1)+CHR(10)+TIMESTRING(-1))'
  string

  /* Interprets the contents of field "CMD" in the current record */
  EXEC(GETFIELD("CMD"))
  /* Or, in an ARexx script... */
  'GETFIELD("CMD")'
  result

  /* Carries out instructions programmed to key sequence "Ctrl -" */
  EXEC(READMAP("CTRL-"))
  /* Or, in an ARexx script... */
  'READMAP("CTRL-")'
  result

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"READMAP" link READMAP}
@endnode
@node FIELD "Macro function: FIELD"
@toc DBase

@{b}FIELD(<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of fields in the current database, or the name of the field corresponding to <integer>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of fields;

Any integer in the range of 1 to FIELD(0) to obtain the name of the corresponding field.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FIELDLENGTH" link FIELDLENGTH}  @{"FIELDTYPE" link FIELDTYPE}  @{"NBFIELDS" link NBFIELDS}
@endnode
@node FIELDLENGTH "Macro function: FIELDLENGTH"
@toc DBase

@{b}FIELDLENGTH("<field>")@{ub}

Returns the maximum allowable length of <field> in the current database, or 0 if <field> is not an existing fieldname.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field>

The name of an existing field in the current database.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FIELD" link FIELD}  @{"FIELDTYPE" link FIELDTYPE}  @{"NBFIELDS" link NBFIELDS}
@endnode
@node FIELDTYPE "Macro function: FIELDTYPE"
@toc DBase

@{b}FIELDTYPE("<field>")@{ub}

Returns the type of <field>, or an empty string if <field> is not an existing fieldname.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field>

The name of an existing field in the current database.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Assuming "Name" is a character field... */
  'FIELDTYPE("name")'

    >>> Char

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FIELD" link FIELD}  @{"FIELDLENGTH" link FIELDLENGTH}  @{"NBFIELDS" link NBFIELDS}
@endnode
@node FILE "Macro function: FILE"
@toc Windows

@{b}FILE(<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of opened windows/databases, or the full path/name of the database loaded into the window corresponding to <integer>. If no database has been loaded into the window, the string returned is QuickFile's current path appended by "NoBase".

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of open windows;

Any integer in the range of 1 to FILE(0) to obtain the corresponding window's file path/name.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILENAME" link FILENAME}  @{"FULLNAME" link FULLNAME}  @{"PATH" link PATH}  @{"SELFILE" link SELFILE}
@endnode
@node FILENAME "Macro function: FILENAME"
@toc Windows

@{b}FILENAME@{ub}

Returns the name (without path) of the database loaded into the current window, or an empty string if no database has been loaded.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILE" link FILE}  @{"FULLNAME" link FULLNAME}  @{"PATH" link PATH}
@endnode
@node FONTNAME "Macro function: FONTNAME"
@toc Info

@{b}FONTNAME("{LIST|REPORT|<string>}")@{ub}

Returns the name of the font corresponding to the specified keyword, or of the STANDARD font.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  LIST

Obtain the name of the font used in LIST views.

  REPORT

Obtain the name of the font used to display reports that are printed to the database window.

  <string>

Any string other than LIST or REPORT to obtain the name of the STANDARD font, used in FORM views and requesters.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FONTSIZE" link FONTSIZE}
@endnode
@node FONTSIZE "Macro function: FONTSIZE"
@toc Info

@{b}FONTSIZE("{LIST|REPORT|<string>}")@{ub}

Returns the size of the font corresponding to the specified keyword, or of the STANDARD font.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  LIST

Obtain the size of the font used in LIST views.

  REPORT

Obtain the size of the font used to display reports that are printed to the database window.

  <string>

Any string other than LIST or REPORT to obtain the size of the STANDARD font, used in FORM views and requesters.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FONTNAME" link FONTNAME}
@endnode
@node FOR "Macro function: FOR"
@toc Control

@{b}FOR(<initial_condition>,<continue_condition,<action1>[,<action2>...])@{ub}

Initiates a loop, performing all <actions> each time through, that continues as long as <continue_condition> is met, or until the @{"SECURITY" link SECURITY} level has been reached, or until the user presses CTRL-ALT-ESC with the affected database window active (as long as the window has not been @{"LOCKED" link LOCK}).

Returns 0.

This function makes it possible to have loops in direct macros, but can also save much macro execution time when used in ARexx scripts, as it decreases the amount of communications required between ARexx and QuickFile. See the examples below.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <initial_condition>

A function or operation that is performed only once, before the loop is commenced; usually the setting of an index variable to a specific value.

  <continue_condition>

A condition that is tested before each cycle through the loop, which, if true, allows the loop to continue; typically the comparison of an index variable to some final value.

  <action1> etc.

One or more functions and/or operations to be performed each time through the loop cycles through, limited in number only by line length. One <action> is usually the updating of an index variable's value.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

  /* Start I at 0; add 1 to I each time, until I = 10 */
  'FOR(I=0,I<10,I=I+1)'

  /* Same as above, but also delete a record each time through the loop */
  'FOR(I=0,I<10,I=I+1,DELRECORD)'

  /* Add numbers 0 through 100, return result */
  'N=100:FOR(I=0:J=0,I<N,J=J+I,I=I+1):J'

  /* The seconds it takes to complete a QuickFile loop 10000 times */
  /* on an A4000 060 at 50MHz...
  call time('r'); 'FOR(I=0,I<10000,I=I+1)'; call time('e')

    >>> 0.24

  /* ...and the same loop on the same machine by ARexx... */
  call time('r'); 'I=0'; do 10000; 'I=I+1'; end; call time('e')

    >>> 13.58

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"WHILE" link WHILE}
@endnode
@node FREEINDEX "Macro function: FREEINDEX"
@toc DBase

@{b}FREEINDEX@{ub}

Discards the contents of the current temporary index in the current database and frees the memory used. The first index in the internal index list becomes the new current index. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.

Returns 0.

The temporary index to be freed must be the current index prior to use of this function. Only temporary indexes, ie those named SORTED and SELECTED, can be freed; attempting to free any others will generate error messages.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SETINDEX("SELECTED"):FREEINDEX'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"DOSEARCH" link DOSEARCH}  @{"SETINDEX" link SETINDEX}  @{"SHOWALL" link SHOWALL}  @{"SORT" link SORT}
@endnode
@node FREEVIEW "Macro function: FREEVIEW"
@toc DBase

@{b}FREEVIEW("<view>")@{ub}

Unloads <view> from memory; if <view> was the current view, the first view in the internal loaded views list becomes the new current view. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.@{b} Note@{ub} that the disk file defining the freed view is not affected.@{b} Note also@{ub} that at least one view must remain loaded.

Returns the name of the new current view.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <view>

The name of a currently loaded view in the current database, as it would appear in the loaded views list, and as long as it is not the only one.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LOADVIEW" link LOADVIEW}  @{"SAVEVIEW" link SAVEVIEW}  @{"SETVIEW" link SETVIEW}  @{"VIEW" link VIEW}  @{"VIEWFORM" link VIEWFORM}
@endnode
@node FULLNAME "Macro function: FULLNAME"
@toc Windows

@{b}FULLNAME@{ub}

Returns the full name (including path) of the database loaded into the current window, or an empty string if no database has been loaded.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILE" link FILE}  @{"FILENAME" link FILENAME}  @{"PATH" link PATH}
@endnode
@node GETCALC "Macro function: GETCALC"
@toc DBase

@{b}GETCALC("<calcfield>")@{ub}

Returns the calculation expression for <calcfield> in the current database. If <calcfield> is the name of an existing field that is not a calculated field, an empty string is returned.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <calcfield>

The name of an existing calculated field in the current database.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'GETCALC("name")'

    >>> GETFIELD("firstname")+" "+GETFIELD("lastname")

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"GETFIELD" link GETFIELD}  @{"GETFIELDSTR" link GETFIELDSTR}
@endnode
@node GETFIELD "Macro function: GETFIELD"
@toc DBase

@{b}GETFIELD("<field>")@{ub}

Returns the contents of <field> in the current record and database. If <field> is empty, the value returned is an empty string, no matter what the field type is. Otherwise, the type of value returned depends on the field type:

  @{u}Field Type@{uu}   @{u}Value Returned                                             @{uu}
  INTEGER      Integer
  FLOAT        Floating point number
  TIME         Floating point number equal to total seconds in field value
  All others   Character string

If text string output is desired from numerical and TIME fields, @{"GETFIELDSTR" link GETFIELDSTR} should be used instead. Alternatively, numerical values returned by this function can be converted to character strings using @{"STR" link STR}. Numbers returned from TIME fields can be converted to standard time strings using @{"TIMESTRING" link TIMESTRING}.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field>

The name of any existing field in the current database, which need not be visible in the current view.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* For a TIME field with name "Arrival" and value "02:30:45" */
  'GETFIELD("arrival")'

    >>> 9045.000000000

  /* For a DATE field with name "Birthday" and value "13-Oct-1952" */
  'GETFIELD("birthday")'

    >>> 13-Oct-1952

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}
@endnode
@node GETFIELDSTR "Macro function: GETFIELDSTR"
@toc DBase

@{b}GETFIELDSTR("<field>")@{ub}

Returns the contents of <field>, in the current record and database, as a character string (always) exactly as the field value is displayed in the record.

If numerical calculations using other QuickFile functions and operators are to be performed with the output of this function for numerical fields, @{"GETFIELD" link GETFIELD} should be used instead, or the strings may be converted to numerical values using @{"VAL" link VAL}. TIME field strings may be converted using @{"TIMEVAL" link TIMEVAL}

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field>

The name of any existing field in the current database, which need not be visible in the current view.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* For a TIME field with name "Arrival" and value "02:30:45" */
  'GETFIELDSTR("arrival")'

    >>> 02:30:45

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}
@endnode
@node GETSELECTED "Macro function: GETSELECTED"
@toc DBase

@{b}GETSELECTED@{ub}

Causes a record that was selected with the mouse in a LIST view to become the current record.

Returns 1 if the current view is a LIST view and a record was manually selected, otherwise 0.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"CURRENTREC" link CURRENTREC}
@endnode
@node GOTO "Macro function: GOTO"
@toc DBase

@{b}GOTO("<indexvalue1>"[,"<indexvalue2>"...])@{ub}

Jumps to the first record with index field value(s) matching the corresponding <indexvalue(s)>, or the next closest matching record. If there is no next closest matching record, this function jumps to the last record in the current index. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.

Returns 1 if a next closest matching record was located, otherwise 0. There is no indication if a record with all specified <indexvalues> was located. The field values in the new record must be compared with the requested index values to determine if they were matched.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <indexvalue1> etc.

One or more strings or numerical values, corresponding in type and order to the index fields defined for the current index. No more than one is required, even if there are more index fields, however, the more <indexvalues> specified, the more likely a closer match. Specifying more <indexvalues> than there are index fields results in an error.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Database has index fields "surname" and "firstname" */
  'GOTO("Brown","John")'
  'GETFIELD("firstname")+GETFIELD("surname")'
  if result ~== "JohnBrown" then 'MESSAGE("John Brown not found")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"NEXT" link NEXT}
@endnode
@node HELP "Macro function: HELP"
@toc Info

@{b}HELP("<node>")@{ub}

Displays <node> from this AmigaGuide file ("QuickFile.guide").

Returns 1 if successful in displaying any node, otherwise 0.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <node>

The name of an existing node in QuickFile.guide. If <node> is not found, the node that was displayed the last time the function was used during the current session is displayed, otherwise the main node is displayed.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'HELP("GETFIELD")'
@endnode
@node IF "Macro function: IF"
@toc Control

@{b}IF(<condition>,<if_true>,<if_false>)@{ub}

Returns <if_true> if <condition> is true, otherwise returns <if_false>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <condition>

A condition to be tested, usually whether a variable holds a certain value.

  <if_true>

A function or operation to be carried out if <condition> is true.

  <if_false>

A function or operation to be carried out if <condition> is false.

@{b}Examples@{ub}

  /* Returns the maximum of A or B */
  'IF(A>B,A,B)'

  'IF(GETFIELD("Name")=="Smith",MESSAGE("Hello Mr Smith !"),0)'
@endnode
@node INDEX "Macro function: INDEX"
@toc DBase

@{b}INDEX(<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of existing indexes for the current database (including SELECTED, and SORTED if it exists), or the name of the index corresponding to <integer>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of indexes;

Any integer in the range of 1 to INDEX(0) to obtain the name of the corresponding index.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"IXFIELD" link IXFIELD}
@endnode
@node INIT "Macro function: INIT"
@toc Control

@{b}INIT(<variable1>[,<variable2>...])@{ub}

Re-initializes one or more QuickFile <variables>, so that they may again be used to store any type of values. Once a QuickFile variable has been used to store either a numerical value or a character string, it may from then on only be used for the same type of value, even after the macro which established it has completed, unless it is INITed.@{b} Note@{ub} that QuickFile variables are globally accessible, i.e. their values may accessed from within any other QuickFile macro or window.

Returns 1.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <variable1> etc.

The names of one or more QuickFile variables to be re-initialized.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"RESET" link RESET}
@endnode
@node INSRECORD "Macro function: INSRECORD"
@toc DBase

@{b}INSRECORD@{ub}

Inserts a new record, which becomes the current record. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used. If the record to be inserted would result in a duplicate index key in a UNIQUE index that is the current index, an error message is displayed and the operation fails.

Returns 0.

@{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD} is normally used to set desired field values before this function. All fields not set with PUTFIELD retain their values from the current existing record (if any), unless they are cleared using @{"CLRRECORD" link CLRRECORD} first.
@endnode
@node INT "Macro function: INT"
@toc Numerical

@{b}INT(<number>)@{ub}

Returns <number> rounded to the nearest integer.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <number>

Any integer or floating point value in the range -2147483647 to 2147483647.
@endnode
@node IXFIELD "Macro function: IXFIELD"
@toc DBase

@{b}IXFIELD("<index>",<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of index fields in <index> for the current database, or the name of the index field corresponding to <integer> in <index>. If no database has been loaded into the window, an error message is displayed.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <index>

The name of an existing index (including SELECTED or SORTED) for the current database.

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of index fields in <index>;

Any integer in the range of 1 to IXFIELD(0) to obtain the name of the corresponding index field.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"INDEX" link INDEX}
@endnode
@node LANGUAGE "Macro function: LANGUAGE"
@toc Info

@{b}LANGUAGE@{ub}

Returns the name of the language locale in use by the system, which can be used to enable localization of macros.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'LANGUAGE'
  if result = 'français.language' then fr=1
  else fr=0
   ...
  if fr=1 then 'MESSAGE("Bonjour !")'
  else 'MESSAGE("Welcome !")'
@endnode
@node LASTPOS "Macro function: LASTPOS"
@toc String

@{b}LASTPOS("<substring>","<string>")@{ub}

Returns the starting position of the last occurance of <substring> within <string>, or 0 if <substring> can't be located. The search is case-sensitive.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <substring>

Any character string.

  <string>

Any character string.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'LASTPOS("Mississippi","miss")'

    >>> 0

  'LASTPOS("Mississippi","issi")'

    >>> 5

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LEFT" link LEFT}  @{"LEN" link LEN}  @{"POS" link POS}  @{"RIGHT" link RIGHT}  @{"SUBSTRING" link SUBSTRING}
@endnode
@node LEFT "Macro function: LEFT"
@toc String

@{b}LEFT("<string>",<length>)@{ub}

Returns the leftmost <length> characters of <string>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string.

  <len>

An integer in the range of 1 to the number of characters in <string>, indicating how many characters are to be returned.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'LEFT("Johnston",3)'

    >>> Joh

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LASTPOS" link LASTPOS}  @{"LEN" link LEN}  @{"POS" link POS}  @{"RIGHT" link RIGHT}  @{"SUBSTRING" link SUBSTRING}
@endnode
@node LEN "Macro function: LEN"
@toc String

@{b}LEN("<string>")@{ub}

Return the length of <string> in number of characters.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'LEN("1234567890")

    >>> 10

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LASTPOS" link LASTPOS}  @{"LEFT" link LEFT}  @{"POS" link POS}  @{"RIGHT" link RIGHT}  @{"SUBSTRING" link SUBSTRING}
@endnode
@node LOAD "Macro function: LOAD"
@toc Windows

@{b}LOAD("<database>")@{ub}

Loads <database> into the current window, replacing the database currently open (if any).

Returns 0 if <database> was successfully loaded but no data was found; returns 1 if both <database> and data were successfully loaded.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <database>

The name of an existing database definition file.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"OPEN" link OPEN}
@endnode
@node LOADVIEW "Macro function: LOADVIEW"
@toc Windows

@{b}LOADVIEW("<view>")@{ub}

Loads <view>, but does not make it the current view.

Returns 1 if <view> was successfully loaded.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <view>

The name of an existing view file, including extension (if any), for the current database. The path need not be specified unless <view> does not reside in the current database's home directory. If a relative path is specified, it is assumed to be relative to QuickFile's current directory.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'LOADVIEW("Product.View")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEVIEW" link FREEVIEW}  @{"SAVEVIEW" link SAVEVIEW}  @{"SETVIEW" link SETVIEW}  @{"VIEW" link VIEW}  @{"VIEWFORM" link VIEWFORM}
@endnode
@node LOCK "Macro function: LOCK"
@toc Control

@{b}LOCK@{ub}

Locks user input out of the current window for the duration of an ARexx script, or until @{"UNLOCK" link UNLOCK} is used.@{b} Note@{ub} that this function cannot be used in a direct macro due to the risk of completely locking the user out. An ARexx script can be halted by running the ARexx DOS command HI.

Returns 0.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"UNLOCK" link UNLOCK}
@endnode
@node LOWER "Macro function: LOWER"
@toc String

@{b}LOWER("<string>")@{ub}

Returns <string> converted to lower-case.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"UPPER" link UPPER}
@endnode
@node MAP "Macro function: MAP"
@toc Control

@{b}MAP("<keys>","<macro>")@{ub}

Assigns <macro> to <keys> globally (for all opened windows) for the remainder of the current session, or until @{"UNMAP" link UNMAP} is used. <keys> may also be reassigned at any time.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <keys>

A single key or key combination description which must include, at a minimum, one of the following keys:

    F1 through F10
    A through Z
    1 through 0
    `[];',./

The key may be optionally preceeded by one or more of the following qualifier keys, in any order:

    SHIFT
    CTRL
    ALT

All keys used in the description may be entered in upper or lower case, and must separated from each other by a single dash. For example:

    a
    shift-a
    ctrl-shift-a
    shift-ctrl-alt-a

@{b}Note@{ub} that to use any character that is normally obtained by pressing SHIFT with the appropriate key, the description must be expressed as SHIFT plus the corresponding unshifted character, even for characters which are also available on the numeric keypad without pressing SHIFT. For example, to use the asterisk (*), the description must include "shift-8".

  <macro>

Any QuickFile function or operation, which, for this purpose, must be surrounded by double-quote marks.@{b} Note@{ub} that any character string values within <macro> must be DOUBLE-double quoted for use here. If <macro> begins with the equal sign (=), the result, if any, will be displayed automatically.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

  'MAP("ctrl-]","WINTOBACK")'
  'MAP("ctrl-[","WINTOFRONT")'

  'MAP("ctrl-alt-shift-1","MESSAGE(""Get to work!"")")'

  'MAP("ctrl-shift-8","=FULLNAME")'

@{b}See also:@{ub}

  @{"READMAP" link READMAP}
@endnode
@node MESSAGE "Macro function: MESSAGE"
@toc Requesters

@{b}MESSAGE("<message>")@{ub}

Displays a requester with <message> and a button labelled OK.

Returns 0.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

Any character string.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  MESSAGE("This is one message"+CHR(10)+"with two lines.")
@endnode
@node NBFIELDS "Macro function: NBFIELDS"
@toc DBase

@{b}NBFIELDS@{ub}

Returns the number of fields defined for the current database, or 0 if no database has been loaded into the current window.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FIELD" link FIELD}  @{"FIELDLENGTH" link FIELDLENGTH}  @{"FIELDTYPE" link FIELDTYPE}
@endnode
@node NBRECORDS "Macro function: NBRECORDS"
@toc DBase

@{b}NBRECORDS@{ub}

Returns the number of records in the current index in the current database, or -1 if no database has been loaded into the current window.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"CURRENTREC" link CURRENTREC}  @{"GOTO" link GOTO}  @{"NEXT" link NEXT}  @{"SELECTREC" link SELECTREC}
@endnode
@node NEWSEARCH "Macro function: NEWSEARCH"
@toc DBase

@{b}NEWSEARCH("<field>","<operator>","<value1>"[,"<value2>"])@{ub}

Discards any previously established search criteria and begins specification of new criteria. @{"ADDSEARCH" link ADDSEARCH} is used to add additional criteria if desired, and @{"DOSEARCH" link DOSEARCH} begins the actual search.

Returns the number of criteria established so far, which should always be 1 for this function. . @{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field>

The name of an existing field in the current database.

  <operator>

Any one of the following search @{"operators" link MatchOp}:

    LIKE
    EQUAL
    BETWEEN
    NOTLIKE
    NOTEQUAL
    SOUNDS

  <value1>

The primary search value, always entered as a string, even when the search is to be performed in numerical fields.

  <value2>

The secondary search value, always entered as a string.

For more details, see the @{"FIELD SELECTION DETAILS" link CriteriaReq} requester.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* find all current memberships that expire in March */
  'NEWSEARCH("status","equal","current")'
  'ADDSEARCH("and","expirdate","between","01-mar-95","31-mar-95")'
  'DOSEARCH'
@endnode
@node NEXT "Macro function: NEXT"
@toc DBase

@{b}NEXT(<integer>)@{ub}

Moves <integer> records forward or backward through the current index in the current database. If <integer> is outside the range of records in the database, the new position will be the first or last record in the current index. If no database has been loaded into the current window, an error message is displayed. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.

Returns 1 if successful in moving exactly <integer> records, otherwise returns 0.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

A positive or negative integer, which should be in the range of existing records in the current index. Smaller and larger integers may be used, but may yield inconsistent results.@{b} Note@{ub} that QuickFile databases are currently limited to 16777215 records.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Move to the last record in a FORM view */
  'NEXT(NBRECORDS)'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"CURRENTREC" link CURRENTREC}  @{"GETSELECTED" link GETSELECTED}  @{"GOTO" link GOTO}  @{"NBRECORDS" link NBRECORDS}
@endnode
@node OPEN "Macro function: OPEN"
@toc Windows

@{b}OPEN("<database>")@{ub}

Opens a new database window; optionally loads <database> (if it exists) into it.@{b} Note@{ub} that the new window does not automatically become the current window.

Returns the number of the ARexx port for the new window.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <database>

A valid path/name for an existing database definition file to be loaded, or an empty string to not load a database into the new window. The path may be relative to QuickFile's current directory.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* If this is to be the third window open */
  'OPEN("AddressBook/AddressBook")'

    >>> 2

  if result > 0 then do
    port = 'QuickFile.'p
    address value port
  end
  else 'MESSAGE("Could not open ""AddressBook/AddressBook""")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LOAD" link LOAD}
@endnode
@node PATH "Macro function: PATH"
@toc Windows

@{b}PATH@{ub}

Returns the full path of the current database. If no database has been loaded into the current window, the program's current path is returned.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILE" link FILE}  @{"FILENAME" link FILENAME}  @{"FULLNAME" link FULLNAME}
@endnode
@node PORTNAME "Macro function: PORTNAME"

@{b}PORTNAME(<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of existing QuickFile ARexx ports, or the port name corresponding to <integer>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of existing QuickFile ARexx ports;

An integer in the range of 1 to PORTNAME(0) to obtain the name of the corresponding port.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILE" link FILE}  @{"REXXPORT" link REXXPORT}  @{"SELFILE" link SELFILE}  @{"SELPORT" link SELPORT}  @{"SENDCOMMAND" link SENDCOMMAND}
@endnode
@node POS "Macro function: POS"
@toc String

@{b}POS("<substring>","<string>")@{ub}

Returns the starting position of <substring> in <string>, or 0 if <substring> is not found. The search is case-sensitive.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <substring>

Any character string.

  <string>

Any character string.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

  'POS("oh","Johnston")'

    >>> 2

  'POS("Oh","Johnston")'

    >>> 0

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LASTPOS" link LASTPOS}  @{"LEFT" link LEFT}  @{"LEN" link LEN}  @{"RIGHT" link RIGHT}  @{"SUBSTRING" link SUBSTRING}
@endnode
@node PUTFIELD "Macro function: PUTFIELD"
@toc DBase

@{b}PUTFIELD("<field>","<string-value>")@{ub}

Sets the contents of <field> to <string-value> for the current record or a new record. <string-value> must be compatible with <field>'s type. Changes to existing records do not take effect until @{"UPDATEREC" link UPDATEREC} has been used. New records are inserted using @{"INSRECORD" link INSRECORD} after all desired fields have been set.

Returns an empty string if successful, or an error message if not.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field>

The name of an existing field in the current database.

  <string-value>

A character string, or numerical value expressed as a character string, that is compatible with the field @{"type" link Types}. For CYCLE fields, this should be a string matching one of the available values defined for the field. Matching is not case sensitive.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  newdate = '31-Mar-1996'
  'PUTFIELD("expiry date","'newdate'"):UPDATEREC'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"CLRRECORD" link CLRRECORD}  @{"CYCLESTRING" link CYCLESTRING}  @{"GETFIELD" link GETFIELD}  @{"GETFIELDSTR" link GETFIELDSTR}  @{"STRINGCYCLE" link STRINGCYCLE}
@endnode
@node READDEF "Macro function: READDEF"
@toc Control

@{b}READDEF("<function>")@{ub}

Returns the definition of user-defined <function>, which must have been previously defined with @{"DEF" link DEF}. If <function> does not exist, an empty string is returned.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <function>

The name of a previously defined user function.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'DEF MAX(A,B) = IF(A>B,A,B)'
  'READDEF("MAX")'

    >>> IF(A>B,A,B)

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"DEF" link DEF}
@endnode
@node READMAP "Macro function: READMAP"
@toc Control

@{b}READMAP("<keys>")@{ub}

Returns the macro that was previously assigned to <keys> with @{"MAP" link MAP}. If no macro has been assigned to <keys>, an empty string is returned.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <keys>

A single key or key combination description. See @{"MAP" link MAP} for details.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

  'MAP("ctrl-shift-8","=FULLNAME")'
  'READMAP("ctrl-shift-8")'

    >>> =FULLNAME

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"UNMAP" link UNMAP}
@endnode
@node REFRESH "Macro function: REFRESH"
@toc Windows

@{b}REFRESH@{ub}

Updates the current window display with any changes that may have resulted from recent macro functions.

Returns 0.

The window is updated automatically, if necessary, upon completion of every macro, so use of this function is only required if it is desired that changes become visible prior to the end of a macro. The following functions result in changes to the window display that do not take effect unless REFRESH is used, or until macro completion:

  @{"DELRECORD" link DELRECORD}  @{"DOSEARCH " link DOSEARCH}  @{"FREEINDEX" link FREEINDEX}  @{"FREEVIEW " link FREEVIEW}  @{"GOTO     " link GOTO}  @{"INSRECORD" link INSRECORD}
  @{"NEXT     " link NEXT}  @{"SETINDEX " link SETINDEX}  @{"UPDATEREC" link UPDATEREC}

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'NEXT(15):REFRESH'
@endnode
@node REPORT "Macro function: REPORT"
@toc DBase

@{b}REPORT(<integer>,"{PRINTER|<string>}","<title>")@{ub}

Prints the report defined for the current view, if one was defined, to the preferences printer or to the current window, processing <integer> records starting with the current record or all remaining records in the current index, and temporarily overriding the title specified in the view's report definition with <title> if desired; returns <integer>. The database window is advanced <integer> records upon completion of the printed report, unless the last record is reached first.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

A positive integer indicating the number of records to process, starting with the current record and up to the last record in the current index;

Or -1 to process all remaining records in the index.

  {PRINTER|<string>}

PRINTER to send the report to the preferences printer;

Any other string to send it to the current window.

  <title>

Up to 50 characters to be used instead of the title defined for the current view's report definition (which is not changed);

An empty string ("") to use the view's defined title.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* To send a report of all records to the printer */
  'REPORT(-1,"printer","Report Title over-ride")'

  /* To send a report of the next 10 records to the window */
  'REPORT(10,"","")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LOADVIEW" link LOADVIEW}  @{"SETVIEW" link SETVIEW}
@endnode
@node REQBASE "Macro function: REQBASE"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQBASE("<message>")@{ub}

Displays a requester with <message> at the top and buttons with the names of each opened database, and "NoBase" for each empty database window.

Returns the name of the ARexx port corresponding to the button selected, or an empty string if the requester is cancelled by selecting its CLOSE gadget or by pressing ESC.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear at the top of the requester.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"REQLIST" link REQLIST}  @{"REQLISTSTR" link REQLISTSTR}  @{"SELECT" link SELECT}
@endnode
@node REQFIELD "Macro function: REQFIELD"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQFIELD("<message>","{NOCALC|<string>}")@{ub}

Displays a requester with <message> at the top, a listview of all, or only non-calculated, existing fields in the current database, and buttons labelled OK and CANCEL.

Returns the name of the selected field, or an empty string if the requester is cancelled.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear above the listview.

  {NOCALC|<string>}

NOCALC to exclude calculated fields from the listview;

Any other string to include calculated fields.
@endnode
@node REQFILE "Macro function: REQFILE"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQFILE("<message>","<path>","<file>")@{ub}

Displays a standard file requester with <message> in the title bar, and open initially to <path> and <file>.

Returns the specified path and filename together as one string, which can be an empty string if no path or filename were specified, as long as the path exists (the filename need not exist). If the requester is cancelled or the specified path does not exist, an empty string is returned.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear in the title bar of the requester window, which will be truncated if it exceeds the width allowed by the window.

  <path>

An initial default path for the requester. If non-existent, the requester will still open, but will report an error.

  <file>

An initial default filename for the requester, which need not exist.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'REQFILE("Choose a file","Work:QuickFile","")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"REQPATH" link REQPATH}
@endnode
@node REQLIST "Macro function: REQLIST"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQLIST("<message>","<item1>"[,"<item2>"...])@{ub}

Displays a custom requester with <message> at the top and <item1>, etc., in a listview.

Returns an integer corresponding to the listview item selected, or 0 if cancelled.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear above the listview.

  <item1> etc.

One or more items to appear in the listview.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'REQLIST("Pick an item","One","Two","Three","Four","Five")'
  /* User picks "Three" */

    >>> 3

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"REQLISTSTR" link REQLISTSTR}  @{"SELECT" link SELECT}
@endnode
@node REQLISTSTR "Macro function: REQLISTSTR"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQLISTSTR("<message>","<item1>"[,"<item2>"...])@{ub}

Identical to @{"REQLIST" link REQLIST}, except that it returns the actual selected <item> string, or an empty string if cancelled.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"SELECT" link SELECT}
@endnode
@node REQNUMBER "Macro function: REQNUMBER"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQNUMBER("<message>",<integer>,"<variable>")@{ub}

Displays an integer requester with <message> at the top and <integer> as an initial default value.

Returns the integer in the requester and sets <variable> to 1 if the requester if OK'd; returns an empty string and sets <variable> to 0 if cancelled.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear above the integer string gadget.

  <integer>

An initial default integer in the range -2147483648 to 2147483647 for the requester.

  <variable>

The name of a QuickFile or ARexx variable to be set according to which button is selected.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"ASKNUM" link ASKNUM}  @{"ASKTEXT" link ASKTEXT}  @{"REQSTRING" link REQSTRING}
@endnode
@node REQPATH "Macro function: REQPATH"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQPATH("<message>","<path>","<variable>")@{ub}

Displays a standard path requester with <message> in the title bar, which
opens to <path> by default.

Returns the specified path, which can be an empty string if no path was specified, as long as it exists and sets <variable> to 1. If the requester is cancelled or the specified path does not exist, an empty string is returned and <variable> is set to 0.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear in the title bar of the requester window, which will be truncated if it exceeds the width allowed by the window.

  <path>

An existing initial default path for the requester;

An empty string to have the requester open to Quickfile's current path.

  <variable>

The name (in UPPER CASE) of a QuickFile or ARexx variable, which will be set to 1 if the requester is OK'd with an existing path, or to 0 if the requester is cancelled or is OK'd with a non-existent path.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'REQPATH("Select a path...","Work:QuickFile","OK")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"REQFILE" link REQFILE}
@endnode
@node REQSTRING "Macro function: REQSTRING"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQSTRING("<message>","<string>","<variable>")@{ub}

Displays a string requester with <message> at the top and <string> as an initial default value.

Returns the string in the requester and sets <variable> to 1 if OK'd; returns an empty string and sets <variable> to 0 if cancelled.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear above the string gadget.

  <string>

An initial default string for the requester.

  <variable>

The name of a QuickFile or ARexx variable to be set according to which button is selected.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"ASKNUM" link ASKNUM}  @{"ASKTEXT" link ASKTEXT}  @{"REQNUMBER" link REQNUMBER}
@endnode
@node REQUEST "Macro function: REQUEST"
@toc Requesters

@{b}REQUEST("<message>")@{ub}

Displays a requester with <message> and buttons labelled OK and CANCEL.

Returns 1 if OK was selected, or 0 if CANCEL was selected.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear in the requester.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"MESSAGE" link MESSAGE}  @{"REQFILE" link REQFILE}  @{"SELECT" link SELECT}  @{"SELECTSTR" link SELECTSTR}
@endnode
@node RESET "Macro function: RESET"
@toc Control

@{b}RESET(<variable>[,...])@{ub}

Resets the value, but not the type, of all QuickFile <variables>. Numerical <variables> are reset to 0; string <variables> are reset to empty strings.

Returns the number of <variables> specified.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <variables>

One or more QuickFile variable names.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"INIT" link INIT}
@endnode
@node REXXPATH "Macro function: REXXPATH"
@toc Control

@{b}REXXPATH("<path>")@{ub}

Changes the default path used by @{"CALL" link CALL} to locate ARexx scripts, for all QuickFile windows.

Returns the current default path (prior to the change caused by this function) for ARexx scripts.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <path>

An empty string to only obtain the current default path;

A valid AmigaDOS path to change the default QuickFile ARexx script path to;@{b} Note@{ub} that no testing is performed to see if <path> exists.
@endnode
@node REXXPORT "Macro function: REXXPORT"
@toc Windows

@{b}REXXPORT("<database>")@{ub}

Returns the name of the ARexx port for the window corresponding to <database>, or the name of the current window's ARexx port, or an empty string.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <database>

An opened database definition filename (without path) to obtain the corresponding window's port;

"NoBase" to obtain the port of the first empty window;

An empty string ("") to obtain the current window's port.

If <database> exists in more than one window, only the first such window's port is returned. If <database> does not exist, an empty string is returned.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"PORTNAME" link PORTNAME}  @{"REQBASE" link REQBASE}  @{"SELFILE" link SELFILE}  @{"SELPORT" link SELPORT}  @{"SENDCOMMAND" link SENDCOMMAND}
@endnode
@node RIGHT "Macro function: RIGHT"
@toc String

@{b}RIGHT("<string>",<length>)@{ub}

Returns the rightmost <length> characters of <string>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string composed of at least one character.

  <length>

An integer in the range of 1 to the number of characters in <string>.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'RIGHT("Johnston",3)'

    >>> ton

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LASTPOS" link LASTPOS}  @{"LEFT" link LEFT}  @{"LEN" link LEN}  @{"POS" link POS}  @{"SUBSTRING" link SUBSTRING}
@endnode
@node SAVE "Macro function: SAVE"
@toc Windows

@{b}SAVE("<path>","<filename>",<blocksize>)@{ub}

Saves the current database with the specified <path>, <filename>, and <blocksize>. If using the database's current path and filename, saving only takes place if data has changed. Otherwise, if <filename> already exists in <path>, it is immediately overwritten, unless <blocksize> is 0, in which case the user is asked for confirmation. INDEX files are also saved.@{b} Note@{ub} that other miscellaneous files related to the database, such as VIEW files, STARTUP macros, saved queries, etc., are NOT saved.

Returns 0 if successful.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <path>

An existing path to save the database to.

  <filename>

A filename to save the database as.

  <blocksize>

0 to be prompted for a <blocksize> to use;

An integer in the range of the current database's maximum record size (the sum of all maximum field lengths) to 32767.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SAVE("RAM:","AddressBook",2048)'

  'SAVE(PATH,FILENAME,BLOCKSIZE)'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"BLOCKSIZE" link BLOCKSIZE}  @{"FILENAME" link FILENAME}  @{"PATH" link PATH}
@endnode
@node SAVEVIEW "Macro function: SAVEVIEW"
@toc Windows

@{b}SAVEVIEW("<view>","<file>")@{ub}

Saves <view>, which must have already been loaded, to <file>.

Returns 1 if successful.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <view>

The name of a view that has already been loaded for the current database, including the extension, if any.

  <file>

An (optional) path and (required) filename to save the view as. If no path is specified, the current database's home directory is used.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SAVEVIEW("Old.View","DB/New/New.View")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEVIEW" link FREEVIEW}  @{"LOADVIEW" link LOADVIEW}  @{"SETVIEW" link SETVIEW}  @{"VIEW" link VIEW}  @{"VIEWFORM" link VIEWFORM}
@endnode
@node SCRHEIGHT "Macro function: SCRHEIGHT"
@toc Info

@{b}SCRHEIGHT@{ub}

Returns the height of the screen that QuickFile is running on, which should be the default public screen.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"SCRMODE" link SCRMODE}  @{"SCRWIDTH" link SCRWIDTH}
@endnode
@node SCRMODE "Macro function: SCRMODE"
@toc Info

@{b}SCRMODE@{ub}

Returns the ID number of the mode of the screen that QuickFile is running on.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"SCRHEIGHT" link SCRHEIGHT}  @{"SCRWIDTH" link SCRWIDTH}
@endnode
@node SCRWIDTH "Macro function: SCRWIDTH"
@toc Info

@{b}SCRWIDTH@{ub}

Returns the width of the screen that QuickFile is running on, which should be the default public screen.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"SCRHEIGHT" link SCRHEIGHT}  @{"SCRMODE" link SCRMODE}
@endnode
@node SECURITY "Macro function: SECURITY"
@toc Control

@{b}SECURITY(<loops>)@{ub}

Sets the maximum number <loops> that can be carried out by QuickFile functions @{"FOR" link FOR} and @{"WHILE" link WHILE} before halting them. As all macros inherit a default SECURITY setting of 500, this function only need be used if a different setting is desired.@{b} Note@{ub} that even a seemingly endless loop can be interrupted by the user by pressing CTRL-ALT-ESC in the window affected by the macro, as long as the window has not been @{"LOCKed" link LOCK}.

Returns the value that was in use prior to use of this function.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <loops>

An integer in the range of 1 to 2147483647;

0 to return the current value without changing it.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"UNLOCK" link UNLOCK}
@endnode
@node SELECT "Macro function: SELECT"
@toc Requesters

@{b}SELECT("<message>","<button1>"[,...])@{ub}

Displays a custom requester with <message> at the top and a variable number of user-defined buttons. If there are four or more buttons, they are aligned vertically, otherwise horizontally.

Returns an integer corresponding to the button selected, or 0 if the requester is closed without a button selected.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <message>

A message to appear above the buttons.

  <button1> etc.

One or more button labels.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SELECT("Pick a card...","Ace","King","Queen","Jack")'
  /* User selects button labelled "Queen" */

    >>> 3

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"REQBASE" link REQBASE}  @{"REQLIST" link REQLIST}  @{"REQLISTSTR" link REQLISTSTR}  @{"SELECTSTR" link SELECTSTR}
@endnode
@node SELECTSTR "Macro function: SELECTSTR"
@toc Requesters

@{b}SELECTSTR("<message>","<button1>"[,...])@{ub}

Identical in usage to @{"SELECT" link SELECT}, but returns the actual label of the button selected, or an empty string if the requester is closed without a button selected.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"REQBASE" link REQBASE}  @{"REQLIST" link REQLIST}  @{"REQLISTSTR" link REQLISTSTR}
@endnode
@node SELECTREC "Macro function: SELECTREC"
@toc DBase

@{b}SELECTREC@{ub}

Adds the current record to the SELECTED index if SELECTED is not the current index; otherwise the current record is removed from SELECTED. This function makes it possible to perform more customized queries that are not available thorugh the QUERY requester or the @{"DOSEARCH" link DOSEARCH} function, such as matching records on a case-sensitive basis.

Returns 1 for each record successfully added to SELECTED, -1 for each record successfully removed, and 0 for each failure (record already added, no more records in index, etc.).

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Match and select all records having "The" (case-sensitive) */
  /* AFTER the first character in the field "Comment" */
  'SETINDEX("selected"):FREEINDEX:SETINDEX(INDEX(0))'
  'R=NBRECORDS:C=GETFIELD("comment")'
  'FOR(0,CURRENTREC<R,IF(POS("The",C)>1,SELECTREC,0),NEXT)'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"DOSEARCH" link DOSEARCH}  @{"SETINDEX" link SETINDEX}  @{"SHOWALL" link SHOWALL}
@endnode
@node SELFILE "Macro function: SELFILE"
@toc Windows

@{b}SELFILE("<database>")@{ub}

Activates the window corresponding to <database> and brings it to the front, but does not cause it to becaome the current window (the current port address is not changed). If there are several windows with identical <databases>, only the first one is affected.

Returns the name of the corresponding ARexx port, or an empty string if <database> could not be located.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <database>

The name of an opened database definition file without path;

"NoBase" for an existing empty window.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILE" link FILE}  @{"PORTNAME" link PORTNAME}  @{"REQBASE" link REQBASE}  @{"REXXPORT" link REXXPORT}  @{"SELPORT" link SELPORT}
@endnode
@node SELPORT "Macro function: SELPORT"
@toc Windows

@{b}SELPORT("<port>")@{ub}

Activates the window corresponding to <port> and brings it to the front, but does not cause it to become the current window (the current port address is not changed).

Returns 1 if successful, 0 otherwise.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <port>

The name of an opened database window's ARexx port.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FILE" link FILE}  @{"PORTNAME" link PORTNAME}  @{"REQBASE" link REQBASE}  @{"REXXPORT" link REXXPORT}  @{"SELFILE" link SELFILE}  @{"SENDCOMMAND" link SENDCOMMAND}
@endnode
@node SENDCOMMAND "Macro function: SENDCOMMAND"
@toc Control

@{b}SENDCOMMAND("<port>","<commandstring>")@{ub}

Sends <commandstring> etc. to the QuickFile database window corresponding to <port> for processing, for which ARexx need not be available.

Returns <port>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <port>

The name of an existing QuickFile ARexx/message port.

  <commandstring>

A string containing one or more valid QuickFile macro functions and/or operations.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Use the value of a variable for this window in another window */
  'A="Test":SENDCOMMAND("QuickFile.1","="""+A+"""")'

  'SENDCOMMAND("QuickFile.1","WINTOFRONT")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"PORTNAME" link PORTNAME}  @{"REXXPORT" link REXXPORT}  @{"SELPORT" link SELPORT}
@endnode
@node SETINDEX "Macro function: SETINDEX"
@toc DBase

@{b}SETINDEX("<index>")@{ub}

Causes <index> to become the new current index for the current database, if it exists. The display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.

Returns the name of the (previous) current index.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <index>

The name of an existing index in the current database, including SELECTED and SORTED (if it exists);

An empty string to only obtain the name of the current index without changing it.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SETINDEX("Sorted")'

  'MESSAGE("The current index is «"+SETINDEX("")+"».")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEINDEX" link FREEINDEX}  @{"INDEX" link INDEX}  @{"SHOWALL" link SHOWALL}
@endnode
@node SETVIEW "Macro function: SETVIEW"
@toc DBase

@{b}SETVIEW("<view>")@{ub}

Causes <view> to become the (new) current view for the current database, if it exists and was previously loaded. The display is updated as necessary immediately.

Returns the name of the (previous) current view, or an empty string if <view> could not be located

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <view>

The name of an existing view for the current database which has already been loaded, including the extension (if any);

An empty string to only obtain the name of the current view without changing it.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Starting view is "First.View" */
  'SETVIEW("Next.View")'

    >>> First.View

  'SETVIEW("")'

    >>> Next.View

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEVIEW" link FREEVIEW}  @{"LOADVIEW" link LOADVIEW}  @{"SAVEVIEW" link SAVEVIEW}  @{"VIEW" link VIEW}  @{"VIEWFORM" link VIEWFORM}
@endnode
@node SGN "Macro function: SGN"
@toc Numerical

@{b}SGN(<number>)@{ub}

Returns the sign of <number>:

  1 if <number> is positive
  0 if <number> is 0
 -1 if <number> is negative

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <number>

Any integer in the range -2147483648 to 2147483647;

Any floating point value.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SGN(-45372.06)'

    >>> -1
@endnode
@node SHOWALL "Macro function: SHOWALL"
@toc DBase

@{b}SHOWALL(<integer>)@{ub}

Switches between the current permanent index and the SELECTED index, depending on the argument provided.

Returns <integer>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to show only SELECTED records;

Any other integer to show ALL records.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEINDEX" link FREEINDEX}  @{"SETINDEX" link SETINDEX}
@endnode
@node SORT "Macro function: SORT"
@toc DBase

@{b}SORT("<field1>","{A|D}"[,"<field2>","{A|D}"...])@{ub}

Sorts all records in the current index by <field1> in the sequence indicated by {A|D}, then by <field2>, etc.; places the records in a temporary index named SORTED and makes it the current index.

Returns the last argument given.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <field1> etc.

The field(s) to sort by, in order of precedence.

  {A|D}

Any string beginning with 'A' for ascending order, for the preceeding <field>;

Any string beginning with 'D' for descending order.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SORT("lastname","d","firstname","a")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEINDEX" link FREEINDEX}  @{"SETINDEX" link SETINDEX}
@endnode
@node STR "Macro function: STR"
@toc Convert

@{b}STR(<number>)@{ub}

Returns <number> as a character string. which can then be used as input for functions requiring string arguments.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <number>

An integer in the range -2147483648 to 2147483647;

A floating point value with no more than 15 digits (non-decimal and decimal combined).

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'MESSAGE("You entered "+STR(ASKNUM("Enter a number",0))+"!")'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"TIMESTRING" link TIMESTRING}  @{"TIMEVAL" link TIMEVAL}  @{"VAL" link VAL}
@endnode
@node STRINGCYCLE "Macro function: STRINGCYCLE"
@toc DBase

@{b}STRINGCYCLE("<cyclefield>","<string>")@{ub}

Returns the string number corresponding to <string> for <cyclefield> in the current database. Numbering starts at 0 for the first string. The string used for <cyclefield> in the current record is not changed.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <cyclefield>

The name of an existing CYCLE field in the current database.

  <string>

One of the strings specified in the expression for <cyclefield>.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* CYCLE field = "Color"; Expression = "Red,Blue,Gold" */
  'STRINGCYCLE("color","gold")'

    >>> 2

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"CYCLESTRING" link CYCLESTRING}.
@endnode
@node SUBSTRING "Macro function: SUBSTRING"
@toc String

@{b}SUBSTRING("<string>",<position>,<length>)@{ub}

Returns a sub-string of <string>, beginning at <position> and of <length> characters.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string of at least one character.

  <position>

An integer in the range 1 to the number of characters in <string>, indicating the starting position of the desired substring.

  <length>

An integer in the range 1 to the number of characters in <string> minus <position> plus 1.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'SUBSTRING("Johnston",2,2)'

    >>> oh

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"LASTPOS" link LASTPOS}  @{"LEFT" link LEFT}  @{"LEN" link LEN}  @{"POS" link POS}  @{"RIGHT" link RIGHT}
@endnode
@node TIMESTRING "Macro function: TIMESTRING"
@toc Convert

@{b}TIMESTRING(<seconds>)@{ub}

Returns a time string, expressed in total hours, minutes and seconds (hh:mm:ss) corresponding to <seconds>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <seconds>

An integer or floating point value in the range 0 to 2147483647.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'TIMESTRING(3600)'

    >>> 01:00:00

  'TIMESTRING(2147483647)'

    >>> 596523:14:07

  'MESSAGE("The sum is "+TIMESTRING(GETFIELD("time1")+GETFIELD("time2")))'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"STR" link STR}  @{"TIMEVAL" link TIMEVAL}
@endnode
@node TIMEVAL "Macro function: TIMEVAL"
@toc Convert

@{b}TIMEVAL("<timestring>")@{ub}

Returns a floating point value representing the total number of seconds in <timestring>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <timestring>

A time string consisiting of at least hours and a separator character, optionally followed by minutes, optionally followed by a separator character and seconds. Valid separator characters are spaces ( ), colons (:), and periods (.). The string should be in the range 00:00:00 to 27777:46:40.@{b} Note@{ub} that values outside this range, but within the range 00:00:00 to 2147483647:59:59, will return somewhat inaccurate results without generating errors, while errors will result from values outside the latter range.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'TIMEVAL("1 ")'

    >>> 3600.000000000

  'TIMEVAL("1.2")' /* or */ 'TIMEVAL("1.02")'

    >>> 3720.000000000

  'TIMEVAL("1:20")'

    >>> 4800.000000000

  'TIMEVAL("1:20.3")' /* or */ 'TIMEVAL("1 20 3")'

    >>> 4803.000000000

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"TIMESTRING" link TIMESTRING}
@endnode
@node TITLE "Macro function: TITLE"
@toc Windows

@{b}TITLE("<title>")@{ub}

Causes <title> to appear in the title bar of the current window, or causes the title bar to revert to its normal state (displaying the current view and index names, record number, etc.).

Returns <title>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <title>

Any character string of at least one character to be displayed, which will be truncated without reporting any errors if it exceeds the displayable length allowed by the window;

An empty string to have the normal title bar text reappear.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'TITLE("Processing...Record "+STR(CURRENTREC)+" of "+STR(NBRECORDS))'
  ...
  'TITLE("")' /* Restores the normal title text */
@endnode
@node UNLOCK "Macro function: UNLOCK"
@toc Control

@{b}UNLOCK@{ub}

Restores the ability for user input to the current window if it was previously prevented by use of @{"LOCK" link LOCK}, else does nothing.

Returns 0.
@endnode
@node UNMAP "Macro function: UNMAP"
@toc Control

@{b}UNMAP("<keys>")@{ub}

Deletes the macro, if any, that was programmed to <keys> with @{"MAP" link MAP}.

Returns <keys>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <keys>

A string describing the key or key combination to which the macro to be deleted was programmed. See @{"MAP" link MAP} for details.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'UNMAP("shift-ctrl-a")' /* or */ 'UNMAP("ctrl-shift-a")'
  'UNMAP("alt-u")'
  'UNMAP("f6")'

@{b}See also:@{ub}

  @{"READMAP" link READMAP}
@endnode
@node UPDATEREC "Macro function: UPDATEREC"
@toc DBase

@{b}UPDATEREC@{ub}

Updates the current record with any changes that were made using @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}, unless the changes would result in creating a duplicate index key in a unique index. The updated record is not necessarily written to disk at this time, and the display is not updated until the macro completes unless @{"REFRESH" link REFRESH} is used.@{b} Note@{ub} that when changing the value of one or more index fields via macro, this function should be used only once per record, after all desired fields have been modified. Otherwise, the first use of UPDATEREC may cause the current record to be moved to a different position in the same index, in which case it will no longer be the current record.

Returns 0 if successful, or an error message if not.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'PUTFIELD("ExpiryDate","31-Mar-95")'
  'UPDATEREC'

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"INSRECORD" link INSRECORD}
@endnode
@node UPPER "Macro function: UPPER"
@toc String

@{b}UPPER("<string>")@{ub}

Returns <string> converted to UPPER CASE.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <string>

Any character string.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'UPPER("which case is this?")'

    >>> WHICH CASE IS THIS?

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"LOWER" link LOWER}
@endnode
@node VAL "Macro function: VAL"
@toc Convert

@{b}VAL("<numberstring>")@{ub}

Returns <numberstring> converted to an actual decimal value.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <numberstring>

Any character string which begins with a valid decimal expression, or a dollar sign ($) and a valid hexadecimal expression, optionally followed by any number of additional characters (which will be ignored) that must be separated from the expression by at least one space.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'VAL("14")'

    >>> 14

  'VAL("14.5")'

    >>> 14.500000000

  'VAL("$14.5")'

    >>> 20.312500000

  'VAL("$5F")'

    >>> 95

  'VAL("12345 here''s some more text")'

    >>> 12345

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"STR" link STR}  @{"TIMESTRING" link TIMESTRING}  @{"TIMEVAL" link TIMEVAL}
@endnode
@node VERSION "Macro function: VERSION"
@toc Info

@{b}VERSION@{ub}

Returns QuickFile's current version number, which can be used to determine if a macro can be executed or not.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  ver.min = 3.26
  'VERSION'
  ver = result
  if ver < ver.min then do
      'MESSAGE("Minimum version required by this script is 'ver.min'.")'
      exit
  end
@endnode
@node VIEW "Macro function: VIEW"
@toc DBase

@{b}VIEW(<integer>)@{ub}

Returns the number of loaded views for the current database, or the name of the loaded view corresponding to <integer>.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to obtain the number of loaded views;

An integer in the range of 1 to VIEW(0) to obtain the name of the corresponding loaded view.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEVIEW" link FREEVIEW}  @{"LOADVIEW" link LOADVIEW}  @{"SAVEVIEW" link SAVEVIEW}  @{"SETVIEW" link SETVIEW}  @{"VIEWFORM" link VIEWFORM}
@endnode
@node VIEWFORM "Macro function: VIEWFORM"
@toc DBase

@{b}VIEWFORM(<integer>)@{ub}

Switches the current view type to LIST or FORM; returns 1 if the previous type was FORM, or 0 if it was LIST.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

  <integer>

0 to set the view type to LIST;

Any other integer to set it to FORM.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  'VIEWFORM(1)'      /* Sets to FORM mode */
  mode = result      /* Remember the original mode */
  ...                /* Perform other actions */
  'VIEWFORM('mode')' /* Returns setting to original mode */

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"FREEVIEW" link FREEVIEW}  @{"LOADVIEW" link LOADVIEW}  @{"SAVEVIEW" link SAVEVIEW}  @{"SETVIEW" link SETVIEW}  @{"VIEW" link VIEW}
@endnode
@node WHILE "Macro function: WHILE"
@toc Control

@{b}WHILE(<continue_condition>,<action1>[,...])@{ub}

Initiates a loop, performing all <actions> as long as <continue_condition> is met, or until the @{"SECURITY" link SECURITY} level has been reached. This function is identical to @{"FOR" link FOR}, but without FOR's first argument.

Returns the result of the final <action> performed.

@{b}Inputs@{ub}

See FOR for details.

@{b}Example@{ub}

  /* Select the current record and next nine records */
  'A=0:WHILE(A<10,A=A+1,SELECTREC,NEXT(1))'
@endnode
@node WINHEIGHT "Macro function: WINHEIGHT"
@toc Windows

@{b}WINHEIGHT@{ub}

Returns the height of the current database window.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"WINLEFT" link WINLEFT}  @{"WINTOP" link WINTOP}  @{"WINWIDTH" link WINWIDTH}
@endnode
@node WINLEFT "Macro function: WINLEFT"
@toc Windows

@{b}WINLEFT@{ub}

Returns the position of the left edge current database window.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"WINHEIGHT" link WINHEIGHT}  @{"WINTOP" link WINTOP}  @{"WINWIDTH" link WINWIDTH}
@endnode
@node WINTOBACK "Macro function: WINTOBACK"
@toc Windows

@{b}WINTOBACK@{ub}

Sends the current database window to the back.

Returns 0.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"WINTOFRONT" link WINTOFRONT}
@endnode
@node WINTOFRONT "Macro function: WINTOFRONT"
@toc Windows

@{b}WINTOFRONT@{ub}

Activates the current database window and brings it to the front.

Returns 0.

@{b}See Also@{ub}

  @{"WINTOBACK" link WINTOBACK}
@endnode
@node WINTOP "Macro function: WINTOP"
@toc Windows

@{b}WINTOP@{ub}

Returns the position of the top edge of the current database window.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"WINLEFT" link WINLEFT}  @{"WINHEIGHT" link WINHEIGHT}  @{"WINWIDTH" link WINWIDTH}
@endnode
@node WINWIDTH "Macro function: WINWIDTH"
@toc Windows

@{b}WINWIDTH@{ub}

Returns the width of the current database window.

@{b}See also@{ub}

  @{"WINHEIGHT" link WINHEIGHT}  @{"WINLEFT" link WINLEFT}  @{"WINTOP" link WINTOP}
@endnode
@node Troubleshooting

Problem: A new @{"field" link Fields} is added to an existing database, but it is not displayed in the current @{"view" link AboutViews}.

Solution: New fields are not automatically added to previously saved views. To add them, select @{"ALTER" link Alter } from the VIEW menu.


Problem: Error message "GetRec: Rec not found" received.

Solution: This is usually due to a mismatch between the @{"index" link AboutIndexes} and data files. It can be corrected by either @{"rebuilding" link Rebuild Index} the index, or by deleting the index file (named "<file>.<index>X"), in which case it is rebuilt automatically the next time the file is opened.


Problem: A duplicate record exists in an index.

Solution: Either @{"reorganize" link Reorganise} the database, or rebuild the index.


Problem: A @{"macro" link Macros} that was intended to modify one or more fields in all records in the current index has modified some records more than once and others not at all.

Solution: This is due to the macro modifying one or more fields that are used in the current index, which results in the sequence of records possibly changing each time a record is updated. An index which does not use any of the fields to be modified should be selected as the current index, or a custom @{"sort" link Sort index} performed, prior to running the macro.


Problem: Changes to a database could not be saved due to a program error, system or power failure.

Solution: Records that were modified or inserted since the database was last saved will more than likely have to be re-done. Otherwise, the indexes should be rebuilt.@{b} Note@{ub} that due to the way buffering works, modifications to a database are not necessarily saved in the order that they occured.


Problem: Memory shortage.

Solutions include:

1) Enable MEMORY SAVE in the @{"CONFIGURATION" link Configuration} requester.

2) Define only a single index.

3) Reduce the number of buffers, temporarily in the @{"BUFFERS" link Buffers} requester, or permanently in the @{"input/output" link IO} details section of the @{"DEFINE FILE" link DefineFile} requester.@{b} Note@{ub} that this may be unacceptably slow for floppy drive users, however.

4) When using QuickFile in conjunction with an automatic compression program such as XFH, reduce the number of buffers to 3. Otherwise, the database is held in RAM: by both QuickFile and XFH.


@{b}Known Bugs, Undesireable Behaviors and Other Limitations@{ub}

Disk thrashing can occur on program startup if QuickFile is started with a database that contains images, due to QuickFile trying to load an image while AmigaGuide is scanning the QuickFile.guide file.

Unless a custom sort sequence is specified when performing a @{"query" link Query}, the sequence of records returned is always determined by the default index (the index used when the database if first opened).

Sometimes when a field is dragged off the bottom of the database window, the drag box is not erased when the mouse button is released. The display is usually redrawn properly when the horizontal scroll bar is clicked on with the mouse, or if the window is cycled.

Fields are clipped at the right window border, but if they overlap the bottom border (or top), they won't be visible at all until scrolled into view with the horizontal scroll bar.

Images are not scaled, and palettes are not remapped for @{"IMAGE" link Image} fields.

Switching views from within a @{"macro" link Macros} causes a series of window redraws to occur after the macro has completed, due to window resize messages sent by Intuition, which are not received by QuickFile until the macro is finished.

It is possible to set numerical fields to out-of-range values using the macro function @{"PUTFIELD" link PUTFIELD}. See @{"INTEGER" link Integer} and @{"TIME" link TimeField} fields.


@{b}Consulting the Author@{ub}

When writing to the @{"author" link Author} regarding a problem with QuickFile, it is highly recommended to join the next information:

 - attach a copy of the database with which the problem was experienced,
 - include which version of QuickFile was being used,
 - the system it is used on,
 - and instructions on how to duplicate the problem.
@endnode
@node Limits "Program Limits"

@{b}General Limits@{ub}

                  @{u}           Max...           @{uu}
                                       Name
  @{u}Item          @{uu}  @{u} Number @{uu}  @{u} Length @{uu}  @{u} Length @{uu}
  Fields             250       250       12
  Indexes             -         -        14
  Views               -         -        30
  Records         16777215    32767       -
  Buffers           65535       -         -
  Records/Buffer     255        -         -

@{b}Note@{ub} that <MAX RECORD LENGTH> is less than <MAX NUMBER OF FIELDS> x <MAX FIELD LENGTH>.

Each index requires a contiguous area of RAM that is (4 * (<RECORDS> + 200)) bytes in size. Sorting requires a contiguous area of RAM that is (<ALL SORT KEYS> + (8 * <RECORDS>)) bytes in size.

Databases may be larger than available memory, though operation is much faster if the number of buffers is set large enough so that the whole file is contained in RAM.


@{b}Field Type Ranges@{ub}

  @{u}Field Type                  @{uu}  @{u}               Range               @{uu}
  FLOAT                         -999999999999999 to 999999999999999
  INTEGER                            -2147483648 to 2147483648
  TIME     (hours)                             0 to 2147483647
  DATE     (years)                          0100 to 9999
  CYCLE    (number of values)                  1 to 32
  CYCLE    (value length)                      1 to 30
@endnode
@node History "Program History"

   3.27   April 2001
   - New guide (Andre Eckenrode)
   - New ARexx scripts (localised in french and english)

   3.26   August 2000/March 2001 (no public release)
   - New ARexx interface (all scripts have to be rewritten, see guide).
   - New import routines (new "Fast import" button that does the work
   VERY fast!!!, updating the index when finished)
   - New ARexx functions : ABS, ASC, BLOCKSIZE, CHR, DEF, EXEC, FOR, HELP,
   IF, INIT, INT, LANGUAGE, LASTPOS, LEFT, LOCK, LOWER, MAP, PORTNAME,
   POS, READDEF, READMAP, RESET, REXXPATH, REXXPORT, RIGHT, SCRHEIGHT,
   SCRMODE, SCRWIDTH, SECURITY, SELECT, SELECTSTR, SELPORT, SENDCOMMAND,
   SGN, STR, SUBSTRING, TIMESTRING, TIMEVAL, UNLOCK, UNMAP, UPPER, VAL,
   VERSION, WHILE, WINHEIGHT, WINWIDTH, FILE, FILENAME, FULLNAME, PATH...
   - All other commands are changed to the new format (see docs)
   - calculated fields with errors are in inverse video
   - New "Macros" menu (with 10 programmable entries)
   - Some bugs removed in the index routines

   3.25   July 2000
   - New guides rewritten by Andre Eckenrode (mazeckenrode@yahoo.com)
   - It's now possible to have more than 65535 records in the
   same base (0xFFFFFF is now the maximum)
   - New QUERY CYCLE and QUERY PATH macros
   - Calc TIME field bug corrected (caused the program to crash)
   - Time bug entry corrected
   - DOSEARCH bug corrected (a % was added to the result)
   - Some ARexx macros have been enhanced (DOSEARCH [Selected],
   REQCHOICE, REQFIELD [NoCalc], REQMSG)
   - Direct macro menu added
   - Function keys requester.
   - New CALL macro added (to call a script from a function key).
   - Some tests and error messages added loading a definition file,
   a bug removed loading an old file.
   - GOTO problem solved (hopefully for every locale version ?).
   - Some requester routines rewritten and optimized
   - OPENFILE macro bug corrected
   - CLOSEWIN command bug removed (caused a crash).
   - ARexx script path bug fixed
   - INSREC and UPDREC bug fixes: the view was sometimes updated
   after the update of the display (could lead to a crash).
   - SORT bug fix (memory allocation error, could lead to a crash)
   - Using SHIFT key when clicking on the Insert gadget makes an
   automatic Copy of the current record.
   - Number of max items in a CYCLE field is now 32.
   - STRINGTOCYCLE bug removed (bad returned value in some cases) and
   error message if a CYCLE field expression contains several identical
   values.
   - All views are now tested when you quit to know if they have changed.
   - Message added when searching records from the ARexx macro DOSEARCH.
   - Position of the views correctly saved (not always working if the
   window had been moved but not resized).
   - When altering the file definition, the data is always saved now.
   - and many other improvements and bug corrections...

   3.24   Dec 1999 - June 2000
   - Intermediate release (debugging). Thanks to Andre Eckenrode and
   to Pascal Marcelin for their kind help in debugging and improving
   the program.

   3.23   Nov 1999
   - selecting OK on the view requester without clicking on an entry
   was giving another entry that the selected one, fixed (thanks to
   Andre Eckenrode for the bug report).
   - ability to add records with trailing spaces (hope it gives no
   new bugs...) on Andre Eckenrode request.
   - corrected an enormous bug : monthes october and november were
   inverted... (thanks again to Andre Eckenrode)
   - added 3 new ARexx commands: SELECTREC, REQFIELD and SHOWALL.
   - corrected some gadget problems with Sysihack (MCP), bug report
   by Alexander Doeller (hope it works correctly...)

   3.22   14 Oct 1999
   - added the ability to make the index sorting using the locale
   library (idea from Gudjon Magnussson).
   - the view requester was adding the fields in the wrong order, fixed (bug
   reported by Anders Drejer).
   - date handler corrected, file filter now set correctly while opening
   a base (bug reports by Didier Giron).

   3.21   26 Sep 1999
   - a no-QuickFile-file was not closed when a user tried to open it,
   fixed (Thanks to Alexander Döller for his bug report).

   3.20   24 Aug 1999
   - first version rewritten using SAS-C compiler by me (Roland Florac).
   - localisation
   - use of gtlayout.library
   - some cosmetics changes, some bugs removed (hopefully)...

   3.19.1 11 June 1996
   - Search from ARexx gave a selection with no key fields.
   - Selecting a large number of records can cause a problem if the
     default sort order is used.

   3.19.0 06 June 1996
   - Enhanced Search. Now called Query and includes sort order as well as
